<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls, Gold Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The dollar was down against other most major  
currencies in European trading today. Gold rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0886, up from $1.0806 Friday. The  
dollar was quoted at 121.87 Japanese yen, down from 122.63. In 
midday trading in New York, the euro was quoted at $1.0903 and the 
dollar was quoted at 121.65 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Europe compared with late Friday: 1.4615  
Swiss francs, down from 1.4720; 1.5140 Canadian dollars, down from 
1.5165. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6090, up from $1.6074.  
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar was worth: 1.7966 German marks, down from 1.8099; 
6.0257 French francs, down from 6.0703; 2.0244 Dutch guilders, down 
from 2.0393; 1,778.68 Italian lire, down from 1,791.85. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $289.30 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$288.00 on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Zurich the bid price was $289.00, up from $287.90.  
</P>
<P>
	Gold rose $0.50 in Hong Kong to close at $288.55.  
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.26 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$5.16. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
