<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Mount St. Mary's Faces Spartan Task </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EMMITSBURG, Md. (AP) -- Mount Saint Mary's doesn't have the size,  
speed and talent of most teams in the NCAA tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	When it comes to coaching, however, the Mountaineers have the  
winningest guy in the business. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Phelan, who has won 800 games and owns a .644 career winning  
percentage, will make his second appearance in the tournament 
Friday when he leads 15th-seeded Mount St. Mary's (15-14) against 
second-ranked Michigan State in the Midwest regional. 
</P>
<P>
	Phelan has recorded at least 20 wins in 19 of his 45 seasons at  
the Mount and trails only retired legends Dean Smith (879), Adolph 
Rupp (876) and Clarence ``Big House'' Gaines (828) on the career 
victory list. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet Phelan's gaudy numbers hardly begin to tell the story of a  
devoted coach who has run a spotless program and helped shape the 
lives of hundreds of young men. 
</P>
<P>
	Fred Carter was playing basketball on the playgrounds of  
Philadelphia in the mid-1960s when Phelan got the 20-year-old high 
school dropout to check out the Mount's cozy campus in the hills of 
western Maryland. 
</P>
<P>
	Carter became the first black to enroll in the school, starred  
for four seasons and went on to both play and coach in the NBA. He 
remains close friends with Phelan to this day. 
</P>
<P>
	``He transcends just being a coach. You talk about a father  
image -- my Dad died when I was 16 and coach Phelan was there for 
me. He's always been there for me,'' Carter said. 
</P>
<P>
	These days, Phelan has another project: center Melvin Whitaker,  
who enrolled after spending two years in jail for slashing a 
University of Virginia football player with a box cutter on a 
recruiting visit there. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitaker, like Carter, had all but abandoned hope of a college  
career when Phelan came along and offered him a shot at redemption. 
</P>
<P>
	``How wonderful, coach Phelan's willingness to help people,''  
Carter said, his voice cracking with emotion. 
</P>
<P>
	``Melvin, like Fred, is a guy working on a second chance,''  
Phelan said. ``He really appreciates the opportunity. I think he 
likes not being at a prominent place like Raleigh or Durham.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Same with Phelan, who long ago laid to the rest the notion of  
coaching at a bigger school. Phelan interviewed at the Mount in 
1954, immediately took the job and has since spurned subsequent 
offers from more prominent institutions. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been wonderful to be out of the limelight. Out here in  
the country I can do as I please,'' he said. ``I was a city-slicker 
the first 24 years of my life -- it was great growing up in south 
Philly -- but now I live in a totally different world and I couldn't 
be happier.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Phelan, 69, skillfully avoids talk about retirement, so it seems  
as if his trademark bow-tie will remain a part of Mount games for 
at least another year or two. 
</P>
<P>
	``If my wife had her way I'd be doing it until I was 85, just so  
I'd be out of her way at home,'' he joked. 
</P>
<P>
	``How long can he stay? As long as he feels like it,'' said Jack  
Sullivan, Class of '57 and the school's career scoring leader. ``As 
long as he feels as if he can contribute and give something to the 
kids, he'll be out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The game has changed dramatically since Phelan began drawing up  
plays on the blackboard in the 1950s. So have the athletes. Yet 
Phelan has managed to cope with it all, tweaking his playbook 
through the years while maintaining a solid rapport with players 
young enough to be his grandchildren. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been able to withstand the test of time,'' Carter said.  
``For a guy to coach four decades, almost four generations, it just 
shows how well he's been able to make the adjustment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Phelan's first year, he transformed a 15-11 team into a 23-4  
powerhouse. The rest, as they say, is history. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got off to a good start, and it started a long love affair  
between me and this place,'' he said. ``It's still going on, too.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
