<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.Y. Fans Remember DiMaggio Fondly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- This was Joe DiMaggio's city and his fans -- even  
those who never saw him play -- knew his place in a town where 
baseball has meant so much. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was a legend,'' said Mike DiPalma, a banker from Manhattan,  
making his way through Rockefeller Center. ``It's not every day 
someone like him comes along. It isn't easy to replace a legend.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio died Monday at 84, and on a cold morning word of his  
death spread across the city where he became synonymous with the 
New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, one of New York's most visible Yankee  
fans, called DiMaggio the ``greatest baseball player who 
represented the very best of American sports.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He was the personification of Yankee pride,'' Giuliani said.  
``He led his team to greatness. He set records, which may never be 
broken. And he was always a man of dignity and class. He was also a 
good friend to New York City.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Former Mayor Ed Koch said that although he was never much of a  
baseball fan, DiMaggio was a man worthy of admiration. 
</P>
<P>
	``He represented the best in America,'' Koch said. ``It was his  
character, his generosity, his sensitivity. He was someone who set 
a standard every father would want his children to follow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the Grand Central Terminal, fans remembered DiMaggio not just  
as one of baseball's greatest, but as a symbol of a more innocent 
time in sports. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was what baseball was all about before we got to that  
high-priced stuff,'' said George Ladino, a former Bostonian who now 
lives in London and makes his living from mutual funds. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's one of the greatest players of all time,'' said Doug  
Connor of Irvington, who works in the financial industry. ``It's 
the passing of a person from a time when baseball was the way it 
should be, when there was a higher ethical and moral standard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio died at home of complications from lung surgery. During  
his hospital stay he rallied several times from near death. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very sad, but maybe it's good for him because he was  
really sick.'' said Marty Gray, a Brooklyn resident. 
</P>
<P>
	A man buying tickets at Yankee Stadium said there was no one  
like Joe D. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was the greatest of all time,'' said the man, identifying  
himself only as Richard from Yonkers. ``I saw him play in his last 
year (1951). I thought he was the greatest then and he's still the 
greatest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among the tributes to DiMaggio on Monday was a new life-size  
statue of DiMaggio, complete with wooden bat, that went on display 
at ``Mickey Mantle's'' restaurant in Manhattan. 
</P>
<P>
	American flags were at half-staff all around Yankee Stadium; and  
a ``Farewell to Joe DiMaggio ... Joltin ' Joe -- 1914-1999'' message 
flashed on an electronic billboard advertising Yankee games on the 
Major Deegan Expressway in the Bronx. 
</P>
<P>
	A proposal to rename Manhattan's West Side Highway the ``Joe  
DiMaggio Highway'' was introduced in the state Legislature last 
month and has picked up support in both the state Senate and 
Assembly. 
</P>
<P>
	Author Joe Dorinson, who wrote ``Jackie Robinson: Races, Sports  
and the American Dream,'' said DiMaggio ``truly epitomized the 
`Hemingway Hero.' He confronted adversity with grace under 
pressure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He added: ``In an era when Mussolini was the dominant political  
image, Joe DiMaggio offered the positive counter image in terms of 
Italian heritage. He lifted Italian-Americans to mainstream status. 
Indeed, the reason why so many Italian-Americans from Brooklyn, 
including Giuliani, became Yankee fans was because of Joe 
DiMaggio.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
