<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> More Fighting in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Mortar and small-arms fire broke out  
in Kosovo along the Macedonian border today, and Yugoslavia's 
president shrugged off the threat of NATO airstrikes to restate his 
opposition to foreign troops policing a peace deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Special U.S. envoy Christopher Hill also was encountering  
resistance in trying to persuade Kosovo Liberation Army commanders 
to accept a U.S.-backed peace plan, and U.S. peace broker Richard 
Holbrooke was reported en route to Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	A senior Western diplomat, speaking on condition of anonymity,  
said rebel commanders still had problems accepting the plan, which 
negotiators hope will bring peace to Kosovo after a year of 
fighting with Serbs that has killed at least 2,000 people. 
</P>
<P>
	The diplomat said stumbling blocks included rebel misgivings  
about Russian participation in a NATO-led peacekeeping force and 
the requirement that the guerrillas surrender weapons to the 
peacekeepers. 
</P>
<P>
	The KLA said the fighting started at dawn around Kacanik, near  
the province's border with Macedonia. Observers with the 
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe reported 
hearing mortar and small-arms fire from a distance. 
</P>
<P>
	One of their spokesmen, Alexander Benz, said detonations could  
be heard from four villages that are believed to be rebel 
strongholds. He said the Yugoslav army had prevented the monitors 
from reaching the villages. 
</P>
<P>
	Trying to push the sides toward agreement, German Foreign  
Minister Joschka Fischer arrived in Belgrade, Yugoslavia's capital, 
for talks with Yugoslav officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S.-sponsored proposal offers autonomy but not full  
independence for Kosovo Albanians, which outnumber the Serbs 9-to-1 
in the secessionist-minded province. 
</P>
<P>
	Before meeting Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, Fischer  
said the plan is ``the last chance'' for peace in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	Fischer said Milosevic told him that Holbrooke would be in  
Belgrade by Tuesday. The American troubleshooter is expected to 
deliver a firm message to Milosevic that NATO will strike in case 
he doesn't accept the Kosovo peace plan in full, including the 
deployment of NATO troops to police the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	But, Fischer said, ``We encountered an opinion (in Belgrade)  
that a political agreement is possible without military 
implementation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a fatal mistake'' by Milosevic, he added.  
</P>
<P>
	Milosevic has adamantly rejected foreign troop deployment,  
saying Yugoslavia would consider that an act of aggression. 
Holbrooke's reported arrival indicates Milosevic still stands firm 
in his defiance. 
</P>
<P>
	The two were key players in forging the Bosnia peace deal in  
1995 and an October cease-fire agreement in Kosovo that averted 
imminent NATO airstrikes against Serbian targets. 
</P>
<P>
	Contrary to Clinton administration expectations, the rebels did  
not sign the deal on Sunday, when KLA leaders met with 
representatives of William Walker, the U.S. chief of international 
monitors in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The refusal of the ethnic Albanians to accept the plan was a  
major setback for the United States during last month's talks in 
Rambouillet, France. It also undercut U.S. efforts to threaten 
Milosevic with airstrikes if he did not accept the plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Moderate Kosovo Albanian politicians have said they would sign  
if the rebels are on board. But the rebels have long been wary of 
the deal, because it requires them to disarm and falls short of 
full independence. 
</P>
<P>
	The accord has also been hindered by Albanian demands for a  
referendum on independence after three years, which Western powers 
oppose. 
</P>
<P>
	A second round of Kosovo talks in France are expected to begin  
March 15. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
