<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 15:40:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ireland, Britain Sign Treaties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) -- The British and Irish governments,  
determined to drive forward the Belfast peace accord, signed four 
treaties Monday that foresee an era of unprecedented cooperation. 
</P>
<P>
	``An old quarrel between Britain and Ireland is being put to  
rest,'' said Seamus Mallon, a moderate Catholic politician who is 
helping spearhead the efforts to form a Protestant-Catholic 
government for Northern Ireland. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sinn Fein party leader Gerry Adams warned that ``we are in  
crisis big-time,'' noting that Wednesday's intended deadline to 
form the government will be missed because of Protestant demands 
for Irish Republican Army disarmament. 
</P>
<P>
	After the treaty-signing ceremony in Dublin Castle -- the seat of  
British power in Ireland until the south won independence in 1922 -- 
Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam conceded that the new target 
date for forming a Northern Ireland administration would be Good 
Friday, April 2. 
</P>
<P>
	``This gives the parties the time and space to find a way  
forward,'' Mowlam said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mallon and David Trimble -- head of Northern Ireland's major  
Protestant party, the Ulster Unionists -- already have been 
appointed to the top two posts that would oversee the 
administration. 
</P>
<P>
	But Trimble, the government's would-be leader, is insisting that  
Sinn Fein cannot assume the two posts it is entitled to until the 
outlawed IRA starts to turn over its weaponry to an independent 
commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The peace accord committed Sinn Fein members to use ``whatever  
influence they may have'' to secure the complete disarmament of the 
IRA by May 2000, but did not specify when the process should begin. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's Anglo-Irish treaty signings underscored the reality  
that, while the British and Irish government are mostly meeting 
their commitments under the peace accord, Northern Ireland's 
politicians have failed to deliver on many of theirs. 
</P>
<P>
	The treaties envision four tiers of new institutions that would  
bring together lawmakers from across Britain and Ireland. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of the treaties bind together the two parts of Ireland,  
which the north's Catholic leaders hope will encourage the gradual 
absorption of Northern Ireland -- founded in 1920 as a 
Protestant-majority state -- into the Irish Republic. 
</P>
<P>
	One lays down the rules for twice-yearly summits of senior  
politicians from Dublin and Belfast, while the other sets up six 
cross-border committees to pursue common policy-making throughout 
Ireland on practical matters such as waterways and business 
promotion. 
</P>
<P>
	The other two emphasize the growing bonds between Britain and  
Ireland and, unlike the all-Ireland treaties, can't be directly 
blocked by the stalemate in Belfast. 
</P>
<P>
	One establishes a council that would bring together legislators  
from throughout the United Kingdom and the Irish Republic, although 
the body would have no powers. The other calls for the British and 
Irish governments to strengthen their commitment to close 
cooperation through regular summits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
