<DOCNO> APW19990308.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 03:17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> World Indoors a Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MAEBASHI, Japan (AP) -- Double golds in the men's and women's  
distance events. World records in the relays. A couple of big 
upsets. The year's best marks in a dozen events. 
</P>
<P>
	It's official -- the World Indoor Athletics Championships were a  
success, even though they didn't play so well in the stands, which 
were virtually empty until the final day. 
</P>
<P>
	``These World Championships in Maebashi have been the greatest  
ever, both in terms of technical results and competitive 
performance,'' said Primo Nebiolo, head of the IAAF, track and 
field's world governing body. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, the lack of anything near a full house was so glaring  
it brought an exclamation of surprise from Ethiopia's Haile 
Gebrselassie, who pulled off an unprecedented double gold 
performance in the 3,000- and 1,500-meter races. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't expect it to be like this,'' he said after winning  
the 3,000 on the meet's opening day Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Gebrselassie added the 1,500 title on the closing day Sunday  
before a larger but still far-from-capacity crowd at the 
20,000-seat Green Dome in this central Japan city. 
</P>
<P>
	Not until the final day did the crowd reach even half of total  
capacity. 
</P>
<P>
	But the lack of interest wasn't due to a lack of excellence.  
</P>
<P>
	The women's distance double went to Romania's Gabriela Szabo.  
She and Gebrselassie are only the second and third athletes to win 
two individual gold medals in the same meet at the championships, 
first held in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 800, fans were provided with a pair of stunning upsets.  
</P>
<P>
	Wilson Kipketer, the Danish world record-holder, was upset by  
South Africa's Johan Botha. Three-time champion Maria Mutola of 
Mozambique was overtaken in the homestretch by Ludmila Formanova of 
the Czech Republic. Formanova's time of 1 minute, 56.90 seconds was 
a meet record and the second-fastest ever run indoors. 
</P>
<P>
	And in the sprints, the second-fastest time ever in the 200 was  
clocked by Frankie Fredericks of Namibia, 20.10 seconds. It was the 
first indoor championship for Fredericks, who had won nine Olympic 
or World Championship medals previously, eight of them silver. 
</P>
<P>
	All told, the United States was the only nation with a  
double-digit performance in medals. Americans won 19. But the gold 
race was a four-way tie among the United States, Romania, Germany 
and Britain with had three apiece. 
</P>
<P>
	Both world records came in the final events of the  
championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Milt Campbell, the silver medalist in the 400, anchored the U.S.  
1,600-meter relay to a world record of 3:02.83, smashing the mark 
of 3:03.05 by Germany at the 1991 championships. Andre Morris, 
Dameon Johnson and Deon Minor ran the other legs for the Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's women's 1,600-meter team, consisting of Tatyana  
Chebykina, Svetlana Goncharenko, Olga Kotlyarova and Natalya 
Nazarova, was timed in 3:24.25, breaking the world mark of 3:26.84 
the Russians set at the 1997 championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Maurice Greene, the world record-holder in the men's 60, came  
back from a poor first-round heat on the final day to add the 
indoor title to his 100-meter outdoor crown. He won in 6.42, a 
championship record, leading a 1-2 U.S. sweep, ahead of Tim Harden. 
</P>
<P>
	America's women had a harder time in the sprints.  
</P>
<P>
	Greece's Ekaterini Thanou capped a brilliant series of sprinting  
by winning the women's 60 in 6.96, the world's fastest this year. 
Americans finished 2-3, with 1993 and 1997 champion Gail Devers the 
runner-up at 7.02 and Inger Miller third at 7.06. 
</P>
<P>
	In the field events, Cuba provided the stars.  
</P>
<P>
	Javier Sotomayor, the world indoor and outdoor record-holder in  
the men's high jump, won his fourth indoor title, clearing 7 feet, 
8 3/4 inches, best in the world this year. 
</P>
<P>
	And in the most dramatic individual event of the championships,  
Cuba's Ivan Pedroso won the men's long jump on the final attempt, 
soaring 28-3 1/2, the second longest ever indoors. The title was 
Pedroso's fourth straight at the championships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
