<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Duke No. 1 Seed in East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Sure, they've already got the best coach in the land. And the  
best defense. And the best big man, a shrewd point guard, a couple 
of lights-out shooters and so many McDonald's high school 
All-Americans that a rival coach calls them ``the all-time burger 
team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And now Duke has a short commute, too.  
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, the NCAA selection committe shipped the Blue Devils  
to the East, which begins next week in Charlotte, N.C., a 90-minute 
bus ride from their campus in Durham, and concludes the week after 
that with the regionals at the Meadowlands in New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	Know anything about the recent history of college basketball,  
and this route is practically a guarantee coach Mike Krzyzewski &AMP; 
Co. will be on hand at St. Petersburg, Fla., when the championship 
hardware is being handed out. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1986, coach K has taken Duke to seven Final Fours,  
including all four times the Blue Devils stopped off at the 
Meadowlands. Yet that wasn't what Krzyzewski meant when he went on 
television after the committee finished its handiwork and said, 
``It's all about the journey.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Because in this instance, he wasn't measuring the trip by miles,  
but by expectations. Yours, his and everybody else's. 
</P>
<P>
	Let Duke get tripped up somewhere along the way to what would be  
Krzyzewski's third national championship and he knows that's what 
the rest of us will remember. Not the 32-1 record, the 27 straight 
wins, the perfect ACC season and the conference championship -- 
nearly all of them in walkovers. 
</P>
<P>
	But that's where his coaching genius comes in. By making sure  
the Blue Devils revel in every accomplishment instead of run from 
the pressure they bring, he's made the Blue Devils even hungrier to 
see what lies ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	That doesn't mean they'll get there.  
</P>
<P>
	Duke's first test should come in a projected second-round  
matchup against the College of Charleston. Coach John Kresse has 
the little school from South Carolina on a 25-win run of its own, 
including a win over North Carolina, and he's already wearing a 
smile that should send chills down Krzyzewski's back. 
</P>
<P>
	He popped up on another one of the post-selection shows Sunday  
and, while swearing he wasn't looking past first-round opponent 
Tulsa, Kresse clearly had done some of his homework already. He 
quickly reeled off every thing a team would need to beat Duke, the 
last of which, Kresse said through a widening grin, was ``a couple 
of Hail Marys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He won't be close enough at the end of their matchup, but  
Cincinnati could. The only team to beat Duke this season wants the 
chance to try again. The Bearcats' Melvin Levett did it with a dunk 
last November in the Great Alaska Shootout, and he felt a jolt of 
electricity run through the room when the pairings were announced. 
</P>
<P>
	``The guys started smiling a little bit around the room when we  
saw that potential match,'' he said. ``Of course you want to go out 
and prove to everybody that the first time was for real. If the day 
ever came that we do meet, we'll be ready.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But not ready enough.  
</P>
<P>
	Duke will advance to the Final Four, and whoever comes out of  
the Midwest to meet them won't be fresh enough to keep them out of 
the championship game. Kentucky will be spent getting past Kansas 
and Utah. Michigan State will be worn out by Arizona. The last man 
standing, which will be Kentucky, falls to Duke. 
</P>
<P>
	The South will be less tiring. Maryland will cruise through the  
lower half of the bracket, but run out of steam by the time the 
Terps face Ohio State in the regional. In the West, Connecticut's 
only test will come at the end, when the Huskies face a Stanford 
team they beat by 11 points without their best scorer, Richard 
Hamilton. In this semifinal, the Huskies won't need much from 
Hamilton, either, to set up a Connecticut-Duke final. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Jim Calhoun has been to the Sweet 16 six times, but never  
once to a Final Four. He, too, is a good coach, with the best point 
guard in the country in Khalid El-Amin, a big-time scorer in 
Hamilton, a good big man in Jake Voskuhl, and something to prove. 
</P>
<P>
	And it that doesn't prove enough, there's always the chance that  
the Duke bus will take a wrong turn somewhere on its way to the 
final. It could happen. After all, soon after Duke won the second 
of back-to-back titles in 1992, Brother Ray Page, who taught at St. 
Anthony's High School, revealed that Bobby Hurley, a student of his 
and the point guard on Duke's championship teams, had a terrible 
sense of direction: 
</P>
<P>
	``He once asked me if Beirut was named after that famous  
baseball player who all those home runs.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at jlike@apmail.ap.org. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 12:34:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  DiMaggio Remembered As Shy, Modest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MARTINEZ, Calif. (AP) -- A bouquet of daffodils and carnations  
sat beside the ``Joltin' Joe'' on the waterfront Monday, along with 
a note expressing this fishing town's sadness at losing its most 
famous son. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dear Joe, from dear, loyal and loving fans,'' said the note,  
its ink beginning to smear in a cold rain. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe DiMaggio, who died Monday at 84, was born in Martinez in  
1914. Though he moved away as a small child, he often returned to 
fish with his cousins and later donated the 22-foot speedboat to 
the town. 
</P>
<P>
	He had received the boat on Joe DiMaggio Day on Oct. 1, 1949, in  
front of 69,551 fans at Yankee Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Harriete Langemeier was one of many Martinez residents who  
visited the ``Joltin' Joe'' on Monday to remember DiMaggio. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's tantamount to the country losing the president,''  
Langemeier said. ``He was a hometown hero.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Residents sometimes saw the lanky, white-haired gentleman  
wheeling his shopping cart gently through Longs Drugs, stopping to 
chat with his granddaughter, who worked there. His eyes would focus 
on the floor, avoiding the astonished stares of strangers. 
</P>
<P>
	Or DiMaggio would slip over to Amato's restaurant for a meal.  
He'd sit in the back room, shielded from gawkers and autograph 
hunters. 
</P>
<P>
	He avoided crowds, skipping funerals and showing up unexpectedly  
at the mortuary to pay his last respects. 
</P>
<P>
	``His head was always down, he wouldn't look around. No eye  
contact,'' said Ernie Lasell, who owned a hardware store and used 
to sell DiMaggio his fishing licenses. ``He was just a naturally 
shy guy, very modest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marie Amato Goodman, whose family ran the restaurant that sits  
about 80 yards from dusty two-lane Joe DiMaggio Drive, said he was 
a humble man who ``had the limelight but didn't capture it and go 
with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``When he came into the restaurant, my mother grabbed Joe and  
took him in the back,'' said Goodman, a third cousin of DiMaggio. 
``He was very private, unobtrusive in all situations. I think Joe 
never forgot who he was and where he came from, and the loyalties 
that come with family and friends in a small town.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most Americans born before World War II remember DiMaggio as the  
dashing ``Yankee Clipper,'' the man who had a 56-game hitting 
streak and married Marilyn Monroe. Baby boomers think of DiMaggio 
as the guy hawking Mr. Coffee on TV. 
</P>
<P>
	But neighbors and relatives in Martinez knew DiMaggio as the  
quiet son of a Sicilian fisherman. 
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio was born in Martinez, a middle-class town about 30  
minutes east of San Francisco, on Nov. 25, 1914. On his birth 
certificate, the midwife that delivered DiMaggio listed ``Fishman'' 
as the occupation of his father, Giuseppe DiMaggio. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe DiMaggio was born in a small wood house on Berrellessa  
Street, along the Martinez waterfront. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuseppe and Rosalia Mercurio DiMaggio moved their family to the  
North Beach section of San Francisco when Joe was 1. The area also 
was an Italian enclave in those days. Now it is largely Asian. 
</P>
<P>
	Dante Benedetti played baseball with the DiMaggio boys. The kids  
used to play on a grassy lot next to a creamery when the horses 
were out pulling milkcarts. They used dried horse manure, covered 
with a sack, for bases. 
</P>
<P>
	``You never slid head first into those,'' Benedetti said.  
</P>
<P>
	Benedetti, who owned the New Pisa restaurant in that  
neighborhood, remembers young Joe DiMaggio sitting by himself at 
North Beach Playground, rolling Bull Durham cigarettes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because he was such a good player, he was the only one the  
director let smoke during the games,'' Benedetti said. ``He was a 
shortstop. He used to overthrow first base, he had such a strong 
arm.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There's a fable that DiMaggio avoided following in his father's  
footsteps only because he got seasick. Benedetti laughs at such 
nonsense, pointing out the $25,000 bonus offered by the Yankees was 
reason enough to stay on land. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know you'd get seasick if somebody offered you $500 a  
month,'' he said. ``After Joe signed, all the fishermen down there 
started to buy their kids gloves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two brothers, Dom and Vince, joined Joe in the major leagues.  
But Giuseppe DiMaggio never really understood. He sent his son a 
letter during his first spring training with the Yankees, in 1936. 
</P>
<P>
	``Come home, Joe,'' the letter said. ``The fish are running.  
Give up this game of baseball. It is for loafers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Benedetti remembers DiMaggio being painfully shy throughout his  
playing days. After his hitting streak in 1941, the residents of 
North Beach threw a testimonial dinner for DiMaggio. When called to 
the microphone, he froze and couldn't speak. 
</P>
<P>
	``He walked by himself. He was a loner,'' Benedetti said. ``You  
couldn't get a word out of him. He talked through his bat and his 
ability to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Benedetti, along with the rest of the neighborhood, attended  
DiMaggio's wedding to actress Dorothy Arnold in 1939 at Sts. Peter 
and Paul Church, whose twin steeples tower over North Beach. 
</P>
<P>
	Gloria Alioto also remembers that wedding vividly, though she  
did not attend. She got married the same day at the same church, 
and her wedding was delayed two hours because of the fanfare 
surrounding DiMaggio's marriage. 
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio tried to avoid attention during his visits to Martinez,  
though that was sometimes next to impossible. 
</P>
<P>
	Jack Lopas remembers pressing his face to the window in awe as  
newlyweds DiMaggio and Marilyn Monroe strolled from a limousine 
into a neighbor's house in Martinez. 
</P>
<P>
	``Joe just slipped into town and he slipped out,'' Lopas said.  
``The city wanted to claim him, but he didn't claim it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When town leaders proposed building a Joe DiMaggio Museum, the  
former ballplayer didn't offer help or promise any memorabilia, and 
the idea died. 
</P>
<P>
	Mostly, though, mention of DiMaggio brings back memories of a  
classy guy who shunned the spotlight that his talent attracted. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a prime example of what athletes should be like. He's a  
great tribute to baseball and sports in general,'' said Fred 
Scolari, who grew up near the DiMaggio family in North Beach and 
went on to an NBA career from 1946-55. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just the way he commanded respect because I think he gave  
you respect. He sat in a corner and had his Coca-Colas. He didn't 
seek out anybody.'' 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 12:34:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  DiMaggio Remembered As Shy, Modest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MARTINEZ, Calif. (AP) -- A bouquet of daffodils and carnations  
sat beside the ``Joltin' Joe'' on the waterfront Monday, along with 
a note expressing this fishing town's sadness at losing its most 
famous son. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dear Joe, from dear, loyal and loving fans,'' said the note,  
its ink beginning to smear in a cold rain. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe DiMaggio, who died Monday at 84, was born in Martinez in  
1914. Though he moved away as a small child, he often returned to 
fish with his cousins and later donated the 22-foot speedboat to 
the town. 
</P>
<P>
	He had received the boat on Joe DiMaggio Day on Oct. 1, 1949, in  
front of 69,551 fans at Yankee Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Harriete Langemeier was one of many Martinez residents who  
visited the ``Joltin' Joe'' on Monday to remember DiMaggio. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's tantamount to the country losing the president,''  
Langemeier said. ``He was a hometown hero.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Residents sometimes saw the lanky, white-haired gentleman  
wheeling his shopping cart gently through Longs Drugs, stopping to 
chat with his granddaughter, who worked there. His eyes would focus 
on the floor, avoiding the astonished stares of strangers. 
</P>
<P>
	Or DiMaggio would slip over to Amato's restaurant for a meal.  
He'd sit in the back room, shielded from gawkers and autograph 
hunters. 
</P>
<P>
	He avoided crowds, skipping funerals and showing up unexpectedly  
at the mortuary to pay his last respects. 
</P>
<P>
	``His head was always down, he wouldn't look around. No eye  
contact,'' said Ernie Lasell, who owned a hardware store and used 
to sell DiMaggio his fishing licenses. ``He was just a naturally 
shy guy, very modest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marie Amato Goodman, whose family ran the restaurant that sits  
about 80 yards from dusty two-lane Joe DiMaggio Drive, said he was 
a humble man who ``had the limelight but didn't capture it and go 
with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``When he came into the restaurant, my mother grabbed Joe and  
took him in the back,'' said Goodman, a third cousin of DiMaggio. 
``He was very private, unobtrusive in all situations. I think Joe 
never forgot who he was and where he came from, and the loyalties 
that come with family and friends in a small town.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most Americans born before World War II remember DiMaggio as the  
dashing ``Yankee Clipper,'' the man who had a 56-game hitting 
streak and married Marilyn Monroe. Baby boomers think of DiMaggio 
as the guy hawking Mr. Coffee on TV. 
</P>
<P>
	But neighbors and relatives in Martinez knew DiMaggio as the  
quiet son of a Sicilian fisherman. 
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio was born in Martinez, a middle-class town about 30  
minutes east of San Francisco, on Nov. 25, 1914. On his birth 
certificate, the midwife that delivered DiMaggio listed ``Fishman'' 
as the occupation of his father, Giuseppe DiMaggio. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe DiMaggio was born in a small wood house on Berrellessa  
Street, along the Martinez waterfront. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuseppe and Rosalia Mercurio DiMaggio moved their family to the  
North Beach section of San Francisco when Joe was 1. The area also 
was an Italian enclave in those days. Now it is largely Asian. 
</P>
<P>
	Dante Benedetti played baseball with the DiMaggio boys. The kids  
used to play on a grassy lot next to a creamery when the horses 
were out pulling milkcarts. They used dried horse manure, covered 
with a sack, for bases. 
</P>
<P>
	``You never slid head first into those,'' Benedetti said.  
</P>
<P>
	Benedetti, who owned the New Pisa restaurant in that  
neighborhood, remembers young Joe DiMaggio sitting by himself at 
North Beach Playground, rolling Bull Durham cigarettes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because he was such a good player, he was the only one the  
director let smoke during the games,'' Benedetti said. ``He was a 
shortstop. He used to overthrow first base, he had such a strong 
arm.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There's a fable that DiMaggio avoided following in his father's  
footsteps only because he got seasick. Benedetti laughs at such 
nonsense, pointing out the $25,000 bonus offered by the Yankees was 
reason enough to stay on land. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know you'd get seasick if somebody offered you $500 a  
month,'' he said. ``After Joe signed, all the fishermen down there 
started to buy their kids gloves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two brothers, Dom and Vince, joined Joe in the major leagues.  
But Giuseppe DiMaggio never really understood. He sent his son a 
letter during his first spring training with the Yankees, in 1936. 
</P>
<P>
	``Come home, Joe,'' the letter said. ``The fish are running.  
Give up this game of baseball. It is for loafers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Benedetti remembers DiMaggio being painfully shy throughout his  
playing days. After his hitting streak in 1941, the residents of 
North Beach threw a testimonial dinner for DiMaggio. When called to 
the microphone, he froze and couldn't speak. 
</P>
<P>
	``He walked by himself. He was a loner,'' Benedetti said. ``You  
couldn't get a word out of him. He talked through his bat and his 
ability to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Benedetti, along with the rest of the neighborhood, attended  
DiMaggio's wedding to actress Dorothy Arnold in 1939 at Sts. Peter 
and Paul Church, whose twin steeples tower over North Beach. 
</P>
<P>
	Gloria Alioto also remembers that wedding vividly, though she  
did not attend. She got married the same day at the same church, 
and her wedding was delayed two hours because of the fanfare 
surrounding DiMaggio's marriage. 
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio tried to avoid attention during his visits to Martinez,  
though that was sometimes next to impossible. 
</P>
<P>
	Jack Lopas remembers pressing his face to the window in awe as  
newlyweds DiMaggio and Marilyn Monroe strolled from a limousine 
into a neighbor's house in Martinez. 
</P>
<P>
	``Joe just slipped into town and he slipped out,'' Lopas said.  
``The city wanted to claim him, but he didn't claim it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When town leaders proposed building a Joe DiMaggio Museum, the  
former ballplayer didn't offer help or promise any memorabilia, and 
the idea died. 
</P>
<P>
	Mostly, though, mention of DiMaggio brings back memories of a  
classy guy who shunned the spotlight that his talent attracted. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a prime example of what athletes should be like. He's a  
great tribute to baseball and sports in general,'' said Fred 
Scolari, who grew up near the DiMaggio family in North Beach and 
went on to an NBA career from 1946-55. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just the way he commanded respect because I think he gave  
you respect. He sat in a corner and had his Coca-Colas. He didn't 
seek out anybody.'' 


</P>
</TEXT>
