<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senators Soaring in NHL Homestretch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	No kidding, the Ottawa Senators look like the real deal. So do  
the Mighty Ducks of Anaheim. 
</P>
<P>
	Both are playing some of the best hockey in the league as the  
NHL heads into its final quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a hot team, I'll tell you,'' Toronto goaltender Curtis  
Joseph said after Saturday night's 3-1 loss to the Senators. ``They 
play a very patient game and have a lot of speed. They're mobile 
and consistent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Senators were expected to do well this season after last  
spring's first-round playoff upset of the New Jersey Devils, the 
top team in the Eastern Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	But no one expected them to be the top team in the East at this  
point, and second only to Dallas in the league. Their 36-18-8 
record is already two victories better than their one-season high 
set last season in the sixth year of their existence. 
</P>
<P>
	And they still have 20 games to go.  
</P>
<P>
	Saturday night, the Senators used the same formula as they have  
in a recent 21-5-5 stretch: solid forechecking and solid 
goaltending. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had three 2-on-1s in a short period and I don't think we  
got a shot away on any of them,'' Maple Leafs coach Pat Quinn said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ottawa goaltender Ron Tugnutt lowered his league-leading  
goals-against average to 1.64 by stopping 25 shots against the 
NHL's top offensive team. Tugnutt has lost just twice since Dec. 
26, going 11-2-4 since then. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senators extended their lead to five points over the Maple  
Leafs in the Northeast Division. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ducks have been no less surprising.  
</P>
<P>
	At 30-25-9, they are five games over .500 for the first time in  
their six-year history. Their recent 13-3-0 streak moved them three 
points behind Phoenix for the fourth playoff spot in the West, 
which would give them home-ice advantage in the first round of the 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``The chemistry on this team is really good,'' said Anaheim  
forward Teemu Selanne. ``We have a really good time together. We 
want to work hard and reach some goals, which we set for ourselves. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think our coaching staff has done a great job. They really  
try to push us to reach the next level.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Mighty Ducks continued their surge with a 3-1 victory over  
defending Stanley Cup champion Detroit on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've definitely got more depth (than previous seasons) and  
they're getting a lot of effective play out of other guys (than 
Paul Kariya and Selanne), so it makes a huge difference for them,'' 
said Detroit captain Steve Yzerman. 
</P>
<P>
	The remainder of the playoff contenders in the West: St. Louis,  
Edmonton, Calgary and San Jose. 
</P>
<P>
	In the East, there are five teams vying for the eighth and final  
spot: Boston, New York Rangers, Florida, Montreal, and Washington, 
separated by merely five points. The Rangers beat Boston 3-1 Sunday 
to move into ninth place, two points behind the Bruins. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
