<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baseball Economic Study Group Meets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- With a former Senate Majority Leader and former  
chairman of the Federal Reserve on hand, baseball's newest economic 
study committee began work Monday by discussing the sport's fiscal 
disparity. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's too early in the process to have any idea what direction  
the group is going to go in,'' said Colorado Rockies owner Jerry 
McMorris, a vice chairman of the ``blue ribbon task force.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some owners, particularly those in small markets, are calling  
for owners to again press for a salary cap, a proposal that led to 
a 32-day spring training lockout in 1990 and a 232-day strike in 
1994-95 -- which caused the first cancellation of the World Series 
in 90 years. 
</P>
<P>
	More than a dozen team officials attended Monday's meeting at  
the commissioner's office. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a lot of ideas and thoughts to go through,''  
commissioner Bud Selig said. 
</P>
<P>
	After the 1990 lockout, owners and players jointly appointed an  
economic study committee, which recommended increased revenue 
sharing among the teams but no cap. This time, owners set up the 
group on their own. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Volcker, chairman of the Federal Reserve from August  
1979-August 1987 and an owners' pick for the last study committee, 
is on the panel along with former Sen. George Mitchell, mentioned 
five years ago as a possible candidate for commissioner. 
</P>
<P>
	The other two outside members are Yale president Richard Levin,  
an economics professor who came up with baseball's original salary 
cap proposal during collective bargaining following the 1989 
season, and television commentator George Will, an author of two 
baseball books and a board member of the Baltimore Orioles and the 
San Diego Padres. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the eight postseason teams all were among the 12  
highest payrolls and the teams with the 12 lowest payrolls all 
finished with losing records. This year, the New York Yankees, 
Baltimore Orioles and Los Angeles Dodgers will start the season 
with payrolls approaching $90 million, while others such as 
Montreal will open between $10 million and $15 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball's current collective bargaining agreement probably will  
expire after the 2001 season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure there's all levels of people out there who have all  
different levels of concern,'' McMorris said. ``All we talked about 
today was the levels of disparity.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
