<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Susan McDougal Trial Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Still defiant after 18 months behind  
bars for refusing to answer questions about President Clinton, 
Whitewater figure Susan McDougal went on trial Monday on contempt 
and obstruction charges that could send her back to prison. 
</P>
<P>
	As lawyers and a federal judge questioned potential jurors,  
prosecutors centered on whether any felt animosity toward Kenneth 
Starr. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're hoping the jury will try the case on legal issues, not  
extraneous matters,'' deputy prosecutor W. Hickman Ewing said 
outside court. ``We'll be vigilant to have the case tried on what's 
relevant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eight prospective jurors were dismissed Monday, including one  
who said she couldn't be fair to the defendant. ``If I was in Mrs. 
McDougal's shoes, I would not want me on the jury,'' the woman 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Three women said they could not be fair to Starr, saying he  
should not have expanded his investigation into what came to be 
referred to in jury selection as ``that Washington stuff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In front of the courthouse where she and two co-defendants were  
convicted of fraud in 1996, Mrs. McDougal said she was fearful 
entering what is expected to be a monthlong trial. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it will be an all-out fight and I think it has become  
a personal vendetta,'' she said. ``It's become more than 
political.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Ewing said the only issue was whether Mrs. McDougal refused  
a judge's direct order to testify to the Whitewater grand jury. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal, 44, is charged with two counts of criminal  
contempt and one count of obstruction of justice. If convicted, she 
could serve a sentence determined by U.S. District Judge George 
Howard Jr. and could face a maximum fine of $750,000. 
</P>
<P>
	In September 1996 and April 1998, Mrs. McDougal refused to talk  
to grand jurors investigating Arkansas business deals involving 
President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton. Mrs. McDougal has 
said she refused to answer questions because she believes the 
special prosecutor would twist her words to suit his purposes and 
possibly charge her with perjury if he doesn't get the testimony he 
wants. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard said last week that he would consider allowing evidence  
of ``prosecutorial misconduct or outrageous government conduct,'' 
specifically whether Starr wanted Mrs. McDougal to lie about the 
Clintons. 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing said the government can prove that Mrs. McDougal had  
relevant information about the Clintons. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal, her ex-husband James McDougal and the Clintons  
were business partners in the failed real estate development known 
as Whitewater. McDougal died in prison a year ago Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors were trying to find out whether the president knew  
about a $300,000 government-backed loan made to Mrs. McDougal in 
1986. Prosecutors say the money was misused. The president has said 
he knew nothing about the loan. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, prosecutors asked Mrs. McDougal before the grand jury  
whether the president answered truthfully at her trial, when she 
was convicted along with her ex-husband and with then-Gov. Jim Guy 
Tucker. 
</P>
<P>
	Last fall, a jury acquitted Mrs. McDougal of charges that she  
embezzled $50,000 from conductor Zubin Mehta's wife when Mrs. 
McDougal was her bookkeeper and personal assistant. 
</P>
<P>
	Two jurors from that trial flew to Little Rock from California,  
at the defense team's expense, to provide moral support for Mrs. 
McDougal. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're here because we watched the system fail in Los  
Angeles,'' said one juror, Jill Ford. ``We believe there's 
collusion between the independent counsel and the prosecution 
there.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
