<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US, EU Face Off on Banana Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- An irate European Union appealed today to members  
of the World Trade Organization to denounce U.S. sanctions in the 
trans-Atlantic banana trade row, but found many countries telling 
both trade giants to stop tying up the world agenda. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington insists it has the right to take the step on  
sanctions due to EU reluctance to change import policies that 
American banana sellers say squeeze them out of the European 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	But many trade diplomats complain that the dispute is blocking  
the WTO from doing anything else. Some have expressed fears that 
the maneuvering by the WTO's two most powerful members threatens to 
wreck the world's rules-based trading system. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were a lot of countries which said we need to get this  
dispute settled,'' said WTO spokesman Keith Rockwell during a break 
in a closed-door gathering of the entire WTO membership this 
morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Rockwell quoted Canadian Ambassador John Weekes as saying the  
world was ``mesmerized'' by the dispute even though EU-US trade 
amounts to only 5 percent of the global market. The WTO should be 
focusing on the other 95 percent, Weekes added. 
</P>
<P>
	Roderick Abbott, head of the EU trade delegation in Geneva,  
claimed to have broad support against U.S. actions. ``There is a 
very wide feeling that they have done the wrong thing,'' Abbott 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the request of the EU, the WTO summoned all its 134 member  
countries to the meeting of the general council, its top 
decision-making body, to discuss U.S. sanctions. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States accuses the 15-member European Union of  
failing to carry out WTO rulings against its selective banana 
import policy, which the United States claims favors producers in 
former European colonies at the expense of U.S.-owned producers 
with huge plantations in Central and South America. 
</P>
<P>
	It has asked the WTO to approve Washington's proposal of 100  
percent tariffs on $520 million worth of European goods, which aim 
to equal the lost sales claimed by U.S.-owned banana companies. 
</P>
<P>
	After the WTO last week delayed approving the U.S. tariffs, the  
Clinton administration notified U.S. importers that they must start 
setting aside funds to cover the tariffs pending a WTO decision. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. requirement means that Washington is in effect  
implementing the sanctions without first getting WTO approval, said 
Abbott. 
</P>
<P>
	The tariffs would apply to a wide range of European products  
chosen by the Clinton administration to penalize particularly those 
EU countries that supported the banana policies, including 
handbags, coffee makers and cashmere sweaters. 
</P>
<P>
	Denmark and the Netherlands are excluded, but all other  
countries are affected. Britain, one of the hardest-hit, has been 
particularly outspoken in its protest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
