<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FTC, Intel Reach Proposed Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Intel Corp., the world's largest maker of  
computer chips, appears to have dodged one bullet from federal 
antitrust enforcers, but a larger battle looms. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel and the Federal Trade Commission announced a proposed  
settlement of some of the agency's allegations Monday, on the eve 
of a hearing before an administrative law judge. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither side would comment on details of the settlement, but  
Intel's president and chief executive officer, Craig Barrett, 
called the agreement a ``win-win'' situation. ``We are satisfied 
that the agreement gives us value for our intellectual property 
rights,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	FTC's attorneys ``got the relief that they wanted,'' said agency  
spokeswoman Victoria Streitfeld. At the same time, however, the 
agency said in a statement that ``there are remaining issues under 
investigation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Antitrust experts said the reference was to a much broader  
inquiry into Intel's practices. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was a piece of a larger investigation where the FTC was  
looking into whether Intel used its market position to achieve 
dominance in related areas,'' said Kevin Arquit, a New York 
antitrust lawyer and former director of the FTC's Bureau of 
Competition. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, a settlement means the FTC will get what it wanted -- an  
order prohibiting Intel from withholding information from customers 
because of patent squabbles. The full commission must approve the 
settlement before it becomes official. It is expected to vote 
within two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is one of those unusual situations where both sides can  
declare that they won,'' Arquit said. ``For Intel, the stakes were 
enormous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That is because ``the last thing they need is for a government  
agency to label them a monopolist'' at a time when the company also 
faces private antitrust lawsuits, Arquit said. 
</P>
<P>
	In its June 8 complaint, the FTC argued that Intel holds a  
monopoly in the market for microprocessors, the ``brains'' of 
computers. Intel is the world's largest maker of microprocessors, 
with $26.2 billion in sales last year. About 80 percent of the 
world's computers run on Intel chips. 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC claims Intel used that monopoly power to withhold key  
technical information about future microchips from three companies 
to punish them for refusing to license key patents to Intel without 
charge. 
</P>
<P>
	The three companies were Digital Equipment Corp., Intergraph  
Corp. and Compaq Computer Corp., which now owns Digital. The 
patents were for microprocessors and related technologies made by 
the three firms. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel acknowledges it did most of what the FTC alleged. However,  
the company claimed those actions were not illegal and had not 
``chilled'' innovation. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Meadlock, Intergraph's chief executive officer, said he  
didn't know details of the settlement but hoped it would modify 
Intel's behavior toward competitors. He said the agreement holds no 
bearing on a separate, much broader lawsuit filed by Intergraph 
against Intel alleging antitrust violations and patent 
infringement. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think the concessions of the settlement indicates that at  
least the antitrust issues in our lawsuit had validity,'' he said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
