<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DiMaggio Was the Embodiment of Cool </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	To the generation behind his, the one that never had the chance  
to see him play in person, Joe D. was the embodiment of cool. 
</P>
<P>
	Joseph Paul DiMaggio would never have described himself that  
way, of course. 
</P>
<P>
	Cool sounded too jazzy, not considered enough. It smacks of a  
snap judgment, something DiMaggio spent a lifetime avoiding. And so 
it was fitting somehow that even his passing Monday at age 84 -- in 
his own bed, finally, surrounded by family some two months after 
everyone else had given up hope -- seemed like a measured decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Nothing drove that point home better than something pro golfer  
Ken Venturi recalled about the first time the two of them met. 
``I'll never forget this,'' Venturi said. ``He said if you're good, 
you can always get in. It's knowing when to get out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And now that he is gone, DiMaggio probably would prefer to be  
remembered with words as weighty as his accomplishments. Words like 
elegant, dignified, graceful. Because he was all of those things, 
to be sure, and more. 
</P>
<P>
	But to those who caught their first glimpse of him in a grainy  
newsreel, gliding across center field in Yankee Stadium, or walking 
into some New York place with Marilyn Monroe on his arm, that's how 
he always looked: composed, collected, dispassionate. 
</P>
<P>
	Cool.  
</P>
<P>
	There was something to admire about the way he did everything.  
For 13 seasons, DiMaggio was the best player on the best team in 
the best town in baseball and didn't seem the least bit smug about 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	For a short time, barely nine months in 1954, he even had the  
best dame. He wasn't smug about that, either. And even after he 
lost Monroe, DiMaggio behaved more like a faithful husband than a 
bitter, divorced one. He looked after her as much as he could, and 
for years after she died in August 1962 he made sure there were 
roses at her grave. 
</P>
<P>
	He was Gary Cooper-in-High Noon cool. He was not afraid of a  
fight, but not afraid to walk away from one, either. DiMaggio spent 
what likely would have been the best three seasons of his career 
serving in the military during World War II, but he never used it 
as an excuse for anything. 
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio was certainly a product of his times, but he was more  
than that, too. He was a perfect fit in a succession of athletes 
whose feats touched a uniquely American nerve, whose careers set 
end-to-end track this nation's rise from an emerging power to a 
consuming one. 
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio wasn't a happy accident the way Babe Ruth, his  
predecessor was, a Jazz Age symbol whose grand home runs and even 
grander appetite put baseball on the map. And yet he wasn't bred 
for the national pastime the way Mickey Mantle, his successor, was, 
the product of a father who worked in a coal mine by day and worked 
his son on a diamond each night. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, DiMaggio was shy and slender, the son of an Italian  
immigrant who operated a fishing boat in San Francisco and thought 
baseball was ``a bum's game.'' But that was before Joe became a 
folk hero, and before two more DiMaggio boys, Vince and Dom, found 
more money chasing baseballs over far-flung lawns than pulling the 
catch of the day out of the bay. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, like everybody else who followed Joe D., the old man  
became an admirer, too. DiMaggio announced his arrival in New York 
in May 1936 with two singles and a triple, when baseball was fast 
becoming America's new religion. Five years later, he turned it 
into an obsession. 
</P>
<P>
	In the summer of 1941, DiMaggio got a hit in 56 straight games.  
When it ended -- thanks to two great defensive stops by a Cleveland 
infielder named Ken Keltner -- he simply started another streak. 
</P>
<P>
	And when he finally left, worn out at age 37, DiMaggio did that  
with grace, too. He showed up at Yankee Stadium a handful of times, 
taped a few commercials and spent much of his energy raising money 
for the Joe DiMaggio Children's Hospital in Hollywood, Fla. Besides 
putting his name over the door, the only thing DiMaggio extracted 
for his years of service was a promise that no child would ever be 
turned away. 
</P>
<P>
	All day Monday the television networks showed those grainy film  
clips again and again and it made you realize there was something 
irresistible about watching him play. There was DiMaggio batting 
and fielding and running like baseball was a game set to Sinatra's 
music -- smart, fluid and full of verve. 
</P>
<P>
	And cooler than just about anything you could ever imagine.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at: jlitke@apmail.ap.org. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 15:16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Purdue Leads Final Women's Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Purdue led the final Associated Press women's basketball poll of  
the season on Monday, joined in the top four by the other No. 1 
seeds in the NCAA tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee, seeking its fourth straight national championship,  
held the No. 2 spot, Louisiana Tech was third and Connecticut 
fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	At the bottom, No. 25 Toledo broke into the poll for the first  
time this season and just the third time overall. 
</P>
<P>
	Purdue (28-1), the top seed in the Midwest Regional, received 39  
of 42 first-place votes and 1,047 points from a national media 
panel to finish at No. 1 for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boilermakers defeated both Tennessee and Louisiana Tech this  
season and take a 26-game winning streak into NCAA play. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee (28-2), seeded No. 1 in the East, had two first-place  
votes and 1,009 points, while Louisiana Tech (26-2) had 967 points 
and the remaining first-place vote. Tech is the top seed in the 
West, and Connecticut (27-4) is No. 1 in the Mideast. 
</P>
<P>
	Connecticut jumped two spots in the poll after winning the Big  
East Conference tournament. Old Dominion remained at No. 5, and was 
followed by Texas Tech, Colorado State, Notre Dame and Rutgers. 
Clemson and Duke were tied for 10th. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Tech, which beat Iowa State in the Big 12 tournament  
final, climbed three places. Colorado State dropped from fourth to 
seventh after losing to Southern Methodist in the Western Athletic 
Conference final. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgia moved up two places to 12th, and Virginia Tech was 13th.  
Then it was North Carolina, UCLA, Oregon and UC Santa Barbara, 
followed by Penn State, Iowa State and Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	LSU, Alabama, Tulane, Florida International and Toledo held the  
final five spots. 
</P>
<P>
	Toledo (25-5), the Mid-American Conference tournament champion,  
was given a No. 6 seed in the NCAA tournament and made the Top 25 
for the first time since the 1993-94 season. The Rockets were 
ranked for two weeks in February of that season. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of Toledo's losses were to Notre Dame, Rutgers and Boston  
College, all of whom made the NCAA field. 
</P>
<P>
	Kansas, which lost to Iowa State in the Big 12 semifinals,  
dropped out. The Jayhawks (22-9) had been 25th. 
</P>
<P>
	Purdue became the 11th different team to finish No. 1 since The  
AP poll started in the 1976-77 season. The Boilermakers were No. 1 
for one week early in the season, then returned on Feb. 22 and 
stayed there the final three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifteen teams were ranked every week of the season. They were  
Purdue, Tennessee, Louisiana Tech, Connecticut, Notre Dame, Duke, 
Old Dominion, Rutgers, Georgia, UCLA, Texas Tech, North Carolina, 
Virginia, Iowa State and Alabama. 
</P>
<P>
	Teams from the preseason poll that didn't make the final Top 25  
were Kansas, Florida, George Washington, Arkansas, North Carolina 
State, Vanderbilt, Stanford, Illinois and Arizona. Kansas was the 
highest-ranked of those teams at No. 11. 
</P>
<P>
	Toledo became the 41st school to appear in the poll this season.  
The most in any season was 45 in 1991-92. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
