<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Newspaper Ad Spending Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Spending on newspaper advertisements rose 6.3  
percent to $43.9 billion last year from 1997, in line with previous 
expectations, according the Newspaper Association of America. 
</P>
<P>
	The trade group reported Monday that national advertising  
recorded the fastest growth, rising 7.7 percent to $5.7 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Retail advertising represented the largest portion of the total  
spending, rising 5.7 percent to $20.3 billion. Classified 
advertising rose 6.6 percent to $17.9 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The total increase in ad spending was slightly higher than the  
NAA's earlier projections for a 6 percent gain for 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``This growth continues to reflect the ongoing strength in local  
markets across the country,'' said John Sturm, the NAA's chief 
executive and president. 
</P>
<P>
	Fourth-quarter ad spending rose 4.9 percent to $12.7 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	The NAA, based in Vienna, Va., is a nonprofit organization  
representing the newspaper industry and more than 1,700 newspapers 
in the U.S. and Canada. Most NAA members are daily newspapers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
