<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 15:16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pirates' Guillen To Appeal Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SARASOTA, Fla. (AP) -- Jose Guillen's request for a U.S. visa was  
denied, the Pittsburgh Pirates said Monday, further delaying the 
right fielder's arrival at spring training. 
</P>
<P>
	Guillen, who remained in the Dominican Republic, has missed the  
first 13 days of workouts as U.S. officials question the validity 
of his marriage last fall. The team media guide lists him as being 
single, so federal officials are wondering about the validity of 
the marriage license he gave them. 
</P>
<P>
	Guillen's immigration lawyer, Christina Perez, has filed an  
appeal with the State Department, but the Pirates do not know how 
long that will take. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's only so much the Pirates can do in this matter,''  
assistant general manager John Sirignano said. ``We will offer any 
assistance we can to help get a decision, but it's really out of 
our hands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pirates manager Gene Lamont says Guillen must get to spring  
training soon to have a realistic chance of playing on opening day, 
scheduled for April 5. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to get Jose started at some point,'' Lamont said.  
``The biggest thing will be if he shows up to camp in good shape 
once he gets his problems resolved. He's supposedly been working 
out in the Dominican. Even if he comes here in shape, it's going to 
take at least two weeks of games to get him ready.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Guillen, 22, has been the Pirates' starting right fielder for  
two seasons after making the jump from Class A to the major leagues 
during 1997. He hit .267 last year with 14 homers and 84 RBIs in 
153 games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 04:26:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ron Howard Talks About New Film </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Ron Howard believes television stars will bring  
added authenticity to his upcoming movie ``EdTV.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``So many of the TV people have been in the media glare recently  
and know what it's like to go from anonymity to full exposure in a 
short period of time,'' Howard told TV Guide for its March 13 
edition. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to Matthew McConaughey, who plays a man who suddenly  
becomes famous, the movie features Jenna Elfman, Woody Harrelson, 
Ellen DeGeneres, Martin Landau and Rob Reiner. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most people link celebrity with a kind of recognition that  
leads to happiness. And in some instances it can lead to some 
wonderfully happy moments,'' Howard said. ``But I don't believe 
that it's really the thing that can satisfy somebody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Howard is a television veteran himself, having starred in  
``Happy Days'' and ``The Andy Griffith Show.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 05:31:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cuban Exiles Protest Baseball Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- Major League Baseball's  
announcement to return to Cuba for the first time in 40 years drew 
protest and criticism from Cuban exiles voicing opposition to any 
interaction between the United States and the communist nation. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuban exiles staging a demonstration at a Baltimore Orioles  
exhibition game Sunday said the team's plan to play the Cuban 
National team in Havana on March 28 symbolizes America's growing 
support for Cuban President Fidel Castro and his government. 
</P>
<P>
	``Going to Cuba under the current conditions there is a sign of  
insensitivity and lack of respect for human rights there,'' said 
Huber Matos, a Cuban native who spent 20 years in prison on the 
island for opposing the Castro government. ``It's like taking part 
in the abuses that are going on there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Matos joined more than 70 exiles waving Cuban flags and holding  
protest signs outside the gates of Fort Lauderdale Stadium before 
an exhibition game with the Florida Marlins. They continued their 
protest from the stands inside the ballpark. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to be able to let Oriole players know Cuba's  
reality,'' said Sylvia Iriondo, head of Mothers and Women Against 
Repression in Cuba. ``This is a time to support the Cuban people. 
They don't realize there is a wave a violence aimed at the 
opposition and certain journalists there. This is not a time to 
play ball with Castro.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The protest came on the day the Orioles announced that they  
finalized an agreement to play on the island after two months of 
negotiations between the State Department, Cuban government, 
commissioner's office, the Orioles and the players' association. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles are hoping to host the Cuban national team in a  
return exhibition game at Camden Yards in Baltimore on April 4. 
</P>
<P>
	``The intention of the Baltimore Orioles is not politics,'' said  
John Maroon, spokesman for the team. ``We want to bring two people 
together that have a common passion for baseball. The love of 
baseball there is as strong as it is here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most Cubans living in exile in Miami have long opposed Castro's  
communist government. Many arrived in South Florida after he took 
power some 40 years ago and hope to return once Castro is gone. 
</P>
<P>
	The protesters said they oppose a game played on the island  
while the Castro government continues to jail political opponents. 
They cited the case of four opposition leaders on the island who 
went on trial last week on charges of sedition amid a new crackdown 
on political dissidents. 
</P>
<P>
	The government accused the four dissidents of promoting U.S.  
policies toward Cuba and trying to harm the economy by discouraging 
foreign investment. 
</P>
<P>
	``In Cuba there is a brutal dictatorship that stomps on the  
rights of people,'' Matos said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the words of the protesters were lost on some baseball fans  
at the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we should keep sports out of the political arena,''  
said Kevin Stutzman of Fort Lauderdale. ``I understand what they 
are saying, but I think they are going about it the wrong way. They 
make people angry instead of sympathetic.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
