<DOCNO> APW19990308.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 15:16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Gains on Cuts Talks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Crude oil futures rose Monday on the New York Mercantile  
Exchange, reaching a four-month high amid news that two major 
oil-producing countries are seeking further production cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, grains and soybeans rose sharply, while copper  
plummeted. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude oil rocketed higher after officials from Saudi Arabia and  
Iran said they would work together to win production cuts at the 
March 23 meeting in Vienna of the Organization of Petroleum 
Exporting Countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude prices have fallen about 35 percent in the last 18 months  
as producers fail to make the necessary cutbacks in the face of 
economic troubles around the globe that has sharply curtailed 
demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Saudi Arabia, the world's largest producer, and Iran depend  
largely on revenues from oil exports to fulfill domestic budgetary 
needs. Both countries now are running huge deficits, analysts say. 
</P>
<P>
	The gains were tempered Monday, however, on reports Venezuela,  
another large producer that ships most of its oil to the United 
States, currently has no plans to further reduce its output. 
</P>
<P>
	Light, sweet crude for April delivery rose 33 cents to $13.63 a  
barrel; April heating oil rose 1.03 cents to 35.78 cents a gallon; 
April unleaded gasoline rose 1.21 cents to 42.61 cents a gallon; 
April natural gas rose .6 cent to $1.859 for each 1,000 cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Grain futures moved higher on the Chicago Board of Trade as  
market participants covered their positions in advance of 
Thursday's government crop supply and production updates. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Agriculture Department was expected to provide further  
insight into national spring planting intentions and the current 
state of inventories. 
</P>
<P>
	Grains also were supported as heavy snow fell across the  
Midwest, limiting movement of grains to U.S. terminals. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat also received a boost from talk of dry weather in U.S.  
growing areas and news that Pakistan is in the market for either 
U.S., Australian or Canadian wheat. Soybean futures were sharply 
higher, receiving support from mild export business and a rallying 
soy oil market. 
</P>
<P>
	May wheat rose 2 1/4 cents at $2.70 a bushel; May corn rose 4 3/4  
cents to $2.20 3/4 a bushel; May soybeans rose 6 1/2 cents to $4.71 a 
bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Copper futures retreated on the New York Mercantile Exchange  
amid news of declining demand in Japan, where housing starts, 
construction orders and vehicle sales all were off. Japan is Asia's 
biggest user of the metal. 
</P>
<P>
	The price drops was held in check by word of the biggest decline  
in London Metal Exchange copper stockpiles since mid-June, with 
much of that coming from a purchase of 5,000 tons of the metal out 
of Singapore warehouses. 
</P>
<P>
	Copper prices have been on a downward trend since June 1997,  
when the price hovered around $1.22 a pound. 
</P>
<P>
	May copper was down .75 cent at 62.65 cents per pound.  
</P>
<P>
	Gold futures hit an eight-week high before settling somewhat  
lower on the New York Mercantile Exchange amid talk that higher 
energy prices could lead to inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed up $3.20 at $292.70 an ounce.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
