<DOCNO> APW19990308.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 05:29:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Paris Show Features Young Designers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Young designers carried the opening day Sunday of  
Paris fall-winter 1999-2000 ready-to-wear collections, steeped in 
mohair and enthusiasm and pleasant surprises. 
</P>
<P>
	The first day of showings is often a slow starter, but the air  
crackled with expectation at the Louvre Carrousel theaters, where 
the hefty price tag for space was chopped from $17,500 to $7,000 so 
youth could have its day. 
</P>
<P>
	Nothing looked startling or even futuristic, though there was  
much to please in these younger collections. 
</P>
<P>
	Ralph Kemp, 33, made a hit with his tribal details from Alaska,  
Central or South America, plus a map of the Americas on the runway. 
</P>
<P>
	He used natural fabrics that went from jersey to leather to  
terry cloth, with plenty of mohair, to create looks that were both 
wild and sophisticated. 
</P>
<P>
	His black, white and gray mohair trouser outfits were good city  
gear. Leather was used to pay tribute to North American Indians, 
with gold-painted knees under hitched-up miniskirts. 
</P>
<P>
	His huge fake monkey-fur coats in red or white roused the crowd.  
</P>
<P>
	Kemp, all French despite the Anglo-Saxon-sounding name, studied  
design in Paris and worked with Chantal Thomass, Marithe and 
Francois Girbaud and Kenzo. He now has two Paris boutiques and one 
in Lyon. 
</P>
<P>
	``I especially admired the beaded jewelry and accessories,''  
said artistic designer Jean-Charles de Castelbajac, in the 
audience. 
</P>
<P>
	Christian Le Drezen's show for the millennium was positively  
medieval, shown among puffs of smoke from a steam machine. The 
32-year-old Breton spent years working as a chef. But he gave up 
the sauces for the fabrics in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	After a start in New York with Roth Import, a bridal wear  
boutique, Le Drezen worked with Kenzo and Dior before creating 
jewelry, costumes and launching his own ready-to-wear line in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	His remarkable clothes were long, yet appealingly wearable. The  
long openwork-weave coat in gray mohair with embroidery over wide 
cotton trousers with a fisherman's apron had echoes of his roots in 
France's sea-faring region of Brittany. 
</P>
<P>
	Long, strapless dresses with attractive knit tops, fabulous  
blue-gray ribbed sweaters with big cowl collars paired with checked 
long skirts and trousers had the clearly modern-medieval line. 
</P>
<P>
	Beautiful silk wrap dresses and tunics -- often over figured net  
or tulle skirts -- and terrific mohair coats or crochet dresses 
completed Le Drezen's fashion picture. 
</P>
<P>
	The audience liked it, and Le Drezen's grandmother, Marie Louise  
Boussard, was delighted to kiss her grandson for the cameras. 
</P>
<P>
	Mohair is big with the young designing set, and Stella Cadente  
used plenty of it. She did mohair tunics, fitted jackets and 
fringes for long skirts, dresses and coats. 
</P>
<P>
	Cadente's background is all French, from design school at  
Academie Bercot to stints at Corinne Cobson and Claude Montana. 
</P>
<P>
	Pleated long skirts with mohair short sweaters, slinky mohair  
dresses, and open wide mohair jackets over bare navels and 
low-slung skirts were her forte. 
</P>
<P>
	The dressier clothes for this urban jungle look included  
high-waisted empire line gray or white dresses with sparkly details 
-- demure but sexy. 
</P>
<P>
	Rooster feathers made a few funny bibs and added detail to  
minicoats. 
</P>
<P>
	And off-white Capucin monk-like garments with their hoods and  
crystal beads plunged any thoughts of the millennium back toward 
the medieval line of thinking. 
</P>
<P>
	But where Cadente stumbled was her use of nudity-for-effect.  
Briefs and bared bosoms to show off winter warm jackets in marabout 
or mohair look, these days, like gratuitous attention-grabbing. 
</P>
<P>
	As the week goes on, new stars may shine at several big-name  
houses. Fashion watchers looked forward to Yves Saint Laurent's 
Rive Gauche ready-to-wear Monday, designed for the first time by 
Alber Elbaz instead of the master himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Gilles Dufour, formerly Karl Lagerfeld's assistant at Chanel, is  
showing the Balmain collection. Ronald van der Kemp is showing for 
the first time at Guy Laroche, and the Nina Ricci collection is 
signed by Nathalie Gervais. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 00:24:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McDougal Defiant in Face of Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- In the face of contempt and obstruction  
of justice charges that could send her back to prison, Whitewater 
figure Susan McDougal insists she has no information on President 
Clinton and the first lady's business dealings in Arkansas. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal already has served 18 months on a civil contempt  
citation, and she goes on trial today for refusing to answer 
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's questions about the Clintons. 
</P>
<P>
	If convicted, she could be sent back to prison and fined up to  
$750,000. But her lawyer says Mrs. McDougal won't be broken. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would say that Susan's resolve is as strong as it's always  
been,'' said Mark Geragos. ``She understands the consequences.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The charges against Mrs. McDougal, 44, relate to the Whitewater  
probe. 
</P>
<P>
	Grand jurors were investigating whether Mrs. McDougal had  
improper financial dealings with the Clintons when the president 
was governor of Arkansas. McDougal and the Clintons were business 
partners in the failed real estate development known as Whitewater. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal has said she refused to answer questions because  
she believes Starr would twist her words to suit his purposes and 
may charge her with perjury if he doesn't get the testimony he 
wants. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge George Howard Jr. said last week that he  
would consider allowing evidence of ``prosecutorial misconduct or 
outrageous government conduct,'' specifically whether Starr wanted 
Mrs. McDougal to lie about the Clintons. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy Independent Counsel Hickman Ewing Jr. was unfazed.  
</P>
<P>
	``We know in any high profile case, it is a normal thing where  
the prosecutor is attacked,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors will introduce evidence that Mrs. McDougal had  
relevant information on the Clintons, Ewing said. According to the 
indictment, prosecutors want to know: 
</P>
<P>
	--Whether Clinton was aware of a $300,000 loan to Mrs. McDougal  
from David Hale, who pleaded guilty to mail fraud and conspiracy. 
Hale said Clinton pressured him to make such a loan in 1986. The 
government claims Mrs. McDougal used the money for purposes other 
than what it was intended for. 
</P>
<P>
	--Whether Clinton knew about Lorance Heights, an 800-acre tract  
south of Little Rock that the Clintons' and the McDougals' 
Whitewater Development Corp. purchased in 1986. Prosecutors say the 
company used money from the $300,000 loan to secure the land. The 
Clintons have said James McDougal, Mrs. McDougal's former husband, 
never told them about Lorance Heights or the loan. 
</P>
<P>
	--Whether Clinton testified truthfully during the 1996 trial of  
Mrs. McDougal, her late husband and then-Gov. Jim Guy Tucker. 
</P>
<P>
	--Why the words ``Payoff Clinton'' were written in the notation  
section of a $5,081.82 check drawn on a McDougal account and 
payable to Madison Guaranty, which the McDougals owned. 
</P>
<P>
	Jury selection in Mrs. McDougal's contempt trial was expected to  
continue through most of the week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 05:29:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
