<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US: New IMF Deal Could Save Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said a new  
economic agreement between the International Monetary Fund and 
Brazil could preserve the financial stability of Latin America's 
largest economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin said Brazil also is working with commercial banks to  
re-establish credit lines, and the United States is prepared to 
lend a financial hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``Substantial participation by Brazil's private sector creditors  
is important to Brazil's economic program,'' Rubin said. ``In this 
context, we are prepared to join with the IMF and other countries 
to make available substantial additional financing from the 
international support program announced last year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil is expected to secure a second $9 billion installment on  
a $41.5 billion international rescue package assembled by the IMF 
last November. The collapse in January of the real, Brazil's 
currency, meant the package had to be re-negotiated. Tentative 
agreement on a new accord was reached Friday after almost nonstop 
negotiations with the IMF since mid-January. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin said Brazil's ``success in preserving stability and laying  
the foundation for growth is of critical importance to the United 
States, other regional economies and the international community.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The head of the International Monetary Fund, Michel Camdessus,  
urged the IMF's executive board to approve Brazil's new 
inflation-control strategy, which would clear the way for the $9 
billion payment. 
</P>
<P>
	Camdessus did not say how long the approval process would take,  
but most forecasts have indicated Brazil would get the money by 
April. 
</P>
<P>
	World Bank President James Wolfensohn also praised the  
IMF-Brazil accord as ``a strong reaffirmation of Brazil's economic 
recovery program.'' The bank is contributing $4.5 billion to the 
rescue package, and $1 billion already has been paid. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazilian President Fernando Henrique Cardoso said the IMF deal  
``is an important step for Brazil to restore economic growth... 
jump start exports and strengthen our currency.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the plan agreed with the IMF, Brazil's central bank has  
pledged to begin setting inflation targets and to bring down 
interest rates, currently at 45 percent, as pressure eases on 
prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The talks with the IMF began after the Brazilians abandoned  
their strategy of tying the value of the real to the dollar. Once 
the real's float began, the currency lost 41 percent of its value 
against the dollar, and import prices soared and raised the risk of 
runaway inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Camdessus said the ``key elements of the new program are a  
strengthened fiscal adjustment, and, in the light of the floating 
exchange rate, the adoption of a new nominal anchor for monetary 
policy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The combination of increasing tax revenues and a firm monetary  
policy are expected ``to contain the impact of the depreciation of 
the real on prices in the first half of 1999 and to facilitate a 
decline in the annualized monthly rate of inflation to single 
digits by the end of the year,'' Camdessus said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Brazilians agreed to aim for a 7.5 percent annualized  
inflation rate by the end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 07:34:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Higher; Dow Up 6 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were firmer at 10 a.m. after a mixed  
opening, in an early indication that Friday's climb to all-time 
highs isn't over yet. 
</P>
<P>
	At 10 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 6.52 at 9,742.60. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the Dow added 268.68 to close at a record 9,736.08,  
helped by strong gains in the bond market that continued this 
morning. The 30-year Treasury bond was up 11/32 point. Its yield, 
which moves opposite the price, stood at 5.57 percent, down from 
5.60 percent late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were higher as well, with the Nasdaq  
composite up a strong 28.53 at 2,365.64, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 
500 index up 2.54 at 1,278.01. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the gains in the indexes, declining issues outnumbered  
advancers by 1,154 to 1,080 on the New York Stock Exchange, where 
volume came to 86.42 million shares. 
</P>
<P>
	The market was also helped by some takeover news. Belgian-Dutch  
financial services group Fortis agreed to pay $2.8 billion for 
American Bankers Insurance Group Inc. Fortis will pay $55 a share, 
or $2.6 billion in cash, for the Miami-based insurer, and assume 
about $200 million in debt. ABI's shares were up 5 7/16 at 51 
13/16. 
</P>
<P>
	In other merger news, Allied Waste Industries Inc. is expected  
to announce today a $7.3 billion cash bid, or $45 a share, for 
larger rival Browning-Ferris Industries Inc. Allied Waste's bid 
would be 30 percent premium over Friday's closing stock price. 
Browning Ferris was up 5 at 39 3/4, while Allied Waste's shares were 
up 2 1/4 at 17 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.77 percent. In  
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.63 percent, 
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.33 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 
0.10 percent. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
