<DOCNO> APW19990308.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 19:31:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Boulding Leads Iditarod </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RAINY PASS, Alaska (AP) -- Veteran musher Charlie Boulding led  
Monday's long climb into the Alaska Range on the second day of the 
Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race. 
</P>
<P>
	Boulding, who finished third in the 1998 Iditarod, arrived at  
the Rainy Pass checkpoint at 1:45 p.m. under sunny skies, light 
winds and temperatures hovering near zero. 
</P>
<P>
	A sizable crowd of eager race fans crowded around to watch the  
bushy-bearded musher lay out straw for his 16 dogs to rest on the 
frozen-over surface of Puntilla Lake. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wish someone else would get here,'' said Boulding, who lives  
near the Interior village of Manley. ``I don't like all of the 
attention.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As he boiled beef and sausage for his team, Boulding shook his  
head about the rough trail conditions encountered in the first 175 
miles of the 1,100-mile race from Anchorage to Nome. 
</P>
<P>
	``Terrible,'' he said. ``It's full of big holes, 6-foot-deep  
holes. You dive in and dive back out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Race officials had warned the Iditarod's 56 mushers beforehand  
that the front end of the trail -- up to Rainy Pass -- was in bad 
shape. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitch Seavey of Sterling was second into the checkpoint at 2:26  
p.m., followed three minutes later by 1995 champion Doug Swingley 
of Lincoln, Mont. Norwegian Harald Tunheim arrived at 3:25 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	Swingley agreed the trail conditions were difficult, but ``I  
expected it to be worse, so it was kind of a pleasant surprise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As he stripped felt booties off the dogs' feet, he said he'll  
continue on Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll stay here six hours and then head out,'' Swingley said.  
</P>
<P>
	After the Rainy Pass checkpoint, the trail climbs to the actual  
pass through North America's highest mountain range, and then it 
drops precipitously through the Dalzell Gorge into Interior Alaska. 
Swingley and other lead mushers will descend through the steep, 
treacherous gorge after nightfall. 
</P>
<P>
	Three-time champion Martin Buser of Big Lake held a narrow lead  
early Monday as front-runners headed into the Alaska Range. 
</P>
<P>
	Buser left the Finger Lake checkpoint at 8:58 a.m., but he  
pulled his team over alongside the trail to rest short of Rainy 
Pass. Several other mushers did the same thing along the 30-mile 
run from Finger Lake to Rainy Pass, which passes through rolling 
hills, dense spruce forests and over frozen rivers. 
</P>
<P>
	Three-time champion Jeff King of Denali Park was nearly a  
half-hour behind Buser out of Finger Lake, followed in short order 
by John Barron of Montana Creek, Linwood Fiedler of Willow, Ramey 
Smyth of Big Lake, Boulding and Sven Engholm of Norway. 
</P>
<P>
	By early afternoon, 44 mushers had passed through the Finger  
Lake checkpoint. The remaining seven competitors had reached the 
checkpoint at Skwentna, 100 miles into the race. 
</P>
<P>
	The mushers are competing for a share of the $450,000 purse. The  
winner will collect $54,000. Prize money is paid to the first 20 
finishers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Iditarod, named after an gold-mining ghost town,  
commemorates the effort of mushers in relaying diphtheria serum to 
Nome during a 1925 epidemic. The race began in 1973, and is run 
along historic trails traveled by gold prospectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 19:31:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Boulding Leads Iditarod </HEADLINE>
