<DOCNO> APW19990308.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 16:42:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Can Anyone Beat Duke? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DURHAM, N.C. (AP) -- No. 1 Duke is so confident it's not even  
worried about overconfidence. 
</P>
<P>
	And that means the Blue Devils can enjoy the NCAA tournament,  
Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski said as he prepared his top-seeded team 
to play Florida A&AMP;M in an East Regional first-round game in 
Charlotte. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've always said we're really good. It's not a matter of  
arrogance, it's a matter of us talking to ourselves,'' Krzyzewski 
said. ``As a result we've learned to enjoy it and anticipate other 
things. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anticipation is a lot better than fear. If you are anxious to  
play and a little bit nervous about that, that's better than being 
nervous about being afraid to lose. That's what we've tried to 
develop. Believe me, we'll be ready to play on Friday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Few will argue that. Playing hard has been a trademark of this  
Duke team, which has amassed a 32-1 record. The Blue Devils have 
won 27 straight, including eight of the last nine by 20 or more 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke is favored to win the NCAA title, and Krzyzewski is a major  
reason. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you are leading a group and you feel the group can do some  
great things then you have to talk to that group about doing those 
great things,'' said Krzyzewski, whose 43-12 NCAA tournament mark 
is the best among active coaches. ``They have to see you be excited 
about it, so we've tried to do that all year long, instead of 
saying, `I'm not sure if we can do this.''' 
</P>
<P>
	While Duke looks unbeatable at this point, Krzyzewski is smart  
enough to know otherwise. He points to his NCAA runner-up team of 
1985-86 that finished 37-3. Its first-round victory was by just 
seven points over lightly regarded Mississippi Valley State. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can be beaten by anybody. I truly believe that because if  
I'm the other guy coaching the other team I believe I'm going to 
beat Duke,'' he said. ``If you respect the other guy and his team, 
I don't see how you overlook anybody. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think sometimes in sports we condone overlooking. I don't  
think it's acceptable. I know when I go in for my hip operation I 
hope that's not a day (the doctor) overlooks me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Krzyzewski will undergo hip replacement surgery after the Final  
Four. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rattlers (12-18) lost their first 10 games this season. In  
contrast, Duke has lost a combined 14 games in the last three 
season playing in the rugged Atlantic Coast Conference. But Duke's 
players seem to be following Krzyzewski's lead of cautious 
optimism. 
</P>
<P>
	Junior forward Chris Carrawell was asked what could trip Duke  
up, if anything. 
</P>
<P>
	``Us not being ready to play,'' he shot back. ``If it was an NBA  
championship series -- four-of-seven games -- nobody in the country 
could beat us. But it's not, it's one game and you are out. We know 
that. If we don't come out and play good for a half that could be 
the half where we lose it. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we come out and play hard against Florida A&AMP;M that will  
prepare us for the next game. We'll probably win, but hey, it's all 
about improving each game. We are going to try to blitz them, 
that's my attitude -- let's go out there and send a message, send a 
statement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Star center Elton Brand shrugged when informed the Blue Devils  
were a whopping 45-point favorite over Florida A&AMP;M. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's just some respect that we earned playing against some  
of the better teams and beating them by 25 or 30,'' Brand said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
