<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gardens Offer a Respite at Jail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Ugliness is everywhere on Rikers Island.  
</P>
<P>
	Loops of razor wire sit atop miles of fences, inmates in drab  
green jumpsuits walk through long, windowless corridors, and jets 
from nearby LaGuardia Airport roar overhead. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of wrecked, angry lives are locked behind the bars and  
metal detectors at Rikers, one of the nation's largest jail 
complexes. But beauty has found an unlikely home in this lonely 
landscape. 
</P>
<P>
	On a 1 1/2-acre patch of land behind the Rose M. Singer jail for  
women, yellow buds bloom in a small winter garden, thanks to an 
early thaw. And come summer, the air around one carefully tended 
flower bed will be thick with butterflies. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the Greenhouse Project, an island of calm in a sea of  
fear and frustration. Run and funded by the Horticultural Society 
of New York, the project gives inmates a refuge from pressures of 
prison life and a chance to replace some of the gray with a bit of 
green. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a connection with nature in a place where nature isn't  
supposed to exist,'' said James Jiler, who runs the project. 
``(Participants) get out of their cells ... they don't really feel 
like they're penned in with thousands of other bodies. There's a 
sense of freedom, even within the enclosure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The project began in 1986 as a gardening program for teen-age  
inmates at the prison, which sits in the East River and is 
reachable only via a 4,200-foot bridge from Queens. It was dropped 
in a city budget cut in 1993 but was revived by the Horticultural 
Society with private funds four years later, Jiler said. Since 
then, about 265 prisoners have participated. 
</P>
<P>
	As rain pounded down one recent afternoon, several inmates at  
the modest greenhouse tended to grape vines and prepared peat moss 
for seedlings. Others flipped carefully through gardening books to 
identify unfamiliar plants. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside, lavender, mint and lemon balm grow in a mini-herb  
garden. Brick walkways wind through shrubbery, and hand-laid stone 
borders protect roses and hydrangeas. 
</P>
<P>
	Inmates have planted one garden solely to attract birds and  
butterflies and are planning a Japanese-style meditation pond. 
</P>
<P>
	Only prisoners selected for good behavior and jailed for  
nonviolent crimes can join the Greenhouse Project, and roughly two 
dozen men and women are enrolled at any given time. They come and 
go often, since most Rikers inmates are serving sentences of less 
than a year or are awaiting trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Jiler tries to teach inmates discipline and organizational  
skills that will be useful in jobs on the outside, even if they 
don't blossom into horticulturists. 
</P>
<P>
	``It changed my life,'' said Elizabeth Lynch, 49, who was  
released from Rikers last summer after serving an eight-month 
sentence for selling drugs. ``It finally gave me something to focus 
on, that I wanted to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lynch, who spoke by phone from her Bronx home, worked  
sporadically as a secretary during a 30-year struggle with heroin 
addiction but now hopes to enroll in a professional horticulture 
training program at the New York Botanical Garden. 
</P>
<P>
	Several other Greenhouse participants have gone on to work with  
plants, Jiler said. Just as important, he said, is the ease inmates 
feel inside the greenhouse and the sense of purpose their work 
there gives them. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes you feel like you're more free,'' said inmate Edwin  
Ortiz, a 21-year-old from the Bronx. ``You can't be upset when you 
come in here. It's practically impossible. ... You can't help but 
to smile.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
