<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Joe DiMaggio Is Dead  
</P>
<P>
	HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) -- Joe DiMaggio was remembered today by  
President Clinton as ``the very symbol of American grace, power and 
skill.'' The New York Yankees Hall of Famer died today at his home. 
He was 84. DiMaggio had lung cancer surgery last October. 
Thereafter, he suffered several lung infections and fell into a 
coma for a while. Flags at Yankee Stadium and the Hall of Fame in 
Cooperstown, N.Y., were lowered to half staff. His 56-game hitting 
streak in 1941 remains as one of greatest records in sports. A 
funeral will be held Thursday in his native northern California. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Visits Central America  
</P>
<P>
	MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) -- President Clinton has begun a tour of  
the Central American sites devastated by Hurricane Mitch, offering 
U.S. help with reconstruction. Clinton four-day, four nation 
mission started in Nicaragua and he will go to El Salvador next. He 
has turned down pleas for an extension of the halt in deportations 
of illegal immigrants that was instituted after last fall's storm. 
The stay in deportations expires today. Salvadoran President 
Armando Calderon Sol has said that to have the immigrants return 
now ``would cause us tragic problems of stability.'' 

</P>
<P>
	New Fighting in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Mortar and small-arms fire broke out  
in Kosovo along the Macedonian border today, and Yugoslavia's 
president shrugged off the threat of NATO airstrikes to restate his 
opposition to foreign troops policing a peace deal. A U.S. envoy 
also was encountering resistance in trying to persuade Kosovo 
Liberation Army commanders to accept a U.S.-backed peace plan. One 
diplomat said rebel commanders still had problems accepting the 
plan, with stumbling blocks including rebel misgivings about 
Russian participation in a NATO-led peacekeeping force and the 
requirement that the guerrillas surrender weapons to the 
peacekeepers. 

</P>
<P>
	Colombia Probes American Deaths  
</P>
<P>
	SAN VICENTE DEL CAGUAN, Colombia (AP) -- Colombia's top rebel  
group will investigate whether its guerrillas killed three 
Americans last week and will punish anyone found responsible, 
according to a senior commander. However, Raul Reyes, a member of 
the seven-man ruling junta of the Revolutionary Armed Forces of 
Colombia, said that up to now he saw no signs of any rebel role. 
The three Americans were kidnapped Feb. 25 while on a mission to 
help an Indian group, the U'wa, organize schools on its reservation 
on the Colombian side. 

</P>
<P>
	McDougal Defiant on Trial  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Whitewater figure Susan McDougal went  
back to court today to face charges of contempt and obstruction of 
justice that could send her back to prison. She is on trial for 
refusing to answer Independent Counsel Ken Starr's questions about 
President and Hillary Clinton. McDougal insists she has no 
information on their dealings in the failed Arkansas real estate 
development known as Whitewater. But prosecutors say they will 
introduce evidence that McDougal had relevant information on the 
Clintons. McDougal already has served 18 months on a civil contempt 
citation. 

</P>
<P>
	Man Shoots, Kills Dad at Hospital  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A man whose parents brought him to a  
hospital for treatment of emotional problems fatally shot his 
father outside the emergency room and wounded a janitor, police 
said. Larry Bradford was arrested following the shooting yesterday 
at the University of California, San Francisco Mount Zion Medical 
Center, police said. Police refused to discuss a motive. The 
janitor is in stable condition with a leg wound. 

</P>
<P>
	Sweepstakes Hearing Held  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Senate subcommittee is considering cracking  
down on mail marketing sweepstakes that say things like ``You may 
be a winner!'' Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine, says the sweeps are 
deceptive and prey on senior citizens, often using misleading 
language, trusted spokesmen and government look-a-like mailings. 
She has sponsored legislation that would impose the first national 
regulation of sweepstakes mailings. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Is Off 5.14  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks were lower but trimming their  
losses in late afternoon, while the Nasdaq composite index was 
sharply higher as the technology sector came surging back. Just 
before the close, the Dow Jones industrials were at 9,730.94, down 
5.14. On the NYSE, losers led gainers 1,636-1,344. The Nasdaq was 
at 2,396.46, up 59.35. 

</P>
<P>
	McGwire Hits Second HR in Two Days  
</P>
<P>
	JUPITER, Fla. (AP) -- Mark McGwire of the St. Louis Cardinals  
today hit his second home run in three spring at-bats, a 
fourth-inning drive to left field off the Houston Astros' Jose 
Lima. Lima gave up one home run last season to McGwire, No. 32, on 
June 17 at Houston. McGwire belted a record 70 homers in 1998. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  
</P>
</TEXT>
