<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schott Foe Carl A. Kroch Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Carl A. Kroch, who owned a small share of the  
Cincinnati Reds and earned the nickname ``Baron of Books'' as head 
of the Kroch's &AMP; Brentano's bookstore chain, has died. He was 84. 
</P>
<P>
	Kroch died Saturday.  
</P>
<P>
	Kroch owned one share of the Reds and was an outspoken opponent  
of controlling partner Marge Schott, who has agreed to sell control 
of the team. The Reds' limited partners met with Schott on Monday 
to discuss her proposed sale. 
</P>
<P>
	The limited partners have the right to match the $65 million  
offer and keep the Reds under local control. Kroch's death adds 
another uncertainty to the process, which is expected to take 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the past decade, Kroch complained that Schott had failed to  
inform the limited partners about her decisions as the Reds' 
president. He and other limited partners sued and won access to 
team financial records in a settlement with Schott. 
</P>
<P>
	When Schott was suspended for inflammatory remarks in 1993,  
Kroch thought she should have been stripped of her ownership. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always thought major league baseball had no guts and now I'm  
convinced,'' Kroch said at the time. ``They didn't even slap her on 
the wrist.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He declined comment recently on Schott's preliminary agreement  
to sell her controlling shares in the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Kroch's father, an Austrian immigrant named Adolph Kroch, set up  
his first shop in 1907 in Chicago as a German-language book store. 
After merging with the Brentano's bookstore in Chicago, the chain 
eventually grew to 19 stores in the Chicago area. 
</P>
<P>
	Kroch started several trends in bookselling, including opening  
outlets in suburban malls and returning unsold books to publishers 
for credit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 18:12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Author Munro Wins Critics' Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Alice Munro, regarded by many as one of the  
world's greatest short story writers, won this year's fiction prize 
from the National Book Critics Circle. She was cited Monday night 
for the collection ``The Love of a Good Woman.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sorry I'm not able to be here .... being relatively  
isolated in the snowy mountains of British Columbia,'' the Canadian 
writer said in a statement read by her editor, Ann Close. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had reason for many years to be grateful to you, the  
American critic. ... It is this attention of yours that has helped 
me to flourish for the past couple of decades, as an unapologetic 
writer of short fiction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Short story writers rarely get the sales or the acclaim of  
novelists, but Munro has long been admired as a master of narrative 
and psychology. She has often been compared to Anton Chekhov and 
among living short story writers perhaps only William Trevor is 
thought of so highly. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just adore her work,'' said fellow nominee and short story  
writer Lorrie Moore, whom Munro praised in her remarks. ``It's the 
subtle way she has of talking about the entirety of a life and the 
strange moments a life suddenly pivots upon. And as a person 
documenting and registering the lives of woman especially, she's 
just a genius.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The three other fiction finalists were novelists: Michael  
Cunningham, David Gates and Lynne Tillman. Among the non-nominees 
were Tom Wolfe, whose ``A Man in Full'' was the most talked about 
novel of last year, and Alice McDermott, winner of the National 
Book Award. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the second year the NBCC has made non-U.S. citizens  
eligible for awards and the second year a foreigner has received 
the fiction prize. In 1998, the winner was British author Penelope 
Fitzgerald. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason to make this award eligible for non-Americans is to  
include writers like Alice Munro,'' Moore said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Monday night, Philip Gourevitch won the general nonfiction  
prize for ``We Wish to Inform You That Tomorrow We Will Be Killed 
With Our Families: Stories From Rwanda.'' The winner for 
biography/autobiography was Sylvia Nasar for ``A Beautiful Mind,'' 
her biography of John Forbes Nash, Jr., a Nobel Prize-winning 
economist and a diagnosed schizophrenic. 
</P>
<P>
	Village Voice writer Gary Giddins won the criticism prize for  
``Visions of Jazz: The First Century.'' The poetry award went to 
Marie Ponsot for ``The Bird Catcher.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The National Book Critics Circle, founded in 1974, is a  
not-for-profit organization of book editors and critics with some 
400 members nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	There are no cash prizes for the NBCC awards.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
