<DOCNO> APW19990308.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 17:24:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mediterranean Forces at Low Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NAPLES, Italy (AP) -- Stretched from Iraq to the Balkans, the  
U.S. military based in Europe has lost strength in key areas since 
the Gulf War and could have trouble in another conflict of that 
scale, leaders in the armed forces said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Depleted forces include the Navy's 6th Fleet, which in coming  
weeks stands to have only seven combat vessels on duty in the 
Mediterranean -- a never-before-seen low, Vice Adm. Daniel J. Murphy 
Jr. told Congress' visiting Subcommittee on Military Readiness. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've hit free-fall,'' Murphy testified at the 6th Fleet's  
base in the southern Italian city of Naples. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're trying to maintain a superpower spread around the globe  
and it just doesn't work,'' he said. ``There simply isn't enough 
money to do what we're being asked to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Commanders of Navy, Army and Marine forces in Europe complained  
chiefly of dwindling ranks. Attracting and keeping good servicemen 
and women is getting tougher, given employment competition from a 
healthy economy at home and the strains of frequent deployments, 
from Iraq to Bosnia and stand-by for intervention in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Aging equipment and overworked people make for a far different  
military than the one that beat Iraqi President Saddam Hussein in 
the 1990-91 Gulf War, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Army, worldwide strength is down from a Gulf War figure  
of 535,000 to 480,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The global strength of the Navy was down from as many as 550  
vessels to no more than about 325, the Navy said, in large part 
because there were not enough people to run the ships. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with fewer ships, the USS Dwight D. Eisenhower recently  
started a 6-month deployment 464 people short of its 2,963 
authorized billets, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Enterprise battle group deploys to the Persian Gulf next  
week, leaving only two submarines and five other vessels to carry 
out the 6th Fleet's duties in the Mediterranean. 
</P>
<P>
	With few ships and planes, Tomahawk missiles will have to stand  
in, Murphy said. In another sign of the strain on the military's 
resources, however, even stocks of Tomahawks are running short, the 
Navy said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I see such a serious problem that I don't even know where to  
begin,'' said visiting committee member Rep. Solomon P. Ortiz, a 
Democrat from Texas. ``Aren't we inviting disaster?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Peacekeeping work in Bosnia and the other, frequent deployments  
have made for some valuable on-the-ground, in-the-air training, 
officers testified. Large-scale combat training has suffered, 
however. 
</P>
<P>
	``There haven't been the kind of high-intensity conflicts''  
since Desert Storm, said Brig. Gen. John T.D. Casey of the 7th Army 
Training Command in Germany. ``If we commit these forces that are 
not as well-trained, the casualties are going to be significant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Congress is considering pay raises for the armed forces. Better  
pay and better benefits and services would help with recruitment 
and retention, the generals said. 
</P>
<P>
	Updated equipment -- replacing airplanes and computers whose  
makes are years older than the men and women using them -- would 
also help, as would careful consideration of the lengths of the 
increasing deployments, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
