<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> William Wrigley Dead at 66 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- William Wrigley, the third generation to head the  
Wrigley chewing gum company founded by his grandfather, died of 
complications associated by pneumonia. He was 66. 
</P>
<P>
	Wrigley died Monday at a Chicago hospital, said Christopher  
Perille, a spokesman for Wm. Wrigley Jr. Co. 
</P>
<P>
	A native of Chicago, Wrigley was listed as the 58th richest  
American last year in a survey by Forbes magazine, with an 
estimated wealth of $2.7 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Wrigley began working in 1956 for the company made famous by its  
chewing gum brands, including Juicy Fruit and Doublemint. He became 
director and vice president of the company in 1960 and succeeded 
his father as president in 1961. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Monday, the Chicago-based company had announced that  
Wrigley's son, William Wrigley Jr., had been named acting president 
while his father was in the hospital recovering from pneumonia. 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Wrigley had fractured his hip in mid-January and  
developed pneumonia while recuperating, according to a company 
statement. After a short hospital stay for the hip injury, Wrigley 
went home, but he recently returned to the hospital and was being 
treated in the intensive care unit when he died. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to his role in the family business, Wrigley served  
as director of several corporations. His business affiliations 
included Madison, N.J.-based American Home Products Corp. and White 
Plains, N.Y.-based Texaco Inc. He was director and chairman of the 
board at Santa Catalina Island Co. in California and served on the 
board of the Grocery Manufacturers of America. 
</P>
<P>
	He was a benefactor and life member of the Santa Catalina Island  
Conservancy and served on the board of trustees of the University 
of Southern California. 
</P>
<P>
	The family also has deep ties to Chicago as former owners of the  
Chicago Cubs. The Cubs still play in Wrigley Field. 
</P>
<P>
	Most recently, Wrigley lived in Lake Geneva, Wisc. Funeral  
arrangements are pending. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
