<DOCNO> APW19990308.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 23:11:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Y2K Nuclear Stand-Down Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States and other nuclear powers  
should take their missiles off alert to avoid dangerous 
confrontations in the event of computer failures on Jan. 1, 2000, a 
Democratic lawmaker says. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a perfect opportunity to use the Y2K issue to open the  
whole discussion'' of nuclear stand-down, Rep. Ed Markey, D-Mass., 
said Monday at a symposium on how the Year 2000 computer crisis 
might affect nuclear power plants and weapons systems. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon has not publicly discussed the idea of a  
stand-down, although some officials have raised concerns that 
taking weapons off alert status and then putting them back on might 
pose additional risks. In the military, a stand-down means to go 
off duty for a certain time. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the administration has proposed that Russian experts  
and American counterparts meet in Colorado at the end of the year 
to jointly monitor early warning systems and prevent 
computer-generated misperceptions of an attack. A Russian 
delegation is coming to Washington later this month to discuss this 
and other ideas on the Y2K problem. 
</P>
<P>
	But Michael Kraig of the British American Security Information  
Council said at the symposium that no matter what steps are taken, 
``computer errors are by their very nature idiosyncratic'' and 
``the real cure is to take the weapons off alert.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Russia is thought to be well behind the United States in fixing  
computers to make sure they don't confuse the date 2000 with the 
year 1900, and Bruce Blair of the Brookings Institution said the 
Russian early warning system, with its thousands of missiles on 
hair-trigger alert, is especially susceptible to the computer bug. 
</P>
<P>
	He added that breakdowns in power grids could degrade the  
Russians' ability to monitor events such as the theft of nuclear 
weapons and that shutdowns in the cooling systems in 72 or 73 
deactivated Russian submarines raise ``the possibility of multiple 
Chernobyls.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blair and others said there is little evidence even in Russia to  
justify fears that computer errors will lead to accidental launches 
or explosions in nuclear silos. Deputy Defense Secretary John Hamre 
told a Senate hearing last month that ``our nuclear command and 
control system has been thoroughly tested and has performed 
superbly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Speakers at the symposium also urged the Nuclear Regulatory  
Commission to adopt a more hands-on approach to assuring that 
nuclear power plants in this country are safe and that adequate 
backup systems will be in place. 
</P>
<P>
	David Lochbaum of the Union of Concerned Scientists said the NRC  
has audited only 12 of 103 operating nuclear plants to ensure their 
preparedness and ``needs to change from being a spectator to being 
a regulator.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NRC's executive director for operations, William Travers,  
testified to Congress last month that the commission is confident 
that all plants will be Y2K ready by October, and, should 
noncompliance be spotted, the NRC is ready to take steps including 
shutting down plants. NRC officials said inspectors will check on 
Y2K fixes at all the plants this spring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
