<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Noon EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Joe DiMaggio Dies  
</P>
<P>
	HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) -- Baseball Hall of Famer Joe DiMaggio,  
whose 56-game hitting streak in 1941 captivated the nation, died 
today at age 84. The New York Yankees star underwent lung cancer 
surgery in October and battled a series of complications for weeks 
afterward. Baseball commissioner Bud Selig called DiMaggio ``the 
personification of grace, class and dignity on the baseball 
diamond.'' Yankees owner George Steinbrenner says he told DiMaggio 
he would see him on Opening Day at Yankee Stadium next month, where 
DiMaggio would throw out the first ball. DiMaggio just smiled. 

</P>
<P>
	Film Director Stanley Kubrick Dies  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Police say director Stanley Kubrick died of  
natural causes and there are no suspicious circumstances. Kubrick, 
who directed ``Dr. Strangelove,'' ``A Clockwork Orange,'' and 
``2001: A Space Odyssey,'' died yesterday at age 70. He had been at 
work on ``Eyes Wide Shut'' for two years. The film, his first since 
``Full Metal Jacket'' in 1987, is scheduled for a mid-year release. 

</P>
<P>
	Doctor: George Jones Getting Better  
</P>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Doctors say country singer George Jones  
has made significant improvement from a traffic accident and may 
soon be able to breathe without a ventilator. They caution that the 
67-year-old music star is still in critical condition with a 
``life-threatening injury.'' Jones had a quiet night, two days 
after nearly dying when he smashed his sport-utility vehicle into a 
bridge near his home. He was talking on his cell phone at the time, 
and wasn't wearing a seat belt. His liver was cut deeply, and his 
right lung was punctured. Jones has charted more than 140 records, 
including classics like ``He Stopped Loving Her Today'' and ``A 
Good Year for the Roses.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Lewinsky Mobbed at Book Store  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Monica Lewinsky temporarily abandoned a signing  
session today on the first stop of her British book tour because of 
a crush of media attention. The world's most famous intern appeared 
shaken and teary as hundreds of photographers shouted her name and 
took her picture at the London department store Harrods. The 
book-signing resumed after the media were herded out of the room. 
When she came back, Ms. Lewinsky got a round of applause from the 
hundreds of people lined up to have copies of her biography 
autographed. ``Monica's Story'' climbed to the top of some Internet 
best seller lists after its release last week, although British 
bookstores reported only moderate sales. 

</P>
<P>
	Fighting Threatens Kosovo Deal  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Fighting broke out today in Kosovo  
along the Macedonian border, hampering attempts by U.S. and 
European envoys to forge a peace deal between Serbs and ethnic 
Albanians. The rebel Kosovo Liberation Army said the fighting 
started at dawn around Kracanik, near the province's border with 
Macedonia, and foreign observers reported hearing mortar and 
small-arms fire in the area. Meanwhile, U.S. and German envoys were 
to meet today with Yugoslav officials. The U.S.-sponsored peace 
proposal offers autonomy but not full independence for Kosovo 
Albanians, which the rebels have been demanding during a bitter 
ethnic war over the past year. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Rejects McVeigh's Appeal  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today left intact Timothy  
McVeigh's conviction and death sentence for the 1995 Oklahoma City 
bombing that killed 168 people and injured hundreds more. The court 
rejected an appeal in which McVeigh argued his trial was tainted by 
jury misconduct and news reports that he confessed to his lawyers. 

</P>
<P>
	J. Peterman Future Still in Flux  
</P>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- John Peterman says he's been ousted from the  
upscale catalog retailer that bears his name, but his new boss said 
today she has yet to decide what his future at the company will be. 
J. Peterman, the company satirized on television by ``Seinfeld,'' 
was rescued from bankruptcy liquidation late Friday by Paul Harris 
Stores of Indianapolis. 

</P>
