<DOCNO> APW19990308.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 14:55:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indians Stopped DiMaggio Streak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- This is where the Streak stopped on July 17,  
1941. 
</P>
<P>
	When Indians shortstop Lou Boudreau fielded Joe DiMaggio's hard  
smash to start a double play in the eighth inning that day, the 
Yankee Clipper's remarkable 56-game hitting streak had come to an 
end. 
</P>
<P>
	However, DiMaggio's legacy as baseball's consummate gentleman  
was only beginning. 
</P>
<P>
	``When Boudreau made the play,'' Bob Feller remembered, ``Joe  
didn't show any emotion. He never did. He didn't kick first base or 
anything like that. He just ran into the dugout like he always 
did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Feller, like baseball fans everywhere, paused Monday to reflect  
upon DiMaggio, who died at 84. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was the best all-around player of my time,'' the Hall of  
Fame pitcher said. ``He was as good a hitter as there ever was. Of 
course, Ted (Williams) was better. But Joe could do it all. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was a great clutch hitter and just a great person. We were  
good friends. We're all going to miss him, and no one is ever going 
to replace him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On July 16, 1941, DiMaggio's streak was at 55 games when the  
first-place New York Yankees arrived in town for a three-game 
series against the Indians. 
</P>
<P>
	In the opener at League Park, DiMaggio got three hits as the  
Yankees won 10-3 to open a six-game lead over Cleveland. Following 
the game, DiMaggio, ever the team player, played down the 
significance of his streak. 
</P>
<P>
	``Winning ballgames is more important than streaks,'' he told  
the Cleveland Press. ``And if I can draw a walk or contribute a 
sacrifice where they would help us most, I'm for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With DiMaggio's streak attracting record crowds in other cities,  
the series was switched to mammoth Municipal Stadium, and a crowd 
of 67,468 -- then the largest night crowd in baseball history -- came 
out for Game 2. 
</P>
<P>
	Facing left-handed starter Al Smith in the first inning,  
DiMaggio ripped a shot down the third-base line that Ken Keltner 
stopped while diving to his right. Keltner, who had nearly stopped 
the Streak at 18 games with a similar play, made a perfect throw to 
first to nip DiMaggio. 
</P>
<P>
	After walking in his next at-bat, DiMaggio hit another shot  
toward third, and again Keltner made a sensational play. 
</P>
<P>
	``Keltner made a couple of great plays,'' said Feller, who would  
beat the Yankees 2-1 the next day back at League Park. ``If not for 
those, and Brooks Robinson is the only other guy I've seen make 
them like that, who knows how far the streak would have gone?'' 
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio got another chance to prolong his streak to 57 games in  
the eighth inning against reliever Jim Bagby. With the bases 
loaded, DiMaggio hit a hard shot that took a bad hop on Boudreau, 
who gloved it and started the double play. 
</P>
<P>
	Keltner's defense denied Indians fans a chance to see if Feller,  
who won 25 games in '41, could have stopped the great DiMaggio. 
</P>
<P>
	``He always hit me quite well,'' said Feller. ``But after the  
war, I started pitching him differently. I started pitching him 
inside. He liked the ball out over the plate. He was a sweep 
hitter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio's 0-for-3 was big news, but the Yankee Clipper was  
knocked off the Press' front page on July 18 by other world events. 
</P>
<P>
	``Report: Hitler SOS To Japs'' read the paper's headline.  
</P>
<P>
	Inside, DiMaggio credited Keltner ``a mighty fine third  
baseman'' for his defensive gems and summed up his streak 
succinctly. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything comes to an end sometime,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 12:35:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fortis Buying American Bankers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Belgian-Dutch banking and insurance group Fortis AG  
is buying American Bankers Insurance Group for $2.4 billion, a move 
the companies said would increase earnings, expand markets and 
eventually increase the number of products sold. 
</P>
<P>
	American Bankers, a leader in selling specialty insurance, such  
as coverage for credit cards, bank loans and mobile homes, had been 
the target of a bidding war last year, but no deal was consummated. 
</P>
<P>
	Fortis, based in Brussels and one of the world's largest  
insurance companies, said Monday that it offered $55 a share for 
all 43 million shares of American Bankers' common stock. Fortis 
also would assume $194 million of debt. 
</P>
<P>
	American Bankers stock shot up 12 percent on the news, gaining  
$5.62 1/2 to $52 in afternoon trading on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, which is expected to close before October, would be  
the latest example of a European insurer buying a U.S. financial 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Aegon NV of the Netherlands recently agreed to buy Transamerica  
Corp. for $9.7 billion in cash and stock after buying Providian 
Corp. for $2.6 billion in 1997. ING Group NV, another Dutch 
company, bought life insurer Equitable of Iowa Cos. for $2.2 
billion in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of its offer, Fortis promised to keep American Bankers  
operations in Miami where American Bankers employs about 1,700 of 
its 3,000 employees. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not anticipate layoffs will be necessary, but we will be  
combining operations,'' said Allen Freedman, chief executive of 
Fortis Inc., the U.S. holding company for Fortis. 
</P>
<P>
	The transaction was approved by the board of directors of both  
companies. It is subject to regulatory approval and must be 
approved by American Bankers' shareholders, who are expected to 
vote within 30 days of regulatory approval. 
</P>
<P>
	Fortis, already strong in the Netherlands, Belgium and  
Luxembourg, will benefit from American Bankers' presence in Latin 
America, including Argentina and Panama, Freedman said. 
</P>
<P>
	American International Group Inc. had agreed to acquire American  
Bankers in late 1997 for $47 a share. The deal was broken up by 
Cendant Corp. in early 1998, which agreed to pay $67 a share in 
cash and stock for American Bankers. 
</P>
<P>
	But Cendant's accounting scandal and swooning stock price then  
contributed to the collapse of the deal in mid-October. Cendant was 
forced to pay American Bankers a $400 million breakup fee. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 10:16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Yanks Wanted To Honor DiMaggio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Joe DiMaggio fell a month and a day short of another appearance  
at Yankee Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio, who died today, had tacked to his bed a sign that said  
``April 9,'' opening day at Yankee Stadium, where he was supposed 
to throw out the first ball. 
</P>
<P>
	``Five days ago, on March 2, I visited with Joe at his home in  
Hollywood, Fla. He was weak but spirited and alert,'' said George 
Steinbrenner, the New York Yankees' owner. ``I told him, 'Joe, you 
have a date with the Yankees on opening day. We are counting on you 
to throw out the first ball.' 
</P>
<P>
	``He just smiled.''  
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio made a lot of people smile, as was apparent by the  
tributes that began pouring in minutes after his death was 
announced. 
</P>
<P>
	He also transcended baseball, much like Michael Jordan in  
basketball a half-century later, and was a spokesman long after he 
retired for a variety of products, including Mr. Coffee. In New 
York's Grand Central Station, a bank he endorsed simply posted the 
pinstriped number ``5.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And he reached fans and non-fans as an American hero.  
</P>
<P>
	``Even though I was never one of those people who cared about  
baseball, I care a lot about Joe DiMaggio,'' said former New York 
Mayor Ed Koch, who grew up in the city during DiMaggio's heyday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He represented the best in America. It was his character, his  
generosity, his sensitivity. He was someone who set a standard 
every father would want his children to follow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	People in the sport agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``His persona extended beyond the playing field and touched all  
our hearts,'' baseball commissioner Bud Selig said. ``In many 
respects, as an immigrant's son, he represented the hopes and 
ideals of our great country. 
</P>
<P>
	``I idolized him from afar as a child growing up in Milwaukee.  
In later years, when I had the opportunity to become acquainted 
with him, my admiration grew. Being with him was an event, bringing 
on an air of excitement, anticipation and joy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tommy Lasorda, former Los Angeles Dodgers manager, suggested  
that DiMaggio's record 56-game hitting streak may stand for another 
100 years, unlike Babe Ruth and Roger Maris' home run records and 
Lou Gehrig's consecutive-game streak. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was always kind of shy,'' Lasorda said of DiMaggio. ``He  
felt uncomfortable with a lot of people, but yet he was always 
there as a tremendous representative of our game of baseball. He 
was an icon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Albany, a bill is before the New York legislature to rename  
the city's West Side Highway for DiMaggio. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm comforted, as are all New Yorkers, that we informed him  
before he died that the West Side Highway will be renamed the Joe 
DiMaggio Highway,'' said Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, a longtime Yankees 
fan. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as baseball is played, Joe DiMaggio will exemplify the  
very best.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Cooperstown, N.Y., the Hall of Fame flag was at half-staff  
and a wreath was placed on DiMaggio's plaque. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hall has also scheduled special DiMaggio video programming  
for March, put a tribute on its Web site and is planning an 
exhibit. 
</P>
<P>
	It will include the glove that outfielder Al Gionfriddo of the  
Brooklyn Dodgers used when he robbed DiMaggio of an extra base hit 
with a spectacular running catch in the 1947 World Series, and 
DiMaggio's contract for 1948, the first in sports to reach 
$100,000. Even the pen is there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 10:16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Yanks Wanted To Honor DiMaggio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Joe DiMaggio fell a month and a day short of another appearance  
at Yankee Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio, who died today, had tacked to his bed a sign that said  
``April 9,'' opening day at Yankee Stadium, where he was supposed 
to throw out the first ball. 
</P>
<P>
	``Five days ago, on March 2, I visited with Joe at his home in  
Hollywood, Fla. He was weak but spirited and alert,'' said George 
Steinbrenner, the New York Yankees' owner. ``I told him, 'Joe, you 
have a date with the Yankees on opening day. We are counting on you 
to throw out the first ball.' 
</P>
<P>
	``He just smiled.''  
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio made a lot of people smile, as was apparent by the  
tributes that began pouring in minutes after his death was 
announced. 
</P>
<P>
	He also transcended baseball, much like Michael Jordan in  
basketball a half-century later, and was a spokesman long after he 
retired for a variety of products, including Mr. Coffee. In New 
York's Grand Central Station, a bank he endorsed simply posted the 
pinstriped number ``5.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And he reached fans and non-fans as an American hero.  
</P>
<P>
	``Even though I was never one of those people who cared about  
baseball, I care a lot about Joe DiMaggio,'' said former New York 
Mayor Ed Koch, who grew up in the city during DiMaggio's heyday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He represented the best in America. It was his character, his  
generosity, his sensitivity. He was someone who set a standard 
every father would want his children to follow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	People in the sport agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``His persona extended beyond the playing field and touched all  
our hearts,'' baseball commissioner Bud Selig said. ``In many 
respects, as an immigrant's son, he represented the hopes and 
ideals of our great country. 
</P>
<P>
	``I idolized him from afar as a child growing up in Milwaukee.  
In later years, when I had the opportunity to become acquainted 
with him, my admiration grew. Being with him was an event, bringing 
on an air of excitement, anticipation and joy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tommy Lasorda, former Los Angeles Dodgers manager, suggested  
that DiMaggio's record 56-game hitting streak may stand for another 
100 years, unlike Babe Ruth and Roger Maris' home run records and 
Lou Gehrig's consecutive-game streak. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was always kind of shy,'' Lasorda said of DiMaggio. ``He  
felt uncomfortable with a lot of people, but yet he was always 
there as a tremendous representative of our game of baseball. He 
was an icon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Albany, a bill is before the New York legislature to rename  
the city's West Side Highway for DiMaggio. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm comforted, as are all New Yorkers, that we informed him  
before he died that the West Side Highway will be renamed the Joe 
DiMaggio Highway,'' said Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, a longtime Yankees 
fan. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as baseball is played, Joe DiMaggio will exemplify the  
very best.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Cooperstown, N.Y., the Hall of Fame flag was at half-staff  
and a wreath was placed on DiMaggio's plaque. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hall has also scheduled special DiMaggio video programming  
for March, put a tribute on its Web site and is planning an 
exhibit. 
</P>
<P>
	It will include the glove that outfielder Al Gionfriddo of the  
Brooklyn Dodgers used when he robbed DiMaggio of an extra base hit 
with a spectacular running catch in the 1947 World Series, and 
DiMaggio's contract for 1948, the first in sports to reach 
$100,000. Even the pen is there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
