<DOCNO> APW19990308.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 15:26:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IRS Entering Credit on Tax Forms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Thousands of people who mistakenly failed to  
take advantage of new child credits on their income tax returns are 
getting some help from the Internal Revenue Service. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRS estimated Monday that so far, more than 30,000 taxpayers  
who appear to qualify for the $400-per-child credits failed to 
enter it on their tax forms this year. But Uncle Sam is taking care 
of the problem for them. 
</P>
<P>
	In some cases, this means a larger-than-expected income tax  
refund; in others, it means a smaller tax bill, IRS spokesman Don 
Roberts said. 
</P>
<P>
	The credit is new for the 1998 tax year. Within certain income  
limits, a taxpayer can qualify for $400 credits for each dependent 
child, grandchild, stepchild, adopted child or foster child who is 
under age 17 and is a U.S. citizen or resident. 
</P>
<P>
	The child credit is largely responsible for a 15.5 percent  
increase in average refunds this year, from $1,497 to $1,729. 
Roberts said about a quarter of the 39 million tax returns filed 
thus far have claimed the credit. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRS is finding that thousands of people checked a box on  
their 1040 forms -- column 4 of line 6c -- indicating that a 
dependent meets these qualifications, but they failed to enter the 
$400 or more on line 43 of the form. 
</P>
<P>
	By using Social Security records, the IRS can determine if one  
dependent qualifies and will automatically correct the mistake. The 
IRS for years has corrected tax return math errors and other 
mistakes, often to taxpayers' benefit. 
</P>
<P>
	If the service can't determine eligibility, taxpayers will get a  
letter from IRS explaining the discrepancy and requesting an 
amended return to take advantage of it. 
</P>
<P>
	For additional child credits, taxpayers should contact IRS about  
whether those dependents are eligible. 
</P>
<P>
	Some taxpayers cannot claim the credit because their incomes are  
too high. The credit is reduced by $50 for every $1,000 of a 
taxpayer's income that is above $75,000, or $110,000 for a married 
couple filing jointly. 
</P>
<P>
	Credits differ from deductions in that they reduce tax liability  
on a dollar-for-dollar basis, while a deduction reduces the amount 
of income that is subject to taxation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 03:28:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles To Play in Cuba March 28 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	For the first time in 40 years, major league baseball will  
return to Cuba when the Baltimore Orioles play the Cuban national 
team on March 28 in Havana. 
</P>
<P>
	After two months of negotiations among the State Department,  
Cuban government, commissioner's office, the Orioles and the 
players' association, the sides finally reached an agreement 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``If this produces the kind of human results that we're all  
hoping it does, this could be something really big,'' baseball 
commissioner Bud Selig said. ``I'm very proud of the role we will 
play in doing something constructive that transcends baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cuban team will play a return exhibition game at Camden  
Yards. The second game will be played either just before Baltimore 
starts the regular season April 5 or on an off day during the 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope that they do come,'' Stanley Hynds, a 25-year-old  
barber, shouted amid the clanging steel drums, trumpet blares and 
impassioned screams Sunday at Havana's Latinoamericano Stadium. 
``It will be a pleasure for us to see them and to see them lose 
right here in this stadium!'' 
</P>
<P>
	The games were planned after the Clinton administration decided  
in January to ease the four-decade-old U.S. trade embargo against 
Cuba. Major league baseball teams used to visit Cuba regularly, but 
the last were the Cincinnati Reds and Los Angeles Dodgers, who 
played exhibition games there in March 1959, about 2 1/2 months after 
Fidel Castro's revolution ousted dictator Fulgencio Batista on New 
Year's Day. 
</P>
<P>
	Selig, who plans to attend the game in Havana, said the major  
leagues might schedule additional events in Cuba if this one is 
successful. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are other clubs that want to do this, too,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Several Cubans have defected in recent years and play for major  
league teams, notably Florida pitcher Livan Hernandez, the 1997 
World Series MVP; his half-brother Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez, 
who starred for the New York Yankees in last year's postseason; and 
Tampa Bay pitcher Rolando Arrojo. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're very good players,'' Orioles outfielder B.J. Surhoff  
said. ``If you look around the majors, there are a number of very 
good players with Cuban backgrounds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Castro, Cuba's president and a former baseball player himself,  
has referred to defectors as ``traitors,'' and Cuban officials have 
accused U.S. teams of trying to bribe Cuban players into abandoning 
their country. U.S. agents have helped Cuban players defect when 
they were on tour outside their homeland. 
</P>
<P>
	While salaries in Cuba average $10 a month, Livan Hernandez got  
a four-year contract from the Marlins worth $4,495,000, and Orlando 
got a $6.6 million, four-year deal from the Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuban refugees and several congressmen have criticized baseball  
and the Orioles for dealing with Castro and oppose the games. About 
70 people protested Sunday at the Orioles' exhibition game against 
the Florida Marlins in Fort Lauderdale, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	``Going to Cuba under the current conditions there is a sign of  
insensitivity and lack of respect for human rights there,'' said 
Huber Matos, a Cuban native who spent 20 years in prison on the 
island for opposing Castro's government. ``It's like taking part in 
the abuses that are going on there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Selig said he understands ``people have all kinds of different  
human and political views.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very sensitive to that. I understand the feelings,'' he  
said in Tampa, Fla. ``We'll take care of the baseball politics and 
let the governments take care of the other issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Proceeds from the two games -- a sticking point in the  
negotiations -- will be used mainly to support baseball and other 
sports activities in the two countries, major league baseball said. 
The Clinton administration did not want profits to go to Castro's 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	Because it's only an exhibition game, Orioles players won't put  
too much emphasis on it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got things I need to get done on the field,'' first  
baseman Will Clark said. ``If I'm one of the guys who has to go 
down there, I'm going to treat it just like another ball game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the deal, two American League umpires and two Cuban  
umpires will work the game, and the Cuban team agreed to use wood 
bats instead of the metal bats it usually hits with, according a 
source familiar with the deal who spoke on the condition he not be 
identified. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles and the commissioner's office will pay for the  
improvements at Latinamericano Stadium, such as padding the 
outfield fence, the source said. 
</P>
<P>
	A delegation from major league baseball, the players'  
association and the Orioles probably will go to Havana this week to 
work out logistics and attempt to settle when the game in Baltimore 
will be played. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 13:17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Monday's Supreme Court Rulings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court took the following actions  
Monday: 
</P>
<P>
	--Let stand Timothy McVeigh's conviction and death sentence for  
the 1995 Oklahoma City bombing that killed 168 people and injured 
hundreds more, the worst such attack on U.S. soil. McVeigh argued 
his trial was tainted by jury misconduct and news reports that he 
confessed to his lawyers. He still can pursue a new round of 
appeals in federal court. 
</P>
<P>
	--Refused to free filmmaker Oliver Stone from a lawsuit that says  
his movie, ``Natural Born Killers,'' led a couple to shoot a woman 
during a robbery. The lawsuit accuses Stone and others of 
intentionally inciting copycat crimes. The filmmakers say the 
lawsuit threatens freedom of expression. 
</P>
<P>
	--Rejected the appeal of a Missouri high school teacher fired for  
letting her students use large amounts of profanity in class while 
performing self-written plays. School officials said she violated a 
policy requiring teachers to enforce a ban on students' use of 
profanity. 
</P>
<P>
	--Turned away Marlena Ramallo Cooke's appeal in her effort to  
avoid being deported over a 1986 guilty plea to a drug conspiracy 
charge. She is the widow of Jack Kent Cooke, who owned the 
Washington Redskins professional football team. 
</P>
<P>
	--Agreed to clarify the filing deadline for lawsuits that invoke  
a federal anti-racketeering law. The justices said they will study 
the case of a Texas man who says he was illegally held in a 
psychiatric hospital by profit-greedy doctors. 
</P>
<P>
	--Turned away a dispute between Santa Barbara, Calif., officials  
and anti-abortion activists over the city's restrictions on how 
close demonstrators can approach abortion clinics or their 
patients. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 15:18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Mount St. Mary's Faces Spartan Task </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EMMITSBURG, Md. (AP) -- Mount Saint Mary's doesn't have the size,  
speed and talent of most teams in the NCAA tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	When it comes to coaching, however, the Mountaineers have the  
winningest guy in the business. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Phelan, who has won 800 games and owns a .644 career winning  
percentage, will make his second appearance in the tournament 
Friday when he leads 15th-seeded Mount St. Mary's (15-14) against 
second-ranked Michigan State in the Midwest regional. 
</P>
<P>
	Phelan has recorded at least 20 wins in 19 of his 45 seasons at  
the Mount and trails only retired legends Dean Smith (879), Adolph 
Rupp (876) and Clarence ``Big House'' Gaines (828) on the career 
victory list. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet Phelan's gaudy numbers hardly begin to tell the story of a  
devoted coach who has run a spotless program and helped shape the 
lives of hundreds of young men. 
</P>
<P>
	Fred Carter was playing basketball on the playgrounds of  
Philadelphia in the mid-1960s when Phelan got the 20-year-old high 
school dropout to check out the Mount's cozy campus in the hills of 
western Maryland. 
</P>
<P>
	Carter became the first black to enroll in the school, starred  
for four seasons and went on to both play and coach in the NBA. He 
remains close friends with Phelan to this day. 
</P>
<P>
	``He transcends just being a coach. You talk about a father  
image -- my Dad died when I was 16 and coach Phelan was there for 
me. He's always been there for me,'' Carter said. 
</P>
<P>
	These days, Phelan has another project: center Melvin Whitaker,  
who enrolled after spending two years in jail for slashing a 
University of Virginia football player with a box cutter on a 
recruiting visit there. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitaker, like Carter, had all but abandoned hope of a college  
career when Phelan came along and offered him a shot at redemption. 
</P>
<P>
	``How wonderful, coach Phelan's willingness to help people,''  
Carter said, his voice cracking with emotion. 
</P>
<P>
	``Melvin, like Fred, is a guy working on a second chance,''  
Phelan said. ``He really appreciates the opportunity. I think he 
likes not being at a prominent place like Raleigh or Durham.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Same with Phelan, who long ago laid to the rest the notion of  
coaching at a bigger school. Phelan interviewed at the Mount in 
1954, immediately took the job and has since spurned subsequent 
offers from more prominent institutions. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been wonderful to be out of the limelight. Out here in  
the country I can do as I please,'' he said. ``I was a city-slicker 
the first 24 years of my life -- it was great growing up in south 
Philly -- but now I live in a totally different world and I couldn't 
be happier.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Phelan, 69, skillfully avoids talk about retirement, so it seems  
as if his trademark bow-tie will remain a part of Mount games for 
at least another year or two. 
</P>
<P>
	``If my wife had her way I'd be doing it until I was 85, just so  
I'd be out of her way at home,'' he joked. 
</P>
<P>
	``How long can he stay? As long as he feels like it,'' said Jack  
Sullivan, Class of '57 and the school's career scoring leader. ``As 
long as he feels as if he can contribute and give something to the 
kids, he'll be out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The game has changed dramatically since Phelan began drawing up  
plays on the blackboard in the 1950s. So have the athletes. Yet 
Phelan has managed to cope with it all, tweaking his playbook 
through the years while maintaining a solid rapport with players 
young enough to be his grandchildren. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been able to withstand the test of time,'' Carter said.  
``For a guy to coach four decades, almost four generations, it just 
shows how well he's been able to make the adjustment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Phelan's first year, he transformed a 15-11 team into a 23-4  
powerhouse. The rest, as they say, is history. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got off to a good start, and it started a long love affair  
between me and this place,'' he said. ``It's still going on, too.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 15:18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
