<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 23:05:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vet Bill As High As Elephant's Eye </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) -- When your prized 7,300-pound East  
Indian elephant develops an infection, you go to great lengths to 
cure it, including asking City Council for help. 
</P>
<P>
	And if you're City Council, you pay the bill.  
</P>
<P>
	When Ruth, an elephant at the Buttonwood Park Zoo, developed a  
corneal infection, the zoo paid $17,500 for a cure. 
</P>
<P>
	The hefty bill raised eyebrows Tuesday when put before the City  
Council. But zoo officials said the value of the 42-year-old 
pachyderm's right eye was priceless. 
</P>
<P>
	In November, zoo officials discovered the penny-sized white  
growth after Ruth poked herself in the eye with a piece of straw. 
Veterinarians suspect the straw carried a fungus. 
</P>
<P>
	Treatment, which included almost three months of round-the-clock  
care, ended up costing $1,400 for medication and supplies, $8,000 
for consulting fees and $8,100 for overtime pay. 
</P>
<P>
	The elephant was mostly cooperative when zoo employees made her  
lie down on her side 12 times a day so they could administer five 
different drops. 
</P>
<P>
	After the mayor asked the City Council to approve a transfer of  
funds to pay for the treatment, councilors wanted a few 
explanations. 
</P>
<P>
	``How much does an elephant cost?'' one councilor asked.  
</P>
<P>
	Director of Zoological Services David Raboy responded that Ruth  
is priceless. He added that there are very few elephants in North 
American zoos and that breeding has proven difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	``She cannot be replaced,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The council approved the payment 11-0.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
