<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 00:53:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Says Campaign Is His Not Dads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- It won't be his father's presidential  
campaign, Texas Gov. George W. Bush says. 
</P>
<P>
	Unveiling his exploratory committee Sunday, Bush said potential  
Republican opponents should steer clear of the other George Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any rival who criticizes my father makes a huge mistake. He's  
not the candidate, I am,'' Bush said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican governor quickly corrected himself -- ``OK, you  
got me. ... He's not the candidate, and should I choose to run I 
will be the candidate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Bush acknowledged it now is ``obvious'' that he is ``very  
interested in running for the presidency.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I went from warming to the task to pretty hot,'' he said. ``I  
wouldn't have asked the people coming from around the country, 
who've agreed to help me raise money, if I wasn't seriously 
interested.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's announcement gives shape to a field of at least 10  
Republicans. Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander officially 
enters the campaign Tuesday; former American Red Cross President 
Elizabeth Dole will take the same step as Bush, forming her 
exploratory committee Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Bush promises to remain in Texas until after the state  
Legislature adjourns on May 31, others in the GOP already are 
taking aim. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander said the strong showings by Bush and Mrs. Dole in  
polls could be fleeting. Bush and the wife of 1996 GOP nominee Bob 
Dole, benefit from name recognition, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pretty soon it will come on down back to earth,'' Alexander  
said Sunday on NBC's ``Meet The Press.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Three prominent conservatives released a letter urging support  
for Steve Forbes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Republicans have suffered two major defeats in a row for the  
presidency by nominating moderate, establishment candidates,'' said 
the letter from L. Brent Bozell III, Richard Viguerie and Morton 
Blackwell. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's father lost in 1992; Mrs. Dole's husband in 1996.  
</P>
<P>
	``If the GOP does not nominate a candidate with a clear,  
concise, conservative message in opposition to the liberal agenda 
of Al Gore, why should the country elect a Republican?'' they 
wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, who has touted a philosophy of ``compassionate  
conservatism,'' so far has declined to respond to such criticism. 
``I'm going to try to work hard not to play the typical political 
game of tearing down your opponent,'' he said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's 10-member exploratory committee includes three women, one  
of them black, one Hispanic man and one black man. Former Secretary 
of State George Schultz, former GOP chairman Haley Barbour, Rep. 
J.C. Watts Jr. of Oklahoma and five other congressional Republicans 
give a Washington flavor to the group. 
</P>
<P>
	Some committee members sounded as though the exploring's already  
over. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we get through with all of the exploring, the answer has  
got to be `yes,''' said Schultz. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am confident this exploratory committee will find plenty of  
support for George Bush for president,'' Barbour added. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, 52, has so far raised no money. He will file papers with  
the Federal Election Committee today allowing him to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	Advisers have said he hopes to quickly collect about $25  
million. In his races for governor, Bush raised about $16 million 
in 1994 and $17.7 million in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush -- who thus far has campaigned largely from the Governor's  
Mansion in Austin, with supporters coming to him -- said he knows 
his strategy of staying in Texas for the next three months is 
unusual. But he's keeping a promise to Texas voters who re-elected 
him, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to tell my friends outside of Texas, especially in the  
early primary states, I won't be able to visit until this summer. I 
know I will be late, but if I go forward with a campaign, I will 
work hard to overcome my late start,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
