<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Elected Into Harness Hall of Fame </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLTS NECK, NJ. (AP) -- The richest Standardbred in history,  
trotting mare Peace Corps, and pacing stallion Abercrombie on 
Monday were elected into the Harness Racing Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	They will be inducted into the Harness Racing Museum and Hall of  
Fame in Goshen, N.Y., on July 4. 
</P>
<P>
	Peace Corps, winner of $5.5 million, won 62 races in the United  
States and Europe, including four Breeders Crowns and the 1991 
Elitlopp in Sweden. She is the leading money-winning female of any 
breed, competing from 1988 to 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Abercrombie, who has sired winners of $115 million in purses,  
raced from 1977 through 1979 and was Horse of the Year in 1978. His 
progeny include three winners of $1 million or more, including his 
son Artsplace with $3 million in earnings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
