<DOCNO> APW19990308.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 16:16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) -- Two young men on bicycles attacked  
the wife of the U.S. ambassador to Costa Rica and stole her 
jewelry, local news media reported Monday. Two suspects were 
arrested. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Embassy wouldn't comment on the reports, and the  
authorities did not confirm them, but Ambassador Thomas Dodd and 
his wife, Mary, were shown on television and radio at a police 
station to give a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's is good shape,'' Dodd said.  
</P>
<P>
	According to the reports, Mrs. Dodd, 61, was attacked near her  
house in southern San Jose on Sunday afternoon. It was unclear 
whether she suffered any injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	The two young men took two pieces of gold jewelry worth $3,000,  
according to the reports. 
</P>
<P>
	A Costa Rican and a Nicaraguan were arrested and one of the  
pieces of jewelry was recovered, according to the reports. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- The son of a dissident army general said  
Monday that someone fired at members of his family while they were 
visiting their father at a military prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Marco Vinicio Gallardo said at a news conference that he was  
playing tennis at a Mexico City prison on visiting day Sunday when 
the shot was fired. His father, army Brig. Gen. Alejandro Gallardo, 
was refereeing the game. 
</P>
<P>
	No one was hurt.  
</P>
<P>
	The son said he and two brothers who were present have filed a  
complaint with the Attorney General's Office. They said the 
shooting was an attempted homicide. 
</P>
<P>
	He added that his family has been harassed by the military since  
April, when Gen. Gallardo was sentenced by a court-martial to 28 
years in prison -- 14 years for illegally amassing a fortune while 
in uniform, and 14 years on charges of corruption and destroying 
files, to run consecutively. 
</P>
<P>
	Gen. Gallardo and his sons claim he was imprisoned because he  
publicly denounced corruption, nepotism and human rights violations 
within military. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- The environmental organization Greenpeace  
said Monday that a Mexican government proposal to increase private 
participation in the power industry does not adequately address 
ecological issues. 
</P>
<P>
	The changes that President Ernesto Zedillo proposed to Congress  
on Feb. 3 ``do not take into account the great waste in electricity 
consumption and almost absolute dependence on fossil fuels,'' said 
Alejandro Calvillo, head of campaigns for Greenpeace in Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mexican government is seeking to amend the constitution to  
allow greater private participation in the electricity sector to 
cope with an expected growth in demand over the next few years. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposals would let private companies take part in power  
distribution, which is currently limited to two state-owned 
utilities. 
</P>
<P>
	Calvillo called for greater promotion of co-generation projects  
-- which use excess energy from other sources -- while urging that 
more attention be paid to efficient energy use. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
