<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 05:30:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Half of Carjackings Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Almost half the nation's annual average of  
49,000 carjacking attempts fail, and the overwhelming majority of 
victims escape injury, the Justice Department says. 
</P>
<P>
	Each year an average of 48,787 carjackings are attempted, but  
only 24,520, or 50.3 percent succeed, the Bureau of Justice 
Statistics said Sunday, reporting on data for 1992 through 1996, 
the most recent available. 
</P>
<P>
	Eighty-four percent of victims suffered no injury at all.  
</P>
<P>
	Only four percent of the victims suffered serious injuries, like  
gunshot or knife wounds, broken bones, internal injuries or loss of 
consciousness. The remainder had minor injuries like bruises or 
chipped teeth. Some incidents had more than one victim. 
</P>
<P>
	The bureau's survey had no data on murders during carjackings  
because the figures are estimates based on interviews during 
1992-1996 with 430,000 U.S. residents over age 12. Only survivors 
could be interviewed. 
</P>
<P>
	Using FBI data based on police reports, the bureau said there  
were an average of 27 murders by strangers each year during 
1992-1996 involving automobile theft. ``These may have been 
carjackings,'' the bureau said. 
</P>
<P>
	Victims were injured in 23 percent of the completed carjackings  
but in only 10 percent of the unsuccessful carjackings. A weapon 
was used in 83 percent of all incidents. 
</P>
<P>
	The bureau defined carjacking as a theft in which a vehicle was  
taken or attempted to be taken by force or threat of it. It only 
counted carjackings by strangers, not by acquaintances or 
relatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Only 22 percent of carjackings occurred at or near the victim's  
home, but 65 percent were within five miles. The bureau offered no 
explanation, but law enforcement and automobile club officials 
privately suggested that most cars spend most of their time within 
five miles of the owner's home. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty percent of the incidents occurred in an open area, such as  
on the street or near a bus, subway or train station or airport. 
Twenty percent were in parking lots or near stores, restaurants, 
gas stations and office buildings. 
</P>
<P>
	Carjackings were more successful in daylight hours, two of three  
times. At night, only half the attempts succeeded. 
</P>
<P>
	A firearm was used in 70 percent of the successful incidents,  
but only 20 percent of the unsuccessful ones. 
</P>
<P>
	No resistance was offered by 38 percent of the victims; the  
other 62 percent took some kind of action to defend themselves or 
their property. 
</P>
<P>
	Nineteen percent of victims attacked, chased or tried to catch  
the offender or threatened use of a weapon. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty-four percent of victims used non-confrontational defenses  
like running away, calling for help or trying to attract attention. 
</P>
<P>
	The remainder used unspecified defenses.  
</P>
<P>
	The bureau said there was not enough data to analyze the impact  
of various self-defenses on either the rate of victim injury or the 
success rate of the carjacking attempts. 
</P>
<P>
	The bureau found that all the completed carjackings were  
reported to the police, but only 57 percent of the attempted 
carjackings. 
</P>
<P>
	This was the bureau's second study of carjacking. A study five  
years ago found a somewhat lower annual average number of 
carjackings. Those totals, however, cannot be compared to the 
current figures because, in the interim, the questions used in the 
interviews were altered to probe the carjacking issue more fully, 
bureau spokesman Stu Smith said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 05:56:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yellow Springs Saves the Farm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YELLOW SPRINGS, Ohio (AP) -- A 1960s brand of counterculture  
still thrives in this southwestern Ohio village, where organic 
food, tie-dyed shirts and men in ponytails are part of the 
mainstream. 
</P>
<P>
	So when local residents found out a sprawling farm north of town  
was being auctioned off, possibly to developers, they rose to the 
occasion with rallies, fund-raisers and a 13-hour benefit. In the 
end, with the generosity of a pair of married lawyers, they 
gathered $3.27 million to buy all 930 acres. 
</P>
<P>
	``The great fear was that developers were going to come in and  
destroy the ambiance, the place and basically the life that people 
have here now,'' said Karen Gundersen, 33, pausing as she shopped 
at a gourmet food store. ``The whole town rallied around. It was 
really exciting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A village of 4,000 people 20 miles east of Dayton, Yellow  
Springs is home to Antioch College and saw hippies and war 
protesters walk its streets in the 1960s and '70s. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, shops selling pottery, art and health food line the main  
street, drawing tourists for a little '60s nostalgia. Incense burns 
inside the Second Chance Hemp Co. clothing store, where album 
covers of the Doors, Grand Funk Railroad, Led Zeppelin and other 
vintage rock groups hang on the walls. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're unique, and we want to keep it that way,'' said Maria  
Thornton-Bunkley, 30, as she tended to customers at the Organic 
Grocer. ``I get all misty just talking about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Residents saw a threat to their identity when they learned in  
January that Whitehall Farm just north of the village would be 
auctioned off to settle an estate. 
</P>
<P>
	The village immediately earmarked $400,000 from a special  
green-space fund to try to buy the farm. And then residents went 
into activist mode, organizing fund-raising events, rallies and 
even protests to try to scare away developers. 
</P>
<P>
	At Antioch College, 20-year-old Sarah Alden organized a 13-hour  
benefit concert. It featured 14 bands from as far away as Tennessee 
and raised nearly $7,000. Merchants also donated food, pottery, 
jewelry, T-shirts and other clothing for sales to raise money. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't understand how people can put these generic, pre-fab  
houses that mean nothing'' on farmland, Alden said. ``I don't want 
everything to look the same.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After three weeks of work, residents had raised about $600,000,  
sending the village to the Feb. 22 auction with nearly $1 million. 
An estimated 800 people crowded into a motel ballroom in nearby 
Springfield for the bidding. 
</P>
<P>
	Village Manager David Heckler popped open his notebook computer  
to track bids he and others made. Gloom set in when he got down to 
his group's last $497, and he began to look for help. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted to identify the strongest horse, get on that horse  
and ride,'' said Heckler. 
</P>
<P>
	David and Sharen Neuhardt, attorneys who wanted a piece of the  
farm because they own adjoining property, agreed to buy the whole 
farm for conservation with a combination of their own and the 
town's money and a bank loan. 
</P>
<P>
	As the auction built to a frenzied pitch, the Yellow  
Springs-Neuhardt coalition found itself pitted against a group of 
25 other bidders. 
</P>
<P>
	With the two groups tied at $3.26 million, the anti-development  
coalition upped its bid to $3.275 million. When the other bidders 
couldn't answer, preservationists in the back of the room counted 
down from 10 and then erupted into cheers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think Yellow Springs is a very special community,'' said  
Mrs. Neuhardt. ``Someone needs to stand up and say what makes sense 
for the use of this land.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In exchange for accepting $1 million from the village, the  
Neuhardts agreed to give their new property a legal status that 
will keep it from being developed by themselves or future owners. 
They plan to resell about 60 percent of the farm to farmers and 
lease some of the remaining property for farm and other 
non-development use. 
</P>
<P>
	Villagers celebrated with a parade and party.  
</P>
<P>
	``I would love to say that it's a blast from the past, but I  
don't think so,'' said Gundersen. ``I think it's moving toward the 
future.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 05:31:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  SEC Makes Record NCAA Showing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Looking for a sure way to get into the NCAA women's basketball  
tournament? 
</P>
<P>
	Scheduling tough opponents certainly helps. So does winning a  
lot of games. But what really helps is playing in the Southeastern 
Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA selection committee loaded up its brackets with SEC  
teams Sunday, giving berths to defending national champion 
Tennessee and seven others from that league -- four of whom finished 
at .500 or below in the conference. 
</P>
<P>
	That's a record for one conference, and a deserved one at that,  
Georgia coach Andy Landers said. The SEC previously had as many as 
seven teams in the NCAA field. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly, we've lived for years with the idea that we play in  
the most competitive conference in the country,'' said Landers, 
whose team is seeded third in the Mideast Regional.''Eight teams is 
certainly a compliment to the players and coaches. Most years, we 
easily could have had one more team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other SEC teams chosen for the tournament were Auburn, Alabama,  
Florida, Kentucky, Louisiana State and Mississippi State. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee (28-2) was seeded No. 1 in the East. The second-ranked  
Lady Vols begin their quest for a fourth consecutive NCAA 
championship at home Saturday against Appalachian State (14-14), 
which qualified by winning the Southern Conference tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	There were no surprises in the No. 1 seeds, with the other slots  
going to top-ranked Purdue (Midwest), third-ranked Louisiana Tech 
(West) and sixth-ranked Connecticut (Mideast). 
</P>
<P>
	The selection committee felt comfortable taking so many SEC  
teams because it was the No. 1-ranked league all season and all of 
those selected had strong power ratings, said Bernadette McGlade, 
who chairs the committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``The committee felt strongly that teams that got in from the  
top three or four conferences in the country were all teams that 
definitely were one of the best 64 in the country,'' McGlade said. 
</P>
<P>
	``That does not mean the SEC will forever get eight,'' she said.  
``I think it fluctuates by teams and conferences on an annual 
basis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two other SEC teams, Arkansas and Mississippi, were selected for  
the women's National Invitation Tournament, which was expanded from 
16 to 32 teams this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think most folks would tell you that one through those top  
eight or nine ... you go into the arena knowing you have to play 
strong basketball to win,'' Summitt said. ``When you weren't ready 
to play, you didn't come away with a win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Atlantic Coast Conference and Big 12 followed the SEC with  
five teams each in the NCAA field. The Big East, Big Ten, 
Conference USA and Pac-10 all had four. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee also rewarded lesser-known teams that tried to  
play competitive schedules outside their league. Maine, for 
instance, received an at-large bid out of the America East 
Conference, which usually gets only its tournament champion in the 
NCAA field. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing in our rules that says the America East can  
only have its automatic qualifier,'' McGlade said. ``They did make 
an effort to schedule. They had Tulane, Mississippi, Western 
Kentucky -- out of region games against teams that were projected to 
be tournament teams.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The lack of a challenging schedule left Cal Santa Barbara,  
ranked 17th and winner of 21 straight games, as a No. 10 seed in 
the West. Cal Santa Barbara plays in the Big West, the nation's 
17th-ranked conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``Scheduling out of conference becomes very important when teams  
can't rely on their conference ranking to get them in the 
tournament,'' said McGlade, who noted Santa Barbara didn't play 
anyone with an RPI in the top 25. ``I would recommend scheduling a 
handful of (strong) nonconference opponents.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Connecticut claimed a No. 1 seed after bouncing back from a rash  
of injuries at midseason, when the Huskies lost three of six games. 
They've won 12 of 13 since, including an impressive three-game run 
through the Big East tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, a late-season injury to All-American Nykesha Sales  
kept Connecticut from becoming a No. 1 seed and the Huskies were 
dropped to a No. 2. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, a key injury cost Notre Dame, expected to be among  
the top 16 seeds before losing point guard Niele Ivey to a 
season-ending knee injury in the Big East tournament. The 
eighth-ranked Irish, with their best record ever at 25-4, became 
the No. 5 seed in the West. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't get it,'' said Notre Dame coach Muffet McGraw, whose  
team beat three of the tournament's No. 3 seeds this season. ``I 
think Niele is a great player, but I think with a week to practice 
we're going to be fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Final Four is in San Jose, Calif., and the national  
semifinals will match the Midwest against the West and the East vs. 
the Mideast. That creates the possibility of a Tennessee-Louisiana 
Tech rematch in the championship game. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee beat Tech 93-75 in last year's title game in Kansas  
City, Mo., to complete a 39-0 season. And while the Lady Vols 
haven't been as dominant this season, Summitt says they're ready to 
go. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think this team has been waiting for March,'' she said.  
``We're all excited that it's finally here.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 05:31:24 </DATE_TIME>
