<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 18:42:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Pleads to Money Laundering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A key player in the largest drug money  
laundering case in U.S. history pleaded guilty Monday to charges in 
one of three indictments stemming from Operation Casablanca. 
</P>
<P>
	Victor Manuel Alcala Navarro pleaded guilty 28 times through a  
Spanish interpreter, an admission prosecutors said would bring him 
no special treatment 
</P>
<P>
	``The most important thing is he is not cooperating with the  
government,'' defense attorney Victor Sherman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Alcala Navarro still faces two other federal indictments in  
Operation Casablanca, which snared officials of three of Mexico's 
largest banks in a sting by U.S. Customs agents. 
</P>
<P>
	Alcala Navarro, 36, admitted to introducing bankers to the U.S.  
agents he thought were operatives of the powerful Cali drug cartel. 
The indictment alleged that about $70 million was laundered through 
Mexican banks and sent to the United States under the direction of 
Alcala Navarro. 
</P>
<P>
	The 28 counts that Alcala Navarro admitted to were only a  
fraction of the 106 charges lodged against him in the indictment. 
The government agreed to drop the rest. 
</P>
<P>
	Each count carries a possible maximum sentence of 20 years in  
prison, although Sherman said he expects Alcala Navarro to draw a 
sentence of about 32 years. Charges in the other two indictments 
could result in terms of life imprisonment without possibility of 
parole. 
</P>
<P>
	Sentencing was scheduled for June 28.  
</P>
<P>
	The Casablanca case raised tensions between Mexico and the  
United States last spring when U.S. law enforcement agents arrested 
167 people including top Mexican bankers and executives. Mexico 
accused the United States of intruding on Mexican sovereignty by 
conducting its sting operation without its involvement. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of Mexico's most prominent banks -- Bancomer, Banca Serfin  
and Confia -- were charged in the case. The indicted banks have 
denied any wrongdoing, saying the illegal activity was committed by 
rogue employees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
