<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls on Profit-Taking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell against the yen and the euro  
Monday as profit-takers stepped in and sent the U.S. currency lower 
following a week of gains. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 121.66  
Japanese yen, down from 122.80 yen on Friday. The euro was quoted 
at $1.0886, up from $1.0835. 
</P>
<P>
	A week ago Monday, the dollar was worth 119.76, ending the week  
at 122.80. The euro hit a series of new lows against the dollar 
last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar's rally continued Monday as trading resumed in Asia.  
But investors lost faith as the rally faltered and turned to taking 
profits. 
</P>
<P>
	``I returned from lunch and wondered what happened,'' said  
Hajime Sato, assistant general manager of the treasury department 
at Daiwa International Trust Bank in Tokyo. ``Apparently, after the 
dollar failed to touch 123.20 yen, players started profit-taking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar ended lower against the yen and the euro in Asian  
trading, then tried to resume its climb during London trading as 
bargain hunters stepped in. But the dollar resumed its slide during 
European trading and never recovered. 
</P>
<P>
	``By the time we came in, the damage was done,'' John Beerling,  
chief foreign exchange dealer at Norwest Bank Corp. in Minneapolis, 
said about the role of North American traders Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4627 Swiss francs, down from  
1.4707, and 1.5156 Canadian dollars, down from 1.5199. The British 
pound rose to $1.6080, up from $1.6064. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the countries participating in the euro no longer  
are traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Monday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.7966 German 
marks, down from 1.8051; 6.0241 French francs, down from 6.0533; 
and Italian lire, 1,779.36, down from 1,785.71. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
