<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tenn. Trying To Lure Car Racing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- A bill that could eventually help lure  
NASCAR's Winston Cup racing series back to Middle Tennessee sailed 
through the state House and Senate on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill passed 97-0 in the House and 29-0 in the Senate, and  
goes to Gov. Don Sundquist for his signature. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill lets the Wilson County Sports Authority issue bonds for  
infrastructure improvements at a proposed $125 million 
superspeedway complex near Lebanon, about 30 miles east of 
Nashville. 
</P>
<P>
	Dover Downs Entertainment Inc., owner of the Dover Downs  
International Speedway in Delaware, where two Winston Cup races are 
run each season, proposes to build the new track. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill allows the Wilson County sports authority to use  
increases in tax revenue to pay off the bonds over 30 years. After 
that the tax income reverts to the state and local governments. 
</P>
<P>
	The authority is expected to issue about $20 million in bonds,  
according to Barry Brooke, vice president of project developer 
Lawler-Wood LLC. The money can be used only for public improvements 
such as roads and sewerage. 
</P>
<P>
	The initial project is proposed to be a 1.33-mile oval  
superspeedway with 50,000 seats. Brooke said NASCAR's Busch, 
Craftsman Truck and ARCA series are expected to race at the track 
when it opens, projected for early 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Dover Downs officials are hopeful NASCAR will eventually  
put a Winston Cup series race back in Middle Tennessee. Nashville 
was on the tour, with two races, until 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooke said Dover Downs also is pursuing an Indy Racing League  
event. The IRL debuted in 1998 at the track in Delaware, where it 
has a three-year contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooke said the speedway complex in Tennessee will be expanded  
to include a short track, probably five-eighths of a mile, to 
replace the current Nashville Speedway. He said it could eventually 
include a dirt track and drag strip as well, depending on demand. 
</P>
<P>
	He said developers hope to start construction this summer. A  
lawsuit pending in Wilson County challenges the rezoning of 1,200 
acres where the speedway is to be built. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 19:32:07 </DATE_TIME>
