<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Diamondbacks' Womack Out Six Weeks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Newly acquired Tony Womack, who didn't want to be  
with the Arizona Diamondbacks, will be out six weeks because of a 
broken wrist. 
</P>
<P>
	X-rays confirmed Womack broke his right wrist when he was hit by  
a pitch Chicago White Sox pitcher Jim Parque on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The arm was placed in a cast, but Womack will participate in  
conditioning drills and a smaller cast may be placed on the arm in 
a week or two, manager Buck Showalter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Womack was slated to play left field, with Steve Finley in  
center and Luis Gonzalez in right. With Womack out, Arizona could 
move Gonzalez back to left, depending on who takes over temporarily 
for Womack. Showalter's options include David Dellucci, Bernard 
Gilkey, Pete Incaviglia and Andy Fox. 
</P>
<P>
	Womack, the NL's leader in stolen bases the last two seasons,  
was acquired last month from Pittsburgh. A player yet to be 
identified is to be sent to the Pirates as part of that deal. 
</P>
<P>
	It's been a rough start for Womack since he came to Arizona.  
First, he was unhappy with being moved from second base to the 
outfield, then the injury occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	Womack was set to be Arizona's leadoff hitter. Showalter likely  
will use several players, including Finley and Gonzalez, in that 
role until Womack returns. 
</P>
<P>
	If Womack is back in six weeks, he would miss the first 2 1/2 weeks  
of the season. Arizona plays its season opener April 5 at Los 
Angeles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
