<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EG&AMP;G To Buy Unit of Perkin-Elmer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WELLESLEY, Mass. (AP) -- EG&AMP;G Inc., a maker of medical and  
security screening instruments, announced Monday it plans to buy 
Perkin-Elmer's Analytical Instruments Division for $425 million. 
</P>
<P>
	EG&AMP;G also said it has hired Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. to investigate  
alternatives for its Technical Services unit, which supplies 
support service to government agencies, including chemical-weapons 
disposal for the Defense Department. 
</P>
<P>
	EG&AMP;G, based in Wellesley, is a technology company providing  
products and systems to medical, aerospace, telecommunications, 
semiconductor, photographic and other industries. The company has 
approximately 13,000 employees worldwide and had sales last year of 
$1.4 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Perkin-Elmer's Analytical Instruments Division, based in  
Norwalk, Conn., develops, manufactures and sells life science 
systems and analytical instruments used for such things as ensuring 
the purity of food and water and the uniformity of drugs and 
medicines. The company, which has about 3,100 employees, had 1998 
sales of $569 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition is expected to be completed in the second  
quarter, pending regulatory approval. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today's actions will greatly accelerate our efforts to focus  
on high-growth electronics, aerospace and life sciences business,'' 
said Gregory L. Summe, EG&AMP;G president and chief executive officer. 

</P>
</TEXT>
