<DOCNO> APW19990308.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 05:31:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Futuristic Olympic Torch Revealed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- The curve of a boomerang and the peaks  
of the Sydney Opera House have been combined to create the 2000 
Games' futuristic blue, silver and white Olympic Torch. 
</P>
<P>
	But Monday's unveiling of the torch provoked complaints from  
many news organizations over why Rupert Murdoch's News Ltd. 
newspapers got advance photos and publicity on the new design to 
display in Monday morning editions. 
</P>
<P>
	New South Wales state Olympics Minister Michael Knight said the  
presentation of the new torch was not a news event, and therefore 
could be offered as an exclusive to News Ltd., a major games 
sponsor. 
</P>
<P>
	SOCOG chief executive Sandy Hollway agreed with Knight, saying  
the torch announcement was not news. 
</P>
<P>
	The torch will be carried by 10,000 Australians on a 100-day,  
16,800-mile journey throughout the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	Passing through almost 1,000 towns and communities, the torch  
will travel within an hour's drive of 85 percent of Australia's 
population, to complete its journey at Stadium Australia on Sept. 
15, when it will light the Sydney 2000 flame. 
</P>
<P>
	A fresh torch will be used for each of the 10,000 relay legs,  
and bearers will be able to buy the torch they carry for 300 
Australian dollars ($185 U.S.), the newspaper reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Weighing 2.2 pounds and made of stainless steel, anodized  
aluminum and textured aluminum, each layer of the 28-inch high 
torch represents fire, water and earth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 12:44:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Corn, Soybeans Close Higher / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain futures and soybeans closed higher in  
trading Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Grain futures were driven higher as market participants were  
buying back positions ahead of Thursday's U.S. Agriculture 
Department crop production report, which is expected to show 
increased South American output. Grains were also supported by 
predictions of a snow storm that is expected to limit movement of 
grains in the central United States, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures closed mostly higher but gave back much of their  
early gains. Wheat was supported by feelings among market 
participants that recent price downturns were overdone, analysts 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat also received a boost from talk of dry weather in U.S.  
growing areas and news that Pakistan is in the market for either 
U.S., Australian or Canadian wheat. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean futures were sharply higher, receiving support from mild  
export business and a rallying soy oil market. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn was also sharply higher as market participants bought back  
into the market. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for May delivery was up 2 1/4 cents at $2.70 a bushel; May  
corn was 4 3/4 cents higher at $2.20 3/4; May oats were up 1 cent at 
$1.06 1/2 a bushel; May soybeans were up 6 1/2 cents to $4.71 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Live cattle and feeder cattle were mostly higher in trading on  
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange Monday, while lean hogs were mixed 
and pork bellies higher. 
</P>
<P>
	April live cattle was up 0.65 cent to 68.42 cents a pound; March  
feeder cattle rose 0.22 cent to 72.67 cents a pound; April lean 
hogs were off .25 cent to 42.57 cents a pound; March pork bellies 
rose .30 cents to 50.37 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
