<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Diet Guidelines May Add Food Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration urged a federal  
panel Monday to add food safety tips to the widely-used dietary 
guidelines, saying that after years of advising Americans on what 
to eat, it is time to teach them how to handle their food. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe the time has come to include food safety in the  
guidelines,'' said Catherine Woteki, the Agriculture Department's 
undersecretary for food safety. ``Government has an obligation to 
help people protect themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Woteki's comments came during a meeting of an advisory committee  
reviewing the ``Dietary Guidelines for Americans.'' The guidelines, 
last altered in 1995, are reviewed every five years for changes. 
The panel will issue a report later this year with revisions for 
2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The guidelines include advice such as choosing a diet with  
plenty of grain products, vegetables and fruits as well as eating a 
diet low in fat, saturated fat and cholesterol. 
</P>
<P>
	The guidelines have never included food safety information, but  
times and dangers have changed since the early 1980s when the 
guidelines began, Woteki said. She declined to recommend particular 
guidelines but said they might include advice on appropriate 
temperatures to store food or how to avoid mixing raw chicken with 
vegetables. 
</P>
<P>
	``Food safety is a critical factor in any discussion about diet  
and long-term health,'' Woteki said. ``New pathogens have emerged 
just in the last decade.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just in the last few months, consumers have witnessed numerous  
recalls of food products due to contamination with the bacteria, 
listera monocytogenes. A large recall in December by the Bil Mar 
Foods plant in Zeeland, Mich., has even been linked to an outbreak 
that has resulted in at least 14 deaths, six miscarriages and 97 
illnesses across the country. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration already has support among some nutritionists,  
including the American Dietetic Association. ``Given the scope of 
consumer concerns about food safety, ADA urges the committee to 
consider adding food safety messages in an informative but not 
alarming way,'' Kathryn M. Carroll, senior nutrition scientist for 
the ADA, told the panel. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Cutberto Garza, who serves as chairman of the advisory  
panel, said the committee would take the request ``very 
seriously.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Food-borne illnesses cost society between $6.6 billion and $37  
billion annually in medical costs and lost productivity, Woteki 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are food-borne illnesses associated with virtually every  
category of food,'' Woteki said, noting that while meat and poultry 
are the largest contributors, other foods also carry pathogens. 
</P>
<P>
	``Education is a very important component in this strategy,''  
she said. ``Consumers need to know what they can do to protect 
themselves.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
