<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Joe DiMaggio Dies  
</P>
<P>
	HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) -- Baseball Hall of Famer Joe DiMaggio died  
today at age 84. The former New York Yankees star, whose 56-game 
hitting streak is one of the most enduring records in baseball, had 
lung cancer surgery last October and had several postoperative 
infections that nearly killed him. Morris Engelberg, DiMaggio's 
long-time friend and attorney, said the star centerfielder died at 
his home shortly after midnight. DiMaggio's hospital stay was 
marred by several premature reports of his death, including a TV 
bulletin he watched announcing his demise. He was discharged from a 
hospital in January and doctors said he was making great progress. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Visiting Central America  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton embarks today on his  
four-day, four-nation mission to Central America just as 15,000 
Guatemalans and Salvadorans illegally in the United States become 
eligible for deportation. Clinton turned down pleas for an 
extension of the halt in deportations that was instituted after the 
devastation of Hurricane Mitch last fall. Clinton will start with a 
survey of damage done by Hurricane Mitch to a Nicaraguan town. The 
president will see the spot where last October a mudslide swept 
away a pair of villages, killing about 2,000 people. 

</P>
<P>
	Lewinsky Mobbed at Book Store  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Overwhelmed by the crush of media attention,  
Monica Lewinsky today temporarily fled the first stop on her 
two-week book tour of Britain after signing only a few copies of 
``Monica's Story.'' Ms. Lewinsky seemed unprepared for the hundreds 
of photographers yelling and shouting her name in the book 
department of the landmark London department store Harrods. ``I 
said to her `Welcome and good luck' but she was shaking. She was so 
scared, the poor girl,'' said Frankie Ruberg, a customer who passed 
Ms. Lewinsky as she made her way to the signing area. The 90-minute 
signing session resumed after the news media were herded out of the 
room. 

</P>
<P>
	US, EU Face Off on Banana Trade  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- The United States and the European Union today  
presented their arguments before the World Trade Organization about 
the growing battle over a trade dispute involving bananas. The EU 
is complaining about proposed U.S. tariffs on some imported 
European goods. But U.S. officials say the sanctions are designed 
to try and change import policies that American banana sellers say 
squeeze them out of the European market. The WTO today summoned all 
of its 134 member countries to investigate the dispute. 

</P>
<P>
	Hezbollah: No Truce in S. Lebanon  
</P>
<P>
	BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Hezbollah will not accept any temporary  
truce in south Lebanon during the run-up to Israel's May 17 
elections, the Shiite Muslim group's leader was quoted today as 
saying. Sheik Hassan Nasrallah also told the leftist As-Safir 
newspaper that Hezbollah would not go along with any amendments to 
a 1996 U.S.-brokered understanding barring Israel and Lebanese 
guerrillas from attacking civilian areas or launching attacks from 
them. The hard-line Hezbollah stance came amid reports that Martin 
Indyk, a U.S. assistant secretary of state, would visit Lebanon 
this week for talks. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Marks 50th Anniversary  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- NATO officials are marking today the 50th  
anniversary of the foundation of the Western military alliance, 
which is about to admit its first former East bloc members. 
Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republic will be welcomed at a 
ceremony in Washington in April. Defense or foreign ministers from 
some founder-member states of the U.S.-led alliance will mingle 
with representatives from soon-to-be members starting today for a 
three-day conference at London's Royal Institute for Strategic 
Studies. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: Birth Pain Payments Halted  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The federal government has ordered doctors and  
hospitals to stop demanding cash payments from poor women for the 
epidural injection to relieve pain in childbirth, The New York 
Times reported today. Medicaid patients may not be charged for some 
medical services related to pregnancy and Medicaid reimburses 
doctors and hospitals. But doctors say the reimbursements for pain 
relief treatment are woefully small. Patients unable to pay cash 
for the epidural injection, which blocks pain in the lower part of 
the body, often were offered weaker forms of pain relief. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stock Prices Fall  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell today on worries that a rise in  
the yen against the dollar could erode profits for Japanese 
companies. The Nikkei shed 114.95 points to close at 14,779.05. 

</P>
<P>
	Duke Finishes Season at No. 1  
</P>
<P>
	DURHAM, N.C. (AP) -- Duke, Michigan State, Connecticut and  
Auburn, the top four seeds in the NCAA tournament, finished in that 
order today in the final AP college basketball poll of the season. 
It was the third No. 1 finish for the Blue Devils (32-1), who 
entered the NCAA tournament on top of the rankings in 1986 and 
1992. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
</P>
</TEXT>
