<DOCNO> APW19990308.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 14:26:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DiMaggio Wasn't Fond of Lyric </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) -- Simon &AMP; Garfunkel could sing what  
they wanted, but Joe DiMaggio didn't especially like it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know why they said that. Where did they think I've  
gone? I'm right here,'' DiMaggio would say when someone played 
``Mrs. Robinson'' on the jukebox at The Irish Pub. 
</P>
<P>
	``But he understood it was the America he represented and the  
sport he represented, that it was Joe DiMaggio as a metaphor,'' 
said Cathy Burke, co-owner of the pub and a longtime DiMaggio 
friend. 
</P>
<P>
	Burke and her husband Richard, who met DiMaggio through a mutual  
friend 15 years ago, frequently hosted him in their New York and 
Atlantic City apartments. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Burke recalled DiMaggio as gracious, thoughtful and  
respectful of the fans who loved him. 
</P>
<P>
	``He felt a responsibility to the public because he was Joe  
DiMaggio,'' she said Monday. ``People looked up to him and he would 
never do anything he felt would hurt his public. We've been with 
him so many times when people would ask for autographs or say 
hello. I've never seen him decline, even though there were times 
people really overstepped the line. 
</P>
<P>
	``One time, at dinner, someone came up to him with 12 baseballs.  
He sat and he signed every one of them,'' Mrs. Burke said. 
</P>
<P>
	On his visits to New York, DiMaggio would stay at the couple's  
Fifth Avenue co-op. 
</P>
<P>
	Last April, the three were planning a quiet evening to celebrate  
Mrs. Burke's birthday when the telephone rang. It was Woody Allen's 
assistant, saying Allen wanted to take DiMaggio out to dinner. 
Deferential to his hosts, DiMaggio said no. He had plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Then Allen's assistant called back. Would they all like to go  
out to dinner? DiMaggio asked Mrs. Burke, she said yes, and all 
three joined Allen, Soon-Yi Previn and two other friends for dinner 
at Elaine's, the trendy Manhattan bistro. 
</P>
<P>
	When DiMaggio came to Atlantic City for an autograph show or a  
boxing match he would stay in the Burkes' apartment above the Pub, 
eating homemade chicken soup with garbanzo beans and drinking root 
beer. 
</P>
<P>
	``He loved Atlantic City. He liked to go up on the Boardwalk and  
he loved the fights,'' Mrs. Burke said. 
</P>
<P>
	There was the time that Mrs. Burke, walking through the Pub's  
dining room, overheard a group of fans arguing about who was 
baseball's greatest player. ``I heard one of them say, `If I ever 
met Joe DiMaggio, I would faint dead away.' Well, Joe was upstairs 
at the time. I just couldn't resist the moment,'' Mrs. Burke said. 
</P>
<P>
	She led the five upstairs without telling them why, then told  
them to wait in an anteroom. After clearing it with DiMaggio, she 
brought them into the apartment, where DiMaggio sat watching a John 
Wayne movie. 
</P>
<P>
	``You should've seen the looks on their faces,'' Mrs. Burke  
said. He sat with them for 45 minutes, just talking. It was vintage 
DiMaggio. 
</P>
<P>
	Then there was the time a group of MTV producers in their 20s  
and 30s were in town in 1989 and DiMaggio happened to be in the 
Pub. ``They said, `Mr. DiMaggio, can we take your picture?' This is 
the greatest honor we've ever had.' Despite their age, they 
responded to him like they would to a rock star,'' Mrs. Burke said. 
</P>
<P>
	Early Monday, Mrs. Burke got a telephone call from a DiMaggio  
friend in Florida. Joltin' Joe had -- finally -- left and gone away. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're devastated,'' Mrs. Burke said, wiping away tears. ``The  
country has lost a hero, but it's a great personal loss, too. We 
knew he was ill, but it's always too soon. It's always too soon.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 14:16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Johnson Returns to Orioles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- As he looked across the diamond at  
the team he took to the playoffs in successive seasons, Davey 
Johnson couldn't help thinking what might have been. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, who resigned as the Baltimore Orioles manager during a  
feud with owner Peter Angelos after the 1997 season, greeted his 
former players and coaches with handshakes and hugs Monday in his 
new role as manager of the Los Angeles Dodgers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not just another game. I have sentimental feelings about  
today,'' he said before the teams played an exhibition game. 
</P>
<P>
	Dressed in Dodger Blue, Johnson said he experienced ``mixed  
emotions'' at seeing the Orioles for the first time since his 
departure in November 1997 after two straight appearances in the AL 
championship series. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's where I learned to play the game, in the city of  
Baltimore,'' he said. ``I had a lot of friends there. I thought 
they had a chance to do something special last year, take it a step 
further. It didn't give me any satisfaction at all seeing them have 
a rough season last year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, who broke into the majors as a second baseman with  
Baltimore, took what he described at the time as his ``dream job'' 
when he became manager of the Orioles. He took the Orioles to the 
AL championship series in 1996 and 1997, but Baltimore never made 
it to the World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles lost to the New York Yankees in the '96 playoffs, a  
series best remembered for a play in which a young fan reached over 
the wall at Yankee Stadium to take away a certain catch from 
outfielder Tony Tarasco. The Cleveland Indians eliminated the 
Orioles the following year when Tony Fernandez homered off Armando 
Benitez in Game 6. 
</P>
<P>
	A few weeks after that, Johnson sent a fax to Angelos asking for  
a contract extension and threatened to resign if the situation 
wasn't rectified. On the day Johnson was voted AL manager of the 
year, Angelos accepted the resignation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I only have good feelings about my time with the Orioles,''  
Johnson said. ``Mr. Angelos brought me back there, and for that I 
will be forever indebted. I know what he expected; we just fell 
short. Who knows? If that 12-year-old didn't reach over the wall 
and Benitez didn't hang a slider, I might still be over there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson spent last season as an assistant in Japan, watching  
baseball on TV and playing golf. The Orioles, meanwhile, didn't 
even reach .500 under manager Ray Miller, Johnson's pitching coach 
in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``I called him the day he resigned and tried to talk him out of  
it,'' Miller said. ``I think he's arguably the best in the game if 
you want to go by winning percentage. He deserves all the 
accolades. I have a lot of respect for him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson gladly gave up the life of leisure when Dodgers general  
manager Kevin Malone, the Orioles' assistant GM during Johnson's 
reign, hired him to manage in Los Angeles. Malone was also at 
Monday's game, which the Orioles won 10-0. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't as bad as it looked,'' Johnson said with a sheepish  
grin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 15:31:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Gwynn's Hit Parade Nears 3,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PEORIA, Ariz. (AP) -- If Tony Gwynn could script his 3,000th hit,  
it would come at home in front of a packed house. Camera flashes 
would be going off all over the stadium, sort of like when Mark 
McGwire and Sammy Sosa stepped to the plate last season. 
</P>
<P>
	The only difference is, Gwynn wants the ball to stay in the  
yard. He wants to get it back and doesn't want to have to pay for 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	He'd be more than content with a nice little grounder to his  
favorite spot -- between shortstop and third base, or the ``5.5 
hole,'' as he calls it. 
</P>
<P>
	``A base hit for me would be, I think, textbook, because it's  
what I've done pretty much through my whole career,'' said the San 
Diego Padres batting star, who enters the season 72 hits from the 
milestone. 
</P>
<P>
	Going the opposite way means the left-hander is dialed in, which  
he wasn't for a good deal of 1998. He still hit .321, an average 
that most major leaguers would kill for, but it was the first time 
in six seasons that he hit lower than .353. And it was a dropoff of 
51 points from 1997, when he hit .372 to win his fourth straight NL 
batting title, and eighth overall. 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn went through a couple of 0-for-14 slumps, tying the worst  
of his career, then saw one drag on to 0-for-19. Just as he was 
pulling out of an 8-for-52 slump, he went on the disabled list with 
an Achilles' injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was inconsistent last year,'' Gwynn said. ``There were  
periods when my mechanics were just terrible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	How does a guy who's topped .300 for 16 straight seasons  
struggle? 
</P>
<P>
	``I tell you what, I did not know,'' said Gwynn, a lifetime .339  
hitter who suffered along with the rest of the Padres' offense for 
most of the year, relying on the pitching staff to help carry the 
team to the World Series. ``We would be wracking our brains 
wondering what the hell was going on. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't care how many years you hit .300, how many things  
you've done on the offensive end, if you're in the middle of the 
rut, it's hard, man, it's hard to get out because you just don't 
think you can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn finally did in the World Series, but by then, he was one  
of the few Padres on his game. He hit .500, going 8-for-16, and 
homered off David Wells in the opener at Yankee Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was really the best run I had of the last two months,''  
Gwynn said. ``So the postseason did a lot for my confidence, 
because I was doing exactly what I wanted to do. They came in, I'd 
let it go. If they were going away, I'd carve it to left. I hope I 
can back to doing that. But mentally, man, I was beat up at the 
end. I couldn't understand why I was sucking gas like I was.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Batting coach Merv Rettenmund said Gwynn pulled the ball a lot  
in batting practice last year instead of hitting it crisply to 
left. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was not one of his most consistent years here,''  
Rettenmund said. ``That's tough to say when someone hits whatever 
he hits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn turns 39 on May 9, a few weeks before he hopes to get his  
3,000th hit. He said he worked hard during the winter, watching 
tape, hitting in the cage, hitting off a tee. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was unbelievable,'' Rettenmund said. ``He hit every day. I  
bet he hit twice on some days. There's no one who hits 300, 320 
days a year. That's why he's what he is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And there's a reason Gwynn swings for that spot between third  
and short. 
</P>
<P>
	``Early on in my career, I could run, I could really run,'' he  
said. ``I knew if I could make that shortstop go in that hole to 
get it, he couldn't throw me out. And then as I got older, it was 
like hey, I've got to get it through.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn has a little patch with ``5.5 hole'' sewn on the tongue of  
his shoes. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I've stepped up to the plate, I've had catchers say `Hey,  
T, what's the 5.5 hole?' and I say, `Hold on a few minutes and 
you'll see.' That's where I made my living, on the left side. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still have it put on my shoes, but last year I just  
completely got away from it. I didn't execute. This spring I'm 
trying to get back to doing that.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 10:20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FTC, Intel Reach Proposed Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Intel Corp. and the Federal Trade Commission  
said today they have agreed to a proposed settlement over 
government charges that the nation's largest computer chipmaker 
illegally bullied three other companies into handing over secret 
information about their products. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel and the FTC announced the settlement on the eve of the  
company's antitrust hearing before an administrative law judge in 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The company and the FTC jointly filed a motion to withdraw the  
government charges that were filed June 8, said FTC spokeswoman 
Michelle Muth. She could not discuss details of the settlement, 
which must be approved by commissioners. 
</P>
<P>
	That approval is expected within two weeks. It would be highly  
unusual for commissioners to reject a recommended settlement from 
the agency's own Bureau of Competition. They could approve the 
settlement during a formal meeting or they could circulate it for 
signatures. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel also declined to talk about the settlement's contents.  
</P>
<P>
	The FTC's statement described ``remaining issues under  
investigation,'' a veiled reference to what's widely believed to be 
a much broader antitrust probe of Intel's business behavior in the 
nation's technology industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``We continue to cooperate with them on that as they continue to  
request documents,'' Intel spokesman Chuck Mulloy said, adding that 
the pending settlement agreement was related only to the June 8 
lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency said its lawyers were ``committed to working  
expeditiously to resolve those concerns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a much broader case the FTC can bring and may bring in  
the future,'' said Steve Newborn, a Washington lawyer who 
represents some of Intel's competitors and has argued for a broader 
lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Newborn said he wasn't surprised to see the settlement proposed,  
citing the Justice Department's ongoing antitrust case against 
Microsoft Corp., which has faced embarrassing disclosures in the 
courtroom from its internal e-mails and from testimony by some of 
its own executives. 
</P>
<P>
	``They saw what's happened to Microsoft and they didn't want to  
go through that,'' Newborn said. ``I've never thought Intel was 
stupid enough to go to trial in this case. On a simple cost-benefit 
analysis, there was no reason for Intel to be fighting this 
fight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the news, Intel stock jumped 3.5 percent, rising $4 to  
$118.62 1/2 a share this morning on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel and the FTC signed the settlement proposal Sunday  
afternoon after telephone negotiations led by Peter Detkin, the 
company's assistant general counsel. 
</P>
<P>
	``The opposition's case has become more and more apparent to the  
other side,'' Mulloy said. ``A few weeks ago, it became apparent 
there was an opening there for discussion, things started falling 
into place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Intel, the world's largest manufacturer of microprocessors, had  
already acknowledged it did most of what the FTC alleged, but the 
company claimed that those actions were not illegal and that its 
business practices had not ``chilled'' innovation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We view this compromise agreement as a 'win-win' for both  
parties and we are satisfied that the agreement gives us value for 
our intellectual property rights. This is acceptable to both 
parties and was the result of constructive dialogue between Intel 
and the FTC,'' said Craig Barrett, president and chief executive 
officer of Intel. 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC had alleged that Intel illegally withheld from three  
companies advanced technical information about its upcoming 
microprocessors to ``extort'' valuable technology that the 
companies had developed independently. 
</P>
<P>
	It called the company's actions ``a raw exercise of monopoly  
power to muscle competitors into signing over intellectual property 
rights.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Intel contended it is legal for the company to decide what  
secrets to disclose to its customers about its upcoming products. 
The company makes processors for more than 80 percent of the 
world's computers and recently introduced its fastest chip ever, 
the Pentium III. 
</P>
<P>
	The three companies allegedly bullied by Intel were Digital  
Equipment Corp., Intergraph Corp. and Compaq Computer Corp., which 
now owns Digital. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokeswoman for Intergraph, Aggie Frizzell, said the company's  
executives were meeting today with FTC lawyers to discuss the 
proposed settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the legal issues in Intel's case were narrow, the FTC  
faced problems winning the case. 
</P>
<P>
	It filed its lawsuit during a period of unprecedented  
competition facing Intel from rival chipmakers, such as from 
Advanced Micro Devices Inc. and National Semiconductor Corp. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 15:31:02 </DATE_TIME>
