<HEADLINE> Yankee Pettitte's Injury Is Mild </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Andy Pettitte's injury is only a mild muscle  
strain, the New York Yankees learned Monday after tests showed no 
serious problems with the pitcher's left elbow. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never thought it was anything serious,'' Pettitte said. ``I  
was aggravated because I knew they would shut me down. It will be a 
long week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pettitte, the only left-hander in the Yankees' starting  
rotation, threw seven pitches in the first inning of Sunday's game 
against Minnesota, then left the game after throwing three warmup 
pitches prior to the second inning. 
</P>
<P>
	He first reported elbow tenderness Feb. 22 after a bullpen  
session and missed his first scheduled batting practice session. 
He's optimistic he'll be ready by opening day. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you could project, you would say he will probably be  
ready,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said. ``Hopefully he'll be all 
right. We won't know until he pitches. If he's not ready for the 
opener, the most important thing is to get him back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pettitte knows he has some catching up to do.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'll be behind, but I'll be ready by the season,'' he said.  
``There's plenty of time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hideki Irabu, whose bullpen session Sunday was cut short by  
stiffness in his upper left back, reported improvement and will 
make his scheduled start Wednesday against Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel better. I didn't think it's was an injury,'' Irabu said  
through interpreter George Rose. ``It's just tightness from 
throwing for the first time. I'm pretty confident I can do what 
they want me to do.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
