<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Weighs Secret Vote on Samaranch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- While the outcome is not in doubt, big questions  
remain over how the IOC will conduct a crucial confidence vote next 
week on president Juan Antonio Samaranch. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials of the International Olympic Committee are undecided  
whether to have a secret ballot or public acclamation on whether 
Samaranch should remain in office. 
</P>
<P>
	An endorsement of the 78-year-old Spaniard is assured. But with  
the world closely watching every move the IOC makes in the wake of 
its biggest corruption scandal, officials expect the committee will 
be criticized no matter what procedure is used. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC's executive board is expected to decide by midweek on  
what action to take against 19 members who remain under 
investigation in the Salt Lake bribery case, the head of the 
inquiry said. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC vice president Dick Pound said in New York that his  
investigation panel would hold a conference call Tuesday in hopes 
of bringing ``substantial closure'' to the review, then send its 
recommendations to the executive board in a second conference call 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Pounds said his commission had reached a decision on all cases  
but one. He refused to identify the member involved or say what 
actions the panel would recommend on any of the alleged offenses. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch, who has faced calls for his resignation from critics  
outside the IOC, announced in January that he would put his 
leadership to a vote of confidence at a special general assembly in 
Switzerland on March 17-18. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on numerous interviews over the past month, it's clear  
that Samaranch has overwhelming support among IOC members to 
continue in office. 
</P>
<P>
	The confidence motion, however, is not listed on the 10-point  
agenda for next week's meeting, where the assembly will vote on 
reform proposals and expulsion of members involved in the Salt Lake 
City bribery scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC members told The Associated Press that the confidence  
question is still being debated among the general membership and 
the leadership. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch has been canvassing the opinions of IOC members and is  
expected to settle on a formula later this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Executive board member Jacques Rogge said members are divided  
into those who favor a secret ballot and those who prefer a round 
of applause or show of hands. 
</P>
<P>
	``What counts is not the system,'' he said. ``What counts is  
whether (Samaranch) can have broad support, and I believe he 
will.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rogge said neither of the proposed vote solutions would appease  
the IOC's critics. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the formula discussed by those seeking a public  
endorsement, Samaranch would give an opening statement to the 
assembly. The IOC's longest-serving member, Joao Havelange of 
Brazil, would then take the floor and ask the members to acclaim 
Samaranch by applause. 
</P>
<P>
	A secret ballot might be more democratic because it allows  
members to vote free of outside pressure. But it could also be seen 
as lacking accountability, especially at a time when the IOC is 
being urged to become more open. 
</P>
<P>
	A vote by acclamation could also be viewed as undemocratic, with  
members under pressure to side publicly with the majority in favor 
of Samaranch. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whatever we do, we will be criticized,'' Rogge said. ``If we  
have a secret ballot, people will say it should be public. If we 
have it public, people will say we should have had a secret 
ballot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rogge noted that when a government or prime minister asks for a  
confidence vote, a public ballot is held. 
</P>
<P>
	``To those who say it should be a secret ballot, I say that the  
impeachment vote of President Clinton, basically a vote of 
confidence, was a public vote,'' Rogge said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rogge said he prefers a secret ballot. But he said the ultimate  
decision should not be made to appease others. 
</P>
<P>
	``The vote of confidence is not a sign to the outside world,''  
he said. ``It's for Samaranch to know if he has the support of his 
own members. I believe there will be overwhelming support.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If the IOC does hold a secret ballot, a dozen or so members  
might vote against Samaranch, according to one delegate who spoke 
on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch, elected as IOC president in 1980, has not faced a  
contest since, re-elected three times by acclamation. In 1995, the 
IOC voted to raise its retirement age to 80 to allow Samaranch 
another term through 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the Salt Lake scandal broke late last year, the IOC  
counted 114 members. But fewer than 100 members will be eligible to 
vote at next week's session. 
</P>
<P>
	Four members have resigned and five others face expulsion and  
are ineligible to vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine new members, appointed at last year's Nagano Games, have  
not been invited to next week's extraordinary session. They are due 
to be sworn in officially at the next regular session, scheduled 
for June. 
</P>
<P>
	The 19 other members under investigation face expulsion, warning  
or exoneration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
