<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 00:12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AN AMERICAN PORTRAIT: Pete Vonachen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PEORIA, Ill. (AP) -- For some baseball fans, spring training is  
the start of the season. Time to scan split-squad scores in Florida 
and Arizona, read season previews in the sports pages, watch for 
trades. 
</P>
<P>
	For Pete Vonachen, co-owner of the Peoria Chiefs, a Class A farm  
team for the St. Louis Cardinals, spring training is the start of 
the best time of the year. Time for welcoming sunshine, eating hot 
dogs, talking baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	To the 73-year-old Vonachen, owning a team isn't about money or  
glory. Sometimes, it's not even about the game; his seat, just a 
few rows behind home plate in the stadium that bears his name, is 
usually empty. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, he's shaking hands and greeting folks. Or he's over by  
the press box introducing a TV reporter to the young woman who sang 
the national anthem. Or he's standing with his arms crossed, 
harrumphing about lousy pitching. ``Used to be, I'd even collect 
the tickets,'' Vonachen says. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball season gives the dreamy-eyed Vonachen, stocked with  
stories and jokes, the chance to do what he does best: meet people 
and have fun. 
</P>
<P>
	For all his love of baseball, Vonachen's knack is not for the  
business side of things -- just as when he owned the hotel, the 
restaurant, the blacktop company. 
</P>
<P>
	``He owned the restaurant, and I can guarantee Pete can't make a  
pot of coffee. He owned that blacktop company, and he didn't know a 
thing about black-topping,'' says state Sen. George Shadid, a 
Democrat from nearby Pekin who counts himself among Vonachen's 
friends. 
</P>
<P>
	``He did know about baseball. But I don't know where he learned  
it, because he's not an athlete by any means.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vonachen was due in Jupiter, Fla., to scout players under  
contract with the Cardinals and assess his roster for this season. 
He expected to watch the pre-season opener against the Los Angeles 
Dodgers in Vero Beach, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	``Oh, it'll be fun. That's what it's all about,'' he says of the  
season's start. ``Talk to the manager, the coaches. Go out to 
dinner. Make a social event out of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Spend time with Vonachen, and you realize he can turn anything --  
even taking tickets at the gate -- into a social event. As the 
Chiefs took on Indiana's Fort Wayne Wizards in the playoffs during 
a cool night last September, Vonachen was greeting dozens of people 
by name and handing out baseballs to children. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've known him all my life,'' says Dick Bogard, who recently  
sold several pharmacies and retired. ``He's a promoter. He'd do 
anything for you. And he just loves this city.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vonachen agreed to buy the Midwest League team one boozy night  
in 1984 at the urging of a couple of local sports writers. The team 
was poised to leave Peoria; with Vonachen, local baseball fans 
found a savior. 
</P>
<P>
	(Since then, Vonachen sold the team, only to buy it back with  
partners a few years later.) 
</P>
<P>
	While Bogard reminisces about his tryout for the Chicago White  
Sox, a batter jacks a foul ball over the fence, sending men and 
boys scrambling. Without rising from his seat, Bogard plucks it 
from the air. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told you I was an athlete,'' he says, showing off a  
knuckle-ball grip. ``And you know, Pete never played baseball in 
school. I don't think he ever played.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vonachen can tell you where he learned baseball: hanging out  
with Harry Caray, the late broadcaster for the Chicago Cubs. ``You 
go to the games every night, and you're bound to learn something 
about the game,'' Vonachen says. ``Harry knew all those people: 
players, coaches, managers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vonachen and Caray were friends for 48 years. They met when  
Caray was in town to broadcast a basketball game at Bradley 
University, where Vonachen ran the food service. They stayed out, 
Vonachen recalls, until 4:30 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	Even up until a few years ago, says Shadid, their capacity for a  
good time was well known in Peoria. The limousine would pull up in 
front of a saloon, Caray would pop out one side, Vonachen would 
jump out the other. ``We just hit it off,'' Vonachen says. 
``Professionally, we had no ties whatsoever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands outside of Peoria heard of Vonachen, even if they  
didn't know who he was, when Caray would lean into the microphone 
at a Chicago Cubs game and say: ``And here's a big hello to my old 
friend Pete Vonachen, in Peoria.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Millions more were introduced to him through a national  
broadcast when he took the podium at Caray's memorial service a 
year ago and spoke of their friendship with love, compassion and a 
well-timed joke. 
</P>
<P>
	Vonachen wowed some of the biggest names in sport and  
entertainment. Being a friend of Caray's, he told the crowd, 
required a cast-iron stomach, endless stamina, and keeping ``your 
bags packed and your divorce lawyer on retainer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He gave another eulogy that was heard nationally in August, at  
the service for another good friend and Chicago broadcaster, Jack 
Brickhouse. 
</P>
<P>
	But Vonachen was a legend in central Illinois long before he  
went in front of the TV cameras at those funerals. ``Now everybody 
knows him ...,'' Shadid says. ``We can walk around, and people stop 
him, in Chicago, everywhere, and say, 'Hey, man, that was great.' 
'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vonachen brushes off the praise. He's just the son of a country  
doctor, he says, a third-generation guy from Peoria. Just someone 
who spoke from the heart about a best pal. 
</P>
<P>
	A boy, his cap pulled low on his head and a big fielder's glove  
dwarfing his arm, is leaning against a seat nearby, watching as the 
Chiefs' pitching gives up a two-run lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Fishing into his pocket, Vonachen pulls out a ball. With a  
``hey, kid,'' he gives it a toss, and makes another friend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
