<DOCNO> APW19990308.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 15:21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Y2K Nuclear Stand-Down Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Year 2000 computer crisis gives the United  
States and other nuclear powers a rare chance to get together and 
take their nuclear weapons off alert, a lawmaker said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	A nuclear stand-down is the only sure way to avoid a mishap on  
Jan. 1, 2000, when computers not upgraded to read the new 
millennium date could malfunction, Rep. Ed Markey, D-Mass., said at 
a Capitol Hill symposium on nuclear aspects of the so-called Y2K 
problem. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Kraig of the British American Security Information  
Council agreed that no matter what precautions are taken, 
``computer errors are by their very nature idiosyncratic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The real cure,'' he said, ``is to take the weapons off  
alert.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Experts at the symposium concurred with Pentagon assessments  
that, even in Russia, which is well behind the United States in 
correcting Y2K problems, it is highly unlikely that computer 
glitches will result in spontaneous missile launches or explosions 
in missile silos. 
</P>
<P>
	But Bruce Blair of the Brookings Institution said the Russian  
early-warning system, backed by thousands of missiles on 
hair-trigger alert, is especially susceptible to the computer bug. 
That, coupled with breakdowns in the cooling systems of 72 or 73 
deactivated Russian submarines, Blair said, raises ``the 
possibility of multiple Chernobyls.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blair said the Russian government is not ready to embrace the  
idea of a nuclear stand-down but has said it would discuss it with 
other nuclear powers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon as well is not receptive. But Pentagon spokesman  
Bryan Whitman said the military is looking at ways to prevent any 
unauthorized launch connected with Y2K problems. 
</P>
<P>
	A group of Russians is coming to Washington this month to  
discuss U.S. proposals, including one that would have Russian 
scientists set up at a special facility in Colorado during December 
and January to monitor U.S. nuclear weaponry into the new 
millennium. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy Defense Secretary John Hamre told a Senate hearing last  
month that ``our nuclear command and control system has been 
thoroughly tested and has performed superbly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A report this month by Congress's General Accounting Office,  
while faulting the Pentagon for being slow in fixing some of its 
computer systems, praised tests carried out by the North American 
Aerospace Defense Command. ``Year 2000 date rollovers worked 
properly, and NORAD officials were able to recover and continue the 
mission when testing problems occurred,'' the GAO said. 
</P>
<P>
	Speakers at the symposium urged the Nuclear Regulatory  
Commission to adopt a more assertive approach to assuring that 
nuclear power plants in this country are safe and that adequate 
backup systems will be in place. 
</P>
<P>
	David Lochbaum of the Union of Concerned Scientists alleged that  
the NRC has audited only 12 of 103 operating nuclear plants to 
assure their preparedness. The agency ``needs to change from being 
a spectator to being a regulator,'' Lochbaum said. 
</P>
<P>
	The NRC's executive director for operations, William Travers,  
testified in Congress last month that the commission is confident 
that all plants will be Y2K ready by October. Should noncompliance 
be spotted, he said, the NRC is ready to act and even shut down 
plants if necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	NRC officials said inspectors will check on Y2K fixes at all the  
plants this spring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
