<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court To Rule on Indigent Appeals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to use a  
California murder case to clarify when a convicted criminal's 
court-appointed lawyer can refuse to file an appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	The court said it will hear arguments by California officials  
that the state's procedure complies with a 1967 Supreme Court 
decision that limited when a court-appointed lawyer can refuse to 
file an appeal on grounds the appeal would be frivolous. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee Robbins was convicted of second-degree murder in Los Angeles  
in the Dec. 31, 1988, shooting death of his former roommate. He was 
sentenced to 17 years to life in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	His court-appointed lawyer filed a court brief that identified  
no issues for appeal but described the procedural history of the 
case and asked a California appeals court to conduct its own 
review. The lawyer also notified Robbins that he could file his own 
brief. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1967, the Supreme Court ruled that court-appointed lawyers  
could not refuse to pursue an appeal simply by filing a letter that 
said there were no issues that merited consideration on appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the court said then that court-appointed lawyers who  
determine an appeal would be frivolous still must file a brief -- 
one that identifies any issue that might support an appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Robbins filed his own brief, and it was denied by state courts.  
He then asked a federal judge to rule that his lawyer failed to 
follow the procedure required by the 1967 ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal judge ruled that Robbins was entitled to pursue a  
new state appeal. The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the 
decision, saying Robbins' lawyer ``completely failed to identify 
any grounds that arguably supported an appeal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal acted on today, the state's lawyers said Robbins'  
lawyer followed proper procedure and that Robbins should have been 
required to show he was harmed by the lawyer's actions. 
</P>
<P>
	The state's appeal said the 9th Circuit court's ruling  
invalidated the procedure used in many California cases and 
threatened to ``work a grievous hardship on the administration of 
justice in the nation's largest state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robbins' new lawyer said the appeals court ruling did not throw  
out the entire California procedure but was limited to the facts in 
his case. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Smith vs. Robbins, 98-1037.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
