<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DiMaggio, No. 56 Linked Forever </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	In his last public appearance, on the final day of the 1998  
baseball season, Joe DiMaggio was driven around Yankee Stadium in a 
'56 Ford Thunderbird. 
</P>
<P>
	The model year was no accident.  
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio and No. 56 were linked forever after the summer of 1941  
when, day after day, game after game, Joe D. delivered base hits, 
establishing one of the most remarkable records in sports history. 
</P>
<P>
	Babe Ruth's record of 714 home runs fell. Roger Maris' record of  
61 home runs fell. Lou Gehrig's record of 2,130 consecutive games 
fell. 
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio's 56-game hitting streak endures.  
</P>
<P>
	The streak started innocently, almost unnoticed. DiMaggio was  
coming off two straight American League batting championships, and 
at 26 was already considered one of baseball's top young stars. The 
New York Yankees had won four World Series in his first five 
seasons but they were struggling at the start of 1941, stuck at 
.500 with a 14-14 record as they opened a three-game series against 
the Chicago White Sox on May 15. 
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio was in a slump, held hitless in the previous two games  
by Cleveland aces Bob Feller and Mel Harder. But in the first 
inning against the White Sox, he delivered an RBI-single against 
Chicago's Edgar Smith. The hit hardly stood out, since the Yankees 
lost the game, 13-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Batting streaks are rarely recognized in their early stages,  
hardly noticed until they reach double digits. When DiMaggio went 
4-for-5, including a home run and drove in three runs at Washington 
on May 27, the streak reached 12 games. 
</P>
<P>
	A week later, on the day Gehrig died at 39, DiMaggio had two  
hits, extending the streak to 19 games. 
</P>
<P>
	Now it was getting serious.  
</P>
<P>
	At the time, the modern National League record was 33 games by  
Rogers Hornsby and the American League record was 41 by George 
Sisler. DiMaggio's consistency was clearly a threat to those marks. 
</P>
<P>
	In a three-game series at St. Louis, he punished Browns pitchers  
for seven hits in 16 at-bats, with three home runs and seven runs 
batted in. DiMag was on a tear. 
</P>
<P>
	On June 21, he blooped a first-inning single off Detroit's Dizzy  
Trout, extending the streak to 34 games, passing Hornsby. Sisler 
was the next target. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the pressure was on.  
</P>
<P>
	``That's when the public, the press and the pitchers really  
started noticing,'' he said later. 
</P>
<P>
	Later that week, the streak was in danger. DiMaggio was hitless  
through seven innings of Game No. 38 at home against St. Louis. He 
was scheduled to be the fourth batter in the bottom of the eighth 
and with the Yankees leading 3-1, there probably wouldn't be a 
ninth. It was clearly a crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	With one out, Red Rolfe walked. Now Tommy Henrich huddled with  
manager Joe McCarthy. Henrich feared hitting into a double play 
that would end the inning and the streak. He suggested a sacrifice. 
McCarthy agreed. It was the first time the Yankees made a move 
designed strictly for the streak. 
</P>
<P>
	The bunt worked and DiMaggio, his swing saved, followed with a  
double against Eldon Auker, keeping the streak alive. 
</P>
<P>
	Two days later, DiMaggio went for 40 against an obscure  
Philadelphia pitcher named Johnny Babich, who swore he was going to 
stop the streak. 
</P>
<P>
	Babich said he would pitch around DiMaggio, give him nothing to  
hit. Fifty years later, Joe D. vividly recalled the encounter. 
</P>
<P>
	``My first time up, the count went to 3-0,'' he said. ``I got  
the hit sign, but the fourth pitch was way outside.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his second at-bat, it was the same story -- four straight  
balls. It was clear what Babich was up to. Four walks in four trips 
would have ended the streak. The rules have been eased since then 
but at the time, DiMaggio was in jeopardy and he knew it. 
</P>
<P>
	``The third at-bat was the same,'' he said. ``Three straight  
balls. They gave me the hit sign again. This time, Babich got the 
fourth pitch not quite as far outside.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio jumped on it, ripping the ball up the middle, through  
the pitcher's legs and into center field, extending the streak to 
40 games. ``Babich went down flat on his back,'' DiMaggio said. 
``When he came up, he was ashen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The next day, the Yankees played a doubleheader at Washington.  
Between games, DiMaggio's bat disappeared. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't just any bat,'' he said. ``This was a very special  
bat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With a backup bat, DiMaggio was 0-for-3 in the second game  
against Red Anderson. Henrich, who used the same model, offered his 
to DiMaggio. Using the borrowed bat, DiMaggio singled to keep the 
streak alive. 
</P>
<P>
	On July 1, DiMaggio tied Wee Willie Keeler's pre-1900 record of  
44 straight games in a doubleheader sweep of Boston. The next day, 
he continued his assault with a home run. 
</P>
<P>
	Keeler was a milestone. Now DiMaggio was in uncharted territory.  
It hardly distracted him. He just kept peppering pitchers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees were in Cleveland on July 16, 1941, and on a rainy  
day, DiMaggio ripped three hits at League Park, where the Indians 
played some of their games. The ground was still damp the next 
night when a crowd of 67,468 crammed into larger Municipal Stadium 
on the lakefront. 
</P>
<P>
	In his first time at bat against Cleveland left-hander Al Smith,  
DiMaggio sent a shot down the third base line but slipped slightly 
on the heavy footing as he started out of the batter's box. Ken 
Keltner lunged to his right, backhanded the ball, and barely had 
time to throw him out. 
</P>
<P>
	After walking in his next at-bat, DiMaggio sent another shot  
down the line in the seventh. Again, Keltner grabbed the ball and 
threw him out. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were unconscious stops,'' Keltner said years later.  
``Both were backhanded plays, down the line. Both times, I got Joe 
by an eyelash. He could run, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Keltner, who led AL third basemen in fielding three times and  
assists four times, had developed a style of looking at the ball 
before throwing it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I grabbed the seams to make sure it didn't sail,'' he said.  
``On those plays, though, there was no time to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The third baseman had been playing deep.  
</P>
<P>
	``He was hitting with authority,'' Keltner said. ``I wanted to  
guard the line and stop the double. Ordinarily, I played him toward 
shortstop, but not that night. He wasn't bunting, I knew that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not once during the streak had DiMaggio bunted. There was no  
reason to expect him to change now. His last swing came in the 
eighth inning against reliever Jim Bagby. He came to the plate with 
the bases loaded and worked the count to 2-1, a good hitting 
situation. Then he sent a shot to shortstop, where Lou Boudreau 
turned it into an inning-ending double play. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees were leading 4-1 at the time. In the ninth inning,  
Cleveland rallied for two runs and had the tying run on third base 
with none out. If the Indians tied the game, DiMaggio would be up 
again in the 10th, with a chance to extend the streak. But relief 
ace Johnny Murphy escaped the jam, preserving the victory and 
depriving DiMaggio of any extra swings. 
</P>
<P>
	After two months, the streak was over.  
</P>
<P>
	He had 91 hits in 223 at-bats, 15 home runs, 35 extra-base hits  
and 55 RBIs. There were four games in which he had four hits, five 
games in which he had three hits and 13 games in which he had two 
hits. 
</P>
<P>
	From May 15 through July 16, 1941, he batted a torrid .408.  
</P>
<P>
	After the 56-game hitting streak ended, DiMaggio started a new  
one that lasted 16 games, giving him a remarkable stretch of hits 
in 72 of 73 games -- not including his All-Star game double. He 
would finish the season batting .357, leading the league with 125 
RBIs and winning the Most Valuable Player award. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 03:17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NCAA Unveils Men's Tournament Field </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- So what if Florida A&AMP;M is a 44-point  
underdog to mighty Duke? 
</P>
<P>
	Back in December, when the Rattlers lost 13 of their first 14  
games, the odds seemed a lot steeper they would even get into the 
NCAA tournament at all. 
</P>
<P>
	``If someone would have told me six months, or even six weeks  
ago, that we would be playing in the NCAA tournament against Duke, 
I would have laughed,'' coach Mickey Clayton said Sunday after the 
Rattlers drew top-seeded Duke (32-1) -- and probably a lot of laughs 
-- in the first round of the East Regional. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida A&AMP;M (12-18) is not in the 64-team field as someone's  
idea of a joke, however. The Rattlers got there by getting hot and 
winning the Mid-Eastern Athletic Conference's automatic bid by 
winning its league tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just have to continue to play together,'' said Jamaal  
Rhodes, a sophomore forward who will probably get the honor of 
covering Elton Brand next Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been branded the Cinderella through the conference  
tournament and we'll keep that moniker in this game, as well. But 
we aren't afraid of them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Rattlers would seem to find little comfort in recent  
history. No No. 16 seed or team with a losing record has ever won 
an NCAA game. Last year's biggest upset hopeful -- 13-16 Prairie 
View -- got crushed 110-52 by No. 1 seed Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	And the Rattlers have more recent experience with No. 1 seeds.  
They opened their season against Auburn, which was made No. 1 seed 
in the South when the 64-team field was unveiled Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The result? A 94-47 rout.  
</P>
<P>
	``We hope to draw from that experience,'' Clayton said. ``We're  
just going to go after these guys and see what happens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, the Big Ten landed seven, and almost eight,  
teams in the field while the proud ACC got just three. 
</P>
<P>
	The other No. 1 seeds were Connecticut in the West and Michigan  
State in the Midwest. There seemed little controversy in the 
committee's selection of top seeds or final teams to fill out the 
34 at-large squads. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there are a lot of teams that didn't get in,'' said  
selection committee chairman C.M. Newton. ``Getting down to those 
last teams was hard, as it always is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If anybody has a gripe it might be Connecticut. Newton admitted  
the committee judged the Huskies the No. 2 team overall behind 
Duke. Yet they alone among the four No. 1 seeds were shipped far 
from home and will open play in Denver in the West Regional. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, leading scorer Richard Hamilton said traveling  
across the country does have its benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will help us, because then there's no distractions,'' he  
said. ``We've got to stick together, we got to be together to do 
the things we want to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Big Ten set the record with seven teams in 1990 and it was  
matched by the Big East in 1991 and the Big Ten again in 1994. The 
league could have gotten the record if Illinois had completed its 
conference tournament run Sunday with another upset over Michigan 
State. 
</P>
<P>
	As for the ACC, it will have its lowest number of tournament  
teams since two, the limit at the time, were picked for the field 
of 40 in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to regular-season and tournament champion Michigan  
State, the other Big Ten teams selected were Ohio State, Indiana, 
Iowa, Minnesota, Wisconsin and Purdue, which almost ruined itself 
with a late-season slump and wound up No. 10 seed in the East. 
</P>
<P>
	The Southeastern Conference has one-fourth of the top 16 seeds:  
Auburn, No. 3 Kentucky and No. 4s Tennessee and Arkansas. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke, second-seeded Maryland and third-seeded North Carolina  
were the ACC teams chosen. The Big East, with Connecticut, No. 2 
Miami and No. 3 St. John's, also had three teams in the top 16. 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan State (29-4) will play on Friday against Mount St.  
Mary's, the Northeast Conference champions coached by 800-game 
winner Jim Phelan. 
</P>
<P>
	Auburn (27-3), which lost to Kentucky in the Southeastern  
Conference tournament semifinals, opens play in the South Regional 
on Thursday in Indianapolis against Winthrop, the Big South 
champion making its first tournament appearance. 
</P>
<P>
	Connecticut (28-2) will play on Thursday against Texas-San  
Antonio, which won the Southland Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	The Big East and Big 12 each had five teams invited. The other  
multi-bid conferences were Conference USA and the Pac-10 with four 
each; Missouri Valley and Western Athletic with three teams each; 
and the Mid-American with two. 
</P>
<P>
	The other games in Charlotte will be Tennessee against No. 13  
Delaware; fifth-seeded Wisconsin against No. 12 Southwest Missouri 
State; and eighth-seeded College of Charleston against No. 9 Tulsa. 
</P>
<P>
	At Boston it will be second-seeded Miami against No. 15  
Lafayette, making its first appearance since 1957; third-seeded 
Cincinnati against No. 14 George Mason; sixth-seeded Temple against 
No. 11 Kent; and seventh-seeded Texas against No. 10 Purdue. 
</P>
<P>
	The East Regional semifinals and finals will be held March 19  
and 21 in East Rutherford, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the Michigan State-Mount St. Mary's game in  
Milwaukee, fourth-seeded Arizona plays No. 13 Oklahoma; 
fifth-seeded North Carolina Charlotte meets No. 12 Rhode Island; 
and No. 8 Villanova plays No. 9 Mississippi. 
</P>
<P>
	The games Friday in New Orleans feature second-seeded Utah  
against No. 15 Arkansas State; Kentucky against 14th-seeded New 
Mexico State; No. 6 Kansas against 11th-seeded Evansville; and 
seventh-seeded Washington against No. 10 Miami of Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	The Midwest Regional semifinals and finals are March 19 and 21  
in St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	In the other games Thursday in Indianapolis, fourth-seeded Ohio  
State plays No. 13 Murray State; No. 5 UCLA meets 12th-seeded 
Detroit; and Syracuse plays Oklahoma State in the 8-9 matchup. 
</P>
<P>
	The other South subregional starts Thursday in Orlando, Fla.,  
and features No. 2 Maryland against last year's surprise team, No. 
15 Valparaiso; St. John's against 14th-seeded Samford; No. 6 
Indiana against No. 11 George Washington; and seventh-seeded 
Louisville, the school given a second chance at being in the 
tournament, against No. 10 Creighton. 
</P>
<P>
	The South Regional semifinals and final will be March 18 and 20  
in Knoxville, Tenn. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to Connecticut vs. Texas-San Antonio, the games  
Thursday in Denver feature Arkansas against No. 13 Siena; No. 5 
Iowa against No. 12 Alabama Birmingham; and No. 8 Missouri against 
No. 9 New Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	In Seattle on Thursday second-seeded Stanford plays No. 15  
Alcorn State; North Carolina meets No. 14 Weber State; No. 6 
Florida goes up against No. 11 Pennsylvania; and No. 7 Minnesota 
plays No. 10 Gonzaga. 
</P>
<P>
	The West Regional semifinals and finals will be March 18 and 20  
in Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	The national semifinals are March 27 in St. Petersburg, Fla.,  
and the matchups are South vs. West and East vs. Midwest. The 
championship game is March 29. 
</P>
<P>
	North Carolina extended its record with its 25th consecutive  
appearance, 10 more than the next best current streak, Arizona's 
15. 
</P>
<P>
	The other first-time NCAA teams are Arkansas State, Kent and  
Samford. 
</P>
</TEXT>
