<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NYC Opera Stages 'Lizzie Borden' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Arts and Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- When the New York City Opera gave the premiere  
of ``Lizzie Borden'' in 1965, it sounded very dissonant. It doesn't 
seem nearly as dissonant now but it retains its fierce impact. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York City Opera presented a new production of the work,  
based on a real double murder, on Saturday night. Composer Jack 
Beeson and librettist Kenward Elmslie were present and took bows 
with the excellent cast. 
</P>
<P>
	Rhoda Levine directed Phyllis Pancella in title role, showing  
how Lizzie's mind began to slip early on. Robin Blitch Wiper, a 
delicate-voiced soprano, sang her younger sister Margret. 
</P>
<P>
	The story takes place in 1892 in Fall River, Mass., where Lizzie  
and Margret live with their father and his second wife Abigail. 
Their father is a strict man, who does not allow Lizzie to leave 
their home. Even the church children's choir, which Lizzie 
conducts, has to meet in the house. 
</P>
<P>
	And when the preacher (Dennie Petersen, making his company  
debut) asks Andrew Borden for money, the tightwad Borden is so 
angry he forbids Lizzie to see either the children or the preacher. 
</P>
<P>
	The singers all expertly wound up the increasing family tension.  
Stephen West as Andrew Borden sang with sternness when addressing 
his daughters but warmly to wife Abigail. In her rich soprano, 
Lauren Flanigan flaunted Abigail's position with pretty clothes 
that were denied the daughters. One of the most musically striking 
and emotionally chilling moments is a Flanigan-Pancella duet. 
</P>
<P>
	Wiper's delicate voice indicates she's about to crack. Her  
sanity is saved by eloping with a young sea captain, sung 
resolutely by Dean Ely. At times, Lizzie fantasizes he wants her. 
</P>
<P>
	In the final scene, Lizzie has been acquitted of murdering her  
father and stepmother and has sealed herself inside the house. The 
preacher calls, suggesting they read the Bible. She sends him away. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the opera's dissonance is in the orchestra, which was  
conducted by George Manahan. John Conklin designed a room with 
center wooden steps leading to the married couple's bedroom. Lizzie 
climbs it twice, carrying an ax. The room is big but with only one 
window it seems stiflingly airless. The production was first 
presented at Glimmerglass Opera in Cooperstown, N.Y. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 15:23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Rise Slightly / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Treasury bonds rose modestly Monday, extending  
last week's strong gains. The rally has been driven by easing 
concerns that the U.S. economy will overheat, leading the Federal 
Reserve to boost interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Higher rates reduce the value of existing fixed-rate securities,  
such as bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 5/32 point  
Monday, or by $1.56 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which 
moves in the opposite direction, dropped to 5.59 percent from 5.60 
percent Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	With inflation under control, investors said bonds look more  
appetizing, particularly with yields at seven-month highs. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan told the  
Mortgage Bankers Association that inflation is ``well behaved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But two other Fed officials were more cautionary.  
</P>
<P>
	William Poole, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of St.  
Louis, said the bond market is correct to believe the central 
bank's next move will be a rate increase, according to Market News 
International. 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago Federal Reserve Bank President Michael Moskow told the  
Wisconsin Bankers Association that inflationary pressures may build 
during 1999, especially if corporations resort to raising prices to 
boost profits. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market Friday, prices of short-term Treasury  
securities rose 1/32 point to 3/32 point, while intermediate 
maturities rose 1/8 point to 3/8 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a 
financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lehman Brothers Daily Treasury Bond Index, reflecting price  
movements on bonds with maturities of a year or longer, rose 0.84 
point to 1,281.01. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills rose to 4.62 percent as the  
discount rose 0.01 percentage point from Friday to 4.50 percent. 
Six-month yields were unchanged at 4.70 percent, as the discount 
remained at 4.53 percent. One-year yields fell to 4.80 percent, 
while the discount fell 0.01 percentage point to 4.57 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 4.88 percent from 4.81 percent Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds rose 5/32 point to 123 15/16. The average 
yield to maturity fell to 5.23 percent from 5.24 percent Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
