<DOCNO> APW19990308.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 15:26:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Berra at a Loss for Words, For Once </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UPPER MONTCLAIR, N.J. (AP) -- It was hard for Yogi Berra to put a  
legacy into words. 
</P>
<P>
	``Oh gosh,'' Berra said every time a reporter asked different  
versions of the same question: What made Joe DiMaggio, who died on 
Monday, the greatest player ever? 
</P>
<P>
	``Oh God,'' said Berra, normally never at a loss for a malaprop.  
</P>
<P>
	Then Berra, who played with DiMaggio from 1947 until DiMaggio  
retired in 1951, came up with the answer. 
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio was perfect.  
</P>
<P>
	``Never did anything wrong on the field. Never did,'' Berra said  
Monday, sitting next to a gray 1939 DiMaggio road jersey on display 
at Berra's baseball museum. 
</P>
<P>
	Berra said he never saw DiMaggio dive for a ball in the  
outfield. And when DiMaggio sprinted from first to second base, 
``You thought, `Where the hell is he going?' He got there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to admire a man like that,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Berra, who later joined DiMaggio in the Hall of Fame, said that  
as a young man, he watched DiMaggio play. When he came to the 
Yankees, DiMaggio was the man Berra and other younger players 
looked up to. 
</P>
<P>
	``I watched him, everything he did,'' Berra said.  
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio was the only player Berra remembers to come to Yankee  
Stadium for home games dressed in a suit. ``Blue shirt, white shirt 
and a beautiful tie,'' Berra said. ``He looked great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Berra saw DiMaggio carefully guard his privacy. Even decades  
after his marriage to Marilyn Monroe, Berra said, he never 
mentioned her. And no one else was allowed to mention her if they 
wanted to remain his friend. 
</P>
<P>
	Though he was a loner once the game was over, Berra said, he  
would play cards and eat dinner with them on the train to away 
games. ``He always had somebody waiting for him when he got off the 
train,'' Berra said. 
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio wouldn't talk much about the injuries that caused him  
to leave the game, Berra said, although DiMaggio wouldn't play if 
he thought he would hurt his team. 
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio's death leaves Berra as the likely replacement for  
DiMaggio on April 9, when DiMaggio was scheduled to throw out the 
first ball at the Yankees' home opener. Berra, who recently ended a 
14-year feud with Yankee owner George Steinbrenner, said if he does 
get invited to Yankee Stadium, he has only one wish: that Joe could 
be there, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``So I could catch the ball instead of throw it.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 15:26:02 </DATE_TIME>
