<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 15:16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Congress Members Eager To Learn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Last year, Rep. Pat Toomey used to just fret  
about his own wallet. But as a newcomer to the twin worlds of 
politics and Congress, this Pennsylvania Republican now finds 
himself worrying about the nation's spending, too. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a demanding job, but Toomey can't contain his enthusiasm  
for it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's exciting for me to be immediately part of the mix,'' said  
Toomey, a 37-year-old former investment banker and restaurateur who 
is now on the Budget, Small Business and Banking committees as well 
as a task force on Social Security reform. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the new crop of House freshmen, Toomey and colleagues Jim  
DeMint, R-S.C., and Stephanie Tubbs-Jones, D-Ohio, were elected 
with no legislative experience. 
</P>
<P>
	That means they have to learn a lot -- from getting around the  
Capitol complex to hiring staff, studying issues and finding a home 
-- and learn it quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very exciting for me to be in the room where we're  
discussing the big issues of what the federal budgets ought to look 
like,'' Toomey said. ``It doesn't get much bigger than that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DeMint, who was surprised by his election as president of the  
Republican freshmen, said keeping tabs on the issues and other 
congressional details requires the skills of a juggler. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to keep a lot of balls in the air,'' added DeMint,  
a former advertiser, marketing consultant and owner of DeMint 
Marketing. He also was recruited by top Republican House leaders to 
work on sharpening the GOP's message. 
</P>
<P>
	DeMint, 47, first sampled politics as a volunteer strategist on  
the 1992 campaign of his predecessor, former Rep. Bob Inglis, 
R-S.C., who lost a Senate bid last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the 40 House freshmen are seasoned politicians, with  
many having served in their state legislatures or other government 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Michael Capuano, D-Mass., was mayor of Somerville. Rep. Jay  
Inslee, D-Wash., returns after a four-year absence. Other freshmen 
have been state judges, state attorney general, state highway 
commissioner or congressional aides. 
</P>
<P>
	Reps. David Wu, D-Ore., an attorney, and Brian Baird, D-Wash., a  
psychologist who lost a 1996 House race, also are among the novices 
-- a group whose prior legislative experience includes service on 
various school and local boards. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the eight Senate freshmen, only Democrat John Edwards, a  
North Carolina trial lawyer, had not previously held public office. 
</P>
<P>
	Tubbs-Jones, 49, is adjusting to doing more with less after  
nearly 20 years as an Ohio county judge and prosecutor. Her 
prosecutorial staff of 300 included 180 lawyers; she now depends on 
15 employees in congressional offices in Washington and Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the thing that's most significant for me is the amount  
of paper we process,'' Tubbs-Jones commented. 
</P>
<P>
	She got a taste of the national limelight last year when, as  
Cuyahoga County's prosecutor, she declined to review new DNA 
evidence in the case of Dr. Sam Sheppard, whose 1954 conviction for 
killing his wife led to the TV series and movie ``The Fugitive.'' 
The Ohio Supreme Court later overturned her decision. 
</P>
<P>
	She succeeded Democratic Rep. Louis Stokes, who retired after 30  
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Overwhelmed by the paper, too, is Toomey. But he skips most of  
it. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's enormous amounts of paper that I don't see because I  
intentionally don't look at it,'' he said. ``You don't have any 
time at all to waste.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A virtual unknown, Toomey even got support from such top  
Republicans as New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and former House 
Speaker Newt Gingrich. They campaigned on his behalf to help 
reclaim the seat for the GOP after Rep. Paul McHale, D-Pa., retired 
after three terms. 
</P>
<P>
	Toomey compared being in Congress to living in another world.  
``All of a sudden, you're immersed in a totally new universe,'' he 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
