<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 05:31:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McGwire Hits First Spring Home Run </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JUPITER, Fla. (AP) -- The crack of the bat was so sharp that it  
startled Ted Lilly. 
</P>
<P>
	Then again, the rookie pitcher had never heard a Mark McGwire  
home run up close. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire hit his first homer of 1999, a three-run shot Sunday for  
the St. Louis Cardinals in a 6-1 exhibition victory over the 
Montreal Expos. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nice to get it out of the way,'' McGwire said. ``But it's  
only spring training.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Just see the ball, hit the ball,'' he said. ``I believe it  
should never be changed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coming off his record-breaking season of 70, McGwire wasted no  
time finding his home-run swing. He launched a trademark drive high 
and far over the left-field wall in only his second official at-bat 
of the spring. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire homered a day after Sammy Sosa hit No. 1 for the Chicago  
Cubs. But there's no race -- at least, not yet -- and McGwire said he 
didn't even know about his rival's home run. 
</P>
<P>
	A sellout crowd at Roger Dean Stadium got exactly what it wanted  
when McGwire crunched an inside fastball from Lilly in the second 
inning. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never seen anything like that,'' the 23-year-old lefty  
said, shaking his head. ``I mean, it was loud.'' 
</P>
<P>
	J.D. Drew, Carlos Baerga and several other Cardinals greeted  
McGwire at the plate, but he did not punctuate this homer with the 
fake punch-to-the-gut routine that became his stamp during his 
historic season. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6,912 fans, many of them wearing No. 25 McGwire jerseys,  
gave him a standing ovation. 
</P>
<P>
	The ball landed between the fence and the Expos clubhouse, an  
off-limits area where park officials considered building bleachers 
this spring expressly for McGwire watchers. 
</P>
<P>
	The souvenir was retrieved by stadium marketing director  
Jennifer Chalhub, preparing to drive a 1999 white convertible 
Camaro around the field as part of an in-between inning promotion. 
</P>
<P>
	``I heard he was up and I got out of the car to protect it,''  
she said. ``He came within 25 feet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chalhub was aware that McGwire's 70th home run ball sold for $3  
million or so, but she didn't try to cash in. Instead, she gave it 
to a little girl about 4 years old standing outside the gate. 
</P>
<P>
	``I figured a ball would mean more to a kid,'' Chalhub said. ``I  
didn't even say it was a Mark McGwire ball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire hit seven home runs last year in exhibition play. The  
Cardinals share their training complex with Montreal, and the Expos 
are plenty familiar with McGwire. The All-Star first baseman hit 
his final five home runs last season against them, and six overall. 
</P>
<P>
	Had this been next month when the Cardinals play Montreal for  
real, Lilly might have just walked him. McGwire led the majors with 
an NL record 162 walks last year, and there were runners on second 
and third when he homered. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess we gave a home run to McGwire and everybody was  
pleased about that,'' Expos manager Felipe Alou said. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire drew a full-count walk in the first inning after hitting  
a long foul. He hooked another drive in the second before homering. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire did not bat again and left the game after three innings.  
He paused in the right-field corner to sign autographs for a few 
minutes before walking to the clubhouse. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the Cardinals' 14 home exhibition games at Roger Dean  
Stadium, 13 are sold out. McGwire items dominate the souvenir 
stand, with Big Mac hats, shirts, posters and model bats on sale. 
</P>
<P>
	Rather than a piece of merchandise, Lilly got a McGwire memory.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was pretty pumped up about the chance to pitch to him for  
the first time. But I went about it the wrong way. I tried to match 
power vs. power,'' he said, ``and obviously he has more.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
