<DOCNO> APW19990308.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 08:17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Might Reinstate Suit Vs. Doctors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to clarify the  
filing deadline for lawsuits that invoke a federal 
anti-racketeering law by studying the case of a Texas man who says 
he was illegally held in a psychiatric hospital by profit-greedy 
doctors. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices said they will consider reinstating Mark Rotella's  
lawsuit against two dozen doctors stemming from his 16-month stay 
at Brookhaven Psychiatric Pavilion in Dallas, which ended in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	Rotella, now a Dallas-Fort Worth area resident, was 16 when in  
1985 he was admitted to Brookhaven on the request of his mother. He 
remained there until shortly after his 18th birthday. 
</P>
<P>
	The hospital closed down in 1992. Two years later, its parent  
company -- Psychiatric Institutes of America -- pleaded guilty to 
charges of fraud and conspiracy and to violations of the federal 
Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act (RICO). 
</P>
<P>
	A series of Supreme Court rulings has permitted broad use of  
RICO, a law originally aimed at mobsters, and allow lawsuits by 
anyone allegedly harmed by a ``pattern'' of illegal activities. The 
law has been invoked to accuse numerous huge corporations of 
racketeering. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Psychiatric Institutes of America had provided  
financial incentives to doctors who unnecessarily admitted, treated 
and retained patients at its facilities across the country. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, Rotella sued doctors who had been associated with  
Brookhaven in Dallas, seeking to collect monetary damages under the 
civil provisions of the RICO law. 
</P>
<P>
	They sought to have the lawsuit thrown out, citing the four-year  
statute of limitations courts have imposed for filing RICO 
lawsuits. The doctors' lawyers said the four-year period began, at 
the latest, when Rotella was released from Brookhaven in 1986, 11 
years before he sued. 
</P>
<P>
	But Rotella's lawyers contended that the deadline clock should  
not have begun ticking until 1994, when he discovered the facts 
that would lead him to suspect a pattern of racketeering activity. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal appeals courts have split on the appropriate start for  
the four-year statute of limitations. In Rotella's case, the 5th 
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled he missed the deadline after it 
selected ``the discovery of the injury alone'' trigger -- not ``the 
discovery of both the injury and the pattern of racketeering 
activity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Rotella vs. Dallas Psychiatric Associates, 98-896.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 05:18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former King Congregation Moves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Ebenezer Baptist Church holds many memories for  
Christine King Ferris: It was where she was baptized, where she 
married and where her famous brother and father once preached. 
</P>
<P>
	But it also was where the funeral for her slain sibling, the  
Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., was held in 1968 and where six years 
later her mother, Alberta, was gunned down while playing the organ. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have mixed emotions,'' said Mrs. Ferris as she walked away  
from the old church toward congregation's new $8 million sanctuary. 
``I will always have an affinity for Ebenezer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Ferris was among the hundreds of members and visitors  
Sunday who filled the old church's wooden pews to pray and reflect 
on Ebenezer's 76-year history before marching over to the new 
facility. 
</P>
<P>
	Singing ``We're Marching to Zion,'' and led by children, the  
congregation marched over to the fan-shaped building where church 
leaders cut the yellow ribbons on the doors of the new sanctuary. 
</P>
<P>
	The congregation had long since outgrown the old, 750-seat  
building, with its cracked ceiling and creaky floors. The new 
building can accommodate both a 150-member choir and 1,800 in its 
oak pews, all of which were filled during the first worship 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now we'll be able to do what we did (Sunday) -- let as many  
people come in as want to. We won't have to turn them away,'' said 
the Rev. Joseph Roberts Jr., the church's senior pastor. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither King's widow, Coretta Scott King, nor any of his  
children were at the service. 
</P>
<P>
	For years, Ebenezer was the cradle of the civil rights movement,  
serving as one of the places where black leaders plotted 
strategies. Both King, his father and grandfather once preached 
from Ebenezer's pulpit. 
</P>
<P>
	The ceremony was bittersweet for many of the church's members,  
including Jethro English, an 86-year-old deacon who joined Ebenezer 
in 1925. 
</P>
<P>
	As a young boy, English was baptized at Ebenezer and it's where  
he and his wife of 61 years were married by the Rev. Martin Luther 
King Sr. He was a pallbearer at the younger King's funeral and was 
sitting in the choir when Mrs. King was slain. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are so many precious memories there,'' English said.  
``I've seen the tragedies and I've seen the victories.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he added, ``The new sanctuary is a dream come true.''  
</P>
<P>
	For decades, Ebenezer has anchored the surrounding area known as  
``Sweet Auburn,'' once a center of black business that has since 
fallen on hard times. The neighborhood is where King grew up and is 
buried. 
</P>
<P>
	Each year, nearly a half million people visit the historic  
church. 
</P>
<P>
	With its faded red brick facade, the historic Ebenezer stands in  
stark contrast to the Afrocentric architecture of the New Horizon 
Sanctuary, with its modern look and towering windows. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Park Service, which already runs the visitor's  
center at the Martin Luther King Jr. National Historic Site, will 
assume responsibility for the preservation of Ebenezer. The Park 
Service will offer tours, lectures, book signings and other 
programs at the church. 
</P>
<P>
	Political and social action will remain a focus of the new  
church's activity, Roberts said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The mandate from Dr. King is still very much ours,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
