<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EU, U.S. Clash in WTO Meeting  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- The United States and the European Union made  
their cases before the World Trade Organization today over hefty 
U.S. sanctions imposed amid the bitter trans-Atlantic banana trade 
row. The EU denounces the U.S. sanctions, but Washington insists it 
has the right to take the step due to EU reluctance to change 
import policies that American banana sellers say squeeze them out 
of the European market. The WTO summoned all its 134 member 
countries to the meeting requested by the EU to discuss the U.S. 
sanctions. But many members fear the high-profile meeting will only 
worsen the dispute between the two most powerful WTO members. 

</P>
<P>
	Hezbollah: No Truce in S. Lebanon  
</P>
<P>
	BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Hezbollah will not accept any temporary  
truce in south Lebanon during the run-up to Israel's May 17 
elections, the Shiite Muslim group's leader was quoted today as 
saying. Sheik Hassan Nasrallah also told the leftist As-Safir 
newspaper that Hezbollah would not go along with any amendments to 
a 1996 U.S.-brokered understanding barring Israel and Lebanese 
guerrillas from attacking civilian areas or launching attacks from 
them. The hard-line Hezbollah stance came amid reports that Martin 
Indyk, a U.S. assistant secretary of state, would visit Lebanon 
this week for talks. 

</P>
<P>
	McDougal Defiant in Face of Trial  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- In the face of contempt and obstruction  
of justice charges that could send her back to prison, Whitewater 
figure Susan McDougal insists she has no information on President 
Clinton and the first lady's business dealings in Arkansas. Mrs. 
McDougal already has served 18 months on a civil contempt citation, 
and she goes on trial today for refusing to answer Independent 
Counsel Kenneth Starr's questions about the Clintons. If convicted, 
she could be sent back to prison and fined up to $750,000. But her 
lawyer says Mrs. McDougal won't be broken. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Marks 50th Anniversary  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- NATO officials were marking the 50th anniversary  
of the foundation of the Western military alliance, which is about 
to admit its first former East bloc members. Defense or foreign 
ministers from some founder-member states of the U.S.-led alliance 
will mingle with representatives from soon-to-be members starting 
today for a three-day conference at London's Royal Institute for 
Strategic Studies. President Clinton will host the official 50th 
birthday NATO celebration -- a late April summit in Washington when 
Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republic will be welcomed. 

</P>
<P>
	Qatar Holds Local Elections  
</P>
<P>
	DOHA, Qatar (AP) -- Men in flowing white Arab robes and veiled  
women covered in black lined up today to vote in Qatar's municipal 
elections, the oil-rich emirate's first taste of democracy that is 
being closely watched throughout the Gulf. Although the 29-member 
Municipality Council being elected will only have advisory powers, 
the vote is a landmark in this conservative region where open 
franchise is rare. The vote is also giving women a unique 
opportunity to vote and run for office. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Visiting Central America  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton embarks today on his  
four-day, four-nation mission just as 15,000 Guatemalans and 
Salvadorans in the United States illegally become eligible for 
deportation. Making a pilgrimage to the sites of Hurricane Mitch's 
worst horrors, the president proffers Central Americans hope for 
their reconstruction so that despair does not turn into political 
trouble for the region. He has turned down pleas for an extension 
of the halt in deportations that was instituted after last fall's 
devastating storm and expires today. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stock Prices Fall  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell today on worries that a rise in  
the yen against the dollar could erode profits for Japanese 
companies. The Nikkei shed 114.95 points to close at 14,779.05. 

</P>
<P>
	Duke Finishes Season at No. 1  
</P>
<P>
	Duke, Michigan State, Connecticut and Auburn, the top four seeds  
in the NCAA tournament, finished in that order today in the final 
AP college basketball poll of the season. It was the third No. 1 
finish for the Blue Devils (32-1), who entered the NCAA tournament 
on top of the rankings in 1986 and 1992, the latter the year they 
repeated as national champions. 

</P>
<P>
	Coyotes 4, Predators 3  
</P>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Keith Tkachuk scored two of his three goals to  
spark a three-goal first period as the Phoenix Coyotes snapped a 
four-game losing streak with a 4-3 win over the Nashville Predators 
last night. Tkachuk has scored five of his team-high 27 goals in 
the last two games for the Coyotes, who won for only the second 
time in their last 11 games. 

</P>
<P>
