<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Banks Promise Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Major Japanese banks assured a government  
commission Monday they would post profits next fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	The assurances came at hearings before a government commission  
that will be doling out taxpayer money to help debt-plagued banks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Financial Reconstruction Commission required the executives  
from 15 banks that have applied for the bailout to explain how much 
bad loans they were writing off as well as what kind of changes 
they planned to carry out to boost profitability. 
</P>
<P>
	They were also asked about their plans for repaying the public  
funds. 
</P>
<P>
	The massive bad debt problem at Japan's top banks are leftover  
from the excessive lending of the late 1980s and early 1990s. 
Fixing the problem is viewed as a crucial step toward turning 
around the economy, mired in the worst recession in decades. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Friday, the banks formally asked the commission for a total  
of $61 billion in public assistance. Based on the hearings Monday, 
the commission will set the terms on the bailout on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Each of the banks, including the Industrial Bank of Japan and  
the Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank, predicted that they expect losses for the 
fiscal year ending March 31 but that they see profits for the next 
fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	The banks also said that the public funds will help them boost  
lending to cash-strapped Japanese companies and individuals. 
</P>
<P>
	Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank told the commission it expects a parent net  
profit of about $415 million next fiscal year, although it expects 
a loss of $3.2 billion this fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	Sakura Bank expects its parent will earn about $620 million next  
fiscal year, compared with a loss of $3 billion this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
