<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> White House Targets Farm Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is announcing a  
final strategy for reducing pollution from so-called factory farms, 
but environmentalists said Monday it doesn't go far enough or fast 
enough. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan to control pollution from cattle feedlots, poultry  
farms and large hog farms will serve as a blueprint for tighter 
regulations to be developed over the next few years. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the more stringent requirements, including compliance  
with permits under tougher federal standards, would not go into 
effect until 2002 and in some cases several years after that, 
environmentalists complained. 
</P>
<P>
	``It does nothing in the near term to address the serious  
shortcomings of current animal waste practices,'' said Joe Rudek, a 
scientist for the Environmental Defense Fund. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan, a draft of which was unveiled last September, was to  
be announced Tuesday by Vice President Al Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	``This comprehensive strategy tackles a major threat to water  
quality. Through tough standards and flexible new approaches, we 
can ensure communities across the country cleaner, safer water,'' 
Gore planned to tell environmental and agricultural leaders who 
were invited to the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Administration officials said the plan will require thousands of  
additional facilities to get permits and develop nutrient 
management plans. While many of the regulations will not go into 
effect until after 2001, thousands of additional operators will 
have to get permits under existing standards. 
</P>
<P>
	The broad outline is similar to a draft version released last  
September. 
</P>
<P>
	The Environmental Protection Agency is to develop the new  
technology standards for reducing pollution, mostly nutrient runoff 
into lakes and streams. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, called it ``a giant leap toward holding  
the biggest livestock producers accountable for water pollution,'' 
including large poultry processors and operators of large, 
concentrated hog farms. 
</P>
<P>
	But environmentalists, who have called for a moratorium on new  
permits for such facilities, were not as enthusiastic. 
</P>
<P>
	Kathryn Hohmann of the Sierra Club said the plan provides ``no  
real protection of groundwater'' and fails to adequately address 
pollution from open-air manure lagoons. 
</P>
<P>
	``Instead of cleaning up, the plan will have many of the largest  
factory farms writing up strategies for storing and disposing large 
volumes of manure, based on existing federal waste management 
standards and practices,'' the Environmental Defense Fund said in a 
statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
