<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wilkins Pleased With Pitching Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRADENTON, Fla. (AP) -- It was only 16 pitches and hardly anyone  
saw them, but Marc Wilkins cherished Monday's appearance in a 
Pittsburgh Pirates' ``B'' game against Tampa Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	The right-handed reliever pitched a scoreless relief inning  
against the Devil Rays, his first game appearance since shoulder 
surgery Sept. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a little emotional for me,'' Wilkins said. ``It really  
hit me when I was walking off the mound. All of a sudden my eyes 
starting tearing up, kind of like when you're watching a movie and 
it kind of hits you at the end.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He recalled the anxiety of not knowing if he would be able to  
return. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a great relief for me to go out and face batters  
without feeling any pain. We'll see how I feel tomorrow and the 
next day, but I'm very encouraged,'' Wilkins said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilkins struck out two of four batters. Another flied out to  
center field, and a fourth reached on third baseman Aramis 
Ramirez's error. 
</P>
<P>
	``''I tried to make this no different than the last 15 times  
I've been on the mound, pitching batting practice or throwing 
sideline sessions. Once I got on the mound, though, that all went 
out the window,'' Wilkins said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said it was hard not to realize the importance of the moment.  
</P>
<P>
	``There was an adrenaline rush from facing hitters,'' Wilkins  
said. ``I really tried to keep my composure the best I could and 
just tried to make good pitches but that was difficult to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wilkins, 28, missed most of last season because of shoulder  
problems. He pitched 15 1-3 innings in 16 appearances with the 
Pirates and a 6 1-3 innings in seven appearances at Triple-A 
Nashville and Double-A Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	He had been one of the Pirates' top relievers in 1996 and 1997.  
</P>
<P>
	``I've been waiting for this for a long time,'' Wilkins said.  
``I've been waiting to see if I can get hitters out again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wilkins will pitch in a regular exhibition game later this week,  
possibly during Thursday's doubleheader with Tampa Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was kind of upset they wouldn't let me pitch in the real  
games right away,'' he said. ``But I understand that they want to 
take things slow with me. They want to make sure my velocity is 
where it should be. ``I really felt I'd have some pain when I 
started throwing down here but there hasn't been any. I feel good, 
way better than I thought I would. It's surprised me that I've felt 
this good. I still have a little bit of a restricted feeling when I 
pitch but it's not uncomfortable or anything like that.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
