<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador Declares Surprise Holiday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- The government declared a banking holiday  
for Monday and Tuesday to protect its shaky currency, the sucre, 
which plunged last week. 
</P>
<P>
	An hour before the banks were to open, bank superintendent Jorge  
Egas announced the surprise closings for Monday in a nationally 
televised address. He said later that the banks would remain closed 
through Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The move was to ``preserve the stability of bank reserves, limit  
the withdrawals that could effect the domestic financial system, 
and avoid pressure on the currency and the continued rise in 
prices,'' Egas said. 
</P>
<P>
	The banking holiday also closed the domestic foreign exchange  
market. 
</P>
<P>
	Ecuador is embroiled in its worst economic crisis in the last 20  
years due to $2.6 billion in damage from El Nino-related floods and 
mudslides last year and falling prices of its main export, oil. 
</P>
<P>
	The sucre lost more than a quarter its value in wild trading  
last week amid growing uncertainty over the Andean nation's 
economic outlook. The instability was fed by rumors the government 
planned to seize dollar-denominated bank accounts to buy sucres and 
that a major bank was going to collapse. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors also have not been sold on President Jamil Mahuad's  
plans to cut Ecuador's budget deficit, which is running at $1.2 
billion, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Adding to the uncertainty, Ecuador's state energy workers have  
threatened to interrupt the flow of oil and electricity if Congress 
approves a Mahuad-sponsored bill to cut public spending. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
