<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Seek Tough N.Korea Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Five Republican House leaders appealed to  
former Defense Secretary William Perry, the Clinton 
administration's point man on North Korea, to recommend a tougher 
U.S. policy toward North Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	``North Korea's nuclear ambitions, chemical-biological  
capability and its burgeoning missile capability present a clear 
and present danger to the security of the United States,'' the 
lawmakers wrote to Perry in a letter released on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Signing the letter were House International Committee Chairman  
Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y., Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, 
R-Ill.; House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas; Rep. Christopher 
Cox, R-Calif., chairman of the House Policy Committee; and Rep. Joe 
Knollenberg, R-Mich., a member of the House Appropriations 
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	They urged an overhaul in policy ``from the ground floor up.''  
</P>
<P>
	Perry is expected to issue a report this month dealing with  
North Korea's nuclear weapons and ballistic missile capability and 
other issues. It follows North Korea's firing a rocket over Japan 
six months ago -- and later threatening to fire more. 
</P>
<P>
	An end to the development, testing and proliferation of such  
missiles must be part of any new U.S. policy toward North Korea, 
the lawmakers insisted. They also called for stronger enforcement 
of a 1991 agreement banning both sides on the Korean peninsula from 
developing weapons of mass destruction and for ``an end to 
state-sponsored illegal narcotics production and trafficking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the State Department, spokesman James Rubin said Perry ``is  
now in the region, consulting with our friends and allies as he 
conducts his policy review.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He has met with key congressional figures and will do so again  
as he proceeds to gather as many views as possible for his 
consideration,'' Rubin said. ``I cannot speculate on the outcome of 
the review, still a work in progress, but I am certain it will 
carefully evaluate the views expressed in Congressman Gilman's 
letter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The letter came as the United States entered a second week of  
negotiations with North Korea over U.S. access to a suspected 
underground nuclear complex. Talks at the U.S. mission to the 
United Nations in New York were scheduled to continue Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Perry, meanwhile, conferred in Seoul on Tuesday with top South  
Korean policy-makers , including a breakfast session with Foreign 
Minister Hong Soon-young and national security adviser Lim 
Dong-won. He also was scheduled to meet President Kim Dae-jung 
later in the day. 
</P>
<P>
	In his arrival statement Monday night, Perry said the United  
States supports South Korea's policy of greater economic and 
diplomatic engagement with North Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	But he also said Seoul and Washington must work together to  
resolve North Korea's missile program and suspected nuclear 
activity. ``We must stand together to resolve problems in these 
areas even as we look for possibilities for engagements in other 
areas,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	South Korea wants the United States and Japan to offer North  
Korea expanded economic and diplomatic benefits in exchange for 
abandoning its missile and nuclear programs and moves toward 
establishing peace on the Korean Peninsula. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, those issues have been dealt with individually, but  
South Korea thinks they should be lumped together in one 
negotiating package. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
