<HEADLINE> Japanese Stocks Rebound / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks rebounded early Tuesday after consumer  
electronics giant Sony Corp. announced a major corporate 
restructuring plan. The dollar edged higher against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei Stock Average rose 122.41 points, or 0.83 percent, to  
14,901.46 points in the first 30 minutes of trading. On Monday, the 
average closed down 114.95 points, or 0.77 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.86 yen in early trading, up 0.08 yen from  
late Monday in Tokyo and also above its level of 121.66 yen in New 
York. 
</P>
<P>
	``The yen is stable and New York shares held up well on Monday.  
The environment is stable,'' said Sachio Ishikawa, general manager 
of the stock division at Chuo Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York Monday, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 8.47  
points to 9,727.61 at Monday's close. 
</P>
<P>
	Sony issues jumped nearly 10 percent after the company said  
early Tuesday it will make wholly-owned subsidiaries of three 
listed units. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading in the shares of the three units involved -- Sony Music  
Entertainment, Sony Chemical and Sony Precision Technology -- were 
temporarily suspended Tuesday morning as exchange officials 
verified the information. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section rose 4.95 points, or 0.43 percent, to 1,152.70 
points. The TOPIX closed up 1.03 points, or 0.09 percent, the day 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar moved slightly higher as  
Japanese institutional investors and foreign fund mangers briefly 
covered short, or oversold positions. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 132.58 yen, up from  
132.09 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the yield on the 10-year Japanese government bond  
rose to 1.665 percent from Monday's finish of 1.625 percent, 
driving its price down to 101.08 yen from 101.41 yen. 

</P>
</TEXT>
