<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Deportations Moratorium Ends Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) -- President Clinton may have  
Hurricane Mitch on his mind during his Central American tour, but 
many here are just as concerned about his position on deporting 
illegal immigrants. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States has halted deporting Central Americans living  
illegally on its soil since Mitch hit the area in October, in an 
effort to not increase the ravaged countries' burdens. 
</P>
<P>
	But the moratorium on deportations ends today for El Salvador  
and Guatemala, and Central American governments insist they need 
more time. 
</P>
<P>
	``We Central Americans fear a massive deportation from the  
United States, which would be equal to or worse than Mitch,'' said 
leftist Salvadoran congressman Ramon Bach. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would cause us tragic problems in terms of stability,''  
said rightist President Armando Calderon Sol, chosen by other 
Central American presidents to speak on their behalf on the issue 
during Clinton's four-day trip. 
</P>
<P>
	``There would be an explosion in Central America and in El  
Salvador if that occurred.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In El Salvador, Clinton's second stop today, roughly a fifth of  
the country's 5.5 million people work in the United States and the 
money they send home provide a fifth of its foreign income. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of thousands of Hondurans, Guatemalans and Nicaraguans  
also are in the United States. Some immigration experts estimate 
that as many as 700,000 Central Americans are in the United States 
illegally. 
</P>
<P>
	Guatemala's president, Alvaro Arzu, asked Clinton in an open  
letter to extend the moratorium for his country and El Salvador to 
18 months, the grace period given to Honduras and Nicaragua, which 
were harder hit by Mitch. 
</P>
<P>
	Extending the moratoriums ``would allow all of us additional  
time to deal with the complex social issues we are facing'' due to 
the hurricane and economic problems, Arzu said. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House said today that an extension was not imminent.  
</P>
<P>
	``We have concluded that both countries are capable of beginning  
to receive their nationals,'' spokesman Michael Hammer said before 
Clinton's departure. ``We don't expect that deportations will begin 
immediately, but there's no further extension being contemplated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But even Honduras, which would not face the deportation of its  
citizens from the United States until late 2000, is asking for more 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	``The moratorium should be reconsidered in view of the economic  
situation facing Honduras, which is prostrate and cannot generate 
jobs,'' said Foreign Minister Roberto Flores Bermudez. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaders throughout the region were appealing for a hold on  
deportations long before Mitch hit the region -- though the 
hurricane added urgency to their appeals. 
</P>
<P>
	Calderon Sol said he would ask Clinton to delay deportations at  
least until the United States takes steps toward free trade and 
investment with the region so that jobs can be created. 
</P>
<P>
	The explosive growth of Central American immigration to the  
United States came in the 1980s, when wars prompted hundreds of 
thousands to flee for their lives. 
</P>
<P>
	Once in the United States, they found jobs and began sending  
vital funds home. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many people here live on their relatives'' up north, said  
Juana de Jesus Morales, 39, who has a cousin in the United States. 
The money sent home by the cousin ``is the only aid my aunt has. 
She sells little cakes, but she doesn't make enough to live on,'' 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Like many here, Morales expressed fear that an expulsion would  
flood the country with U.S.-trained gang members who are blamed for 
much of El Salvador's crime. 
</P>
<P>
	Those working in the United States should be helped, she said.  
</P>
<P>
	But ``the criminals -- let them be stoned. I don't say that; it's  
the word of the Lord,'' she added, waving a Bible she had just 
carried to her Baptist church service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
