<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Few Patients Get Cholesterol Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Despite a drumbeat of research and  
advertising, at least 20 million Americans at risk of heart attacks 
aren't getting cholesterol-lowering drugs that could save their 
lives. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest statistics, released Monday at a cardiology  
conference in New Orleans, underline one of heart experts' biggest 
frustrations: Even though the benefits of these medicines are now 
beyond dispute, they are prescribed to perhaps only one in five of 
those who could benefit. 
</P>
<P>
	``Increasingly we know what to do,'' said Dr. Richard Pasternak  
of Massachusetts General Hospital. ``The issue is why it's not 
getting done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Experts said doctors and their patients share the blame.  
</P>
<P>
	The drugs, called statins, can reduce cholesterol levels by 60  
points or so. Taking them cuts the chances of heart attacks by 
about one-third. 
</P>
<P>
	Studies showing their benefits have become a staple at  
conferences like this week's meeting of the American College of 
Cardiology. In general, they show that people who already have 
serious heart disease benefit most. But the drugs appear to help 
just about everyone with modestly elevated cholesterol levels or 
abnormally low amounts of the ``good cholesterol'' that protects 
against heart attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1993, the government recommended giving the medicines to  
those with elevated levels of ``bad cholesterol.'' Since then, the 
evidence in favor of statins has only gotten stronger. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, doctors often do not recommend them even to  
patients who are at highest risk of heart attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. James Froehlich of the University of Michigan reviewed  
surveys of about 250,000 patient visits to doctors between 1990 and 
1996. He found that just 14 percent of those diagnosed with 
cardiovascular disease went away with a prescription for a 
cholesterol-lowering drug. 
</P>
<P>
	The use of these medicines is going up and had increased to  
about 18 percent by 1996, the last year of the survey. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Antonio M. Gotto of Cornell University said that between 4.5  
million and 5 million Americans are currently taking statins, while 
at least 25 million could benefit. Only about half of heart attack 
victims are sent home from the hospital with prescriptions for 
statins. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's enough blame to go around. It's not just the doctors'  
fault,'' Pasternak said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gotto noted that patients themselves are often unenthusiastic  
about taking statins, because they are not terribly afraid of heart 
trouble. Many women think heart problems won't harm them -- even 
though they are the No. 1 killer of U.S. women -- while men often 
believe they can get all the treatment they need after they have a 
heart attack. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they were told statins prevented cancer, they'd be taking  
it in droves,'' Gotto said. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts at the conference cited several other reasons for low  
use: 
</P>
<P>
	--Doctors are better paid for treating diseases than for  
preventing them. 
</P>
<P>
	--The drugs are expensive. They often cost $75 to $100 a month.  
</P>
<P>
	--Doctors are by nature extremely conservative and slow to adopt  
new ideas. 
</P>
<P>
	--There are lingering concerns about the drugs' safety, even  
though the latest data suggest they are extremely safe and produce 
few side effects. 
</P>
<P>
	--Patients with no outward symptoms of heart trouble are often  
reluctant to take drugs that don't make them feel better. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
