<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spring Training Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Gabe Alvarez made the biggest splash at spring training Monday --  
even bigger than Mark McGwire's second home run in two days -- not 
that Alvarez was proud of it. 
</P>
<P>
	Detroit's third baseman made five errors, including four on poor  
throws, and the Tigers made seven in all during a 9-7 loss to the 
Atlanta Braves at Lakeland, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	``I should have had every one of those balls,'' Alvarez said.  
``They were all routine plays.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alvarez, who had 19 errors in 55 games at third last season,  
made four throwing errors. First baseman Frank Catalanotto and 
non-roster pitcher Jeff Weaver made one error each for Detroit, 
which allowed five unearned runs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll run Gabe out there again,'' Tigers manager Larry Parrish  
said. ``Not tomorrow. But we've got to get him over it. He kind of 
had that, `Oh, God, don't hit the ball to me,' look. We've all had 
that at one time. But, if you're going to play up here, you've got 
to want the ball hit to you. Right now, I don't think he feels that 
way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Jupiter, Fla., McGwire launched one for the second time in  
three spring at-bats, connecting off Houston's Jose Lima -- who gave 
up Sammy Sosa's 66th and final home run last year. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire isn't putting much significance on the home runs.  
</P>
<P>
	``Hey, guys, this is spring training,'' he said after the St.  
Louis Cardinals' 2-1 loss. 
</P>
<P>
	At Fort Lauderdale, Fla., new Dodgers manager Davey Johnson saw  
many familiar faces -- his former teammates on the Baltimore 
Orioles. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not just another game. I have sentimental feelings about  
today,'' Johnson said before Los Angeles was routed 10-0. 
</P>
<P>
	Dodgers outfielders Trenidad Hubbard and Hiram Bocachica were  
injured during a violent outfield collision as Jerry Hairston Jr. 
circled the bases for an inside-the-park homer. 
</P>
<P>
	Hubbard hurt his right thumb and wrist. Bocachica injured his  
right rib cage, and Dodgers manager Davey Johnson suspected the 
rookie might have cracked at least one rib. Both players were to 
undergo X-rays. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona, meanwhile, learned that newly acquired Tony Womack will  
be out six weeks because of a broken wrist sustained Sunday when he 
was hit by a pitch from Jim Parque of the Chicago White Sox. 
</P>
<P>
	The arm was placed in a cast, but Womack will be able to  
participate in conditioning drills and a smaller cast may be placed 
on the arm in a week or two, manager Buck Showalter said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Port Charlotte, Fla., the Texas Rangers pulled off a triple  
play in a 6-4 win over the Tampa Bay Devil Rays. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas led 6-3 in the sixth inning when Fred McGriff walked and  
Julio Franco singled. John Flaherty lined a shot to third base that 
Rob Sasser caught. He threw to second baseman Kelly Dransfeldt to 
double up McGriff, and Dransfeldt's relay to first beat Franco back 
to the base. 
</P>
<P>
	In other games:  
</P>
<P>
                          *Pirates 3, Reds 2    	
</P>
<P>
	At Sarasota, Fla., Pete Harnisch, expected to be Cincinnati's  
opening day starter, pitched four shutout innings. He has given up 
only two hits in eight shutout innings this spring, striking out 
eight and walking none. 
</P>
<P>
                           *Mets 3, Expos 2    	
</P>
<P>
	At Port St. Lucie, Fla., Jason Isringhausen pitched in a game  
for the first time since winter ball in December 1997, throwing two 
innings. He allowed one hit, struck out four and balked in the only 
run he allowed. 
</P>
<P>
                        *Indians 4, Blue Jays 3    	
</P>
<P>
	At Dunedin, Fla., Pat Hentgen, in his first game appearance  
since missing his final three starts last year because of shoulder 
tendinitis, was pounded for four runs in 2 2-3 innings. 
</P>
<P>
                          *Twins 6, Red Sox 3    	
</P>
<P>
	At Fort Myers, Fla., Mark Portugal allowed two hits in three  
scoreless innings as he made his spring debut for Boston. 
</P>
<P>
                         *Royals 8, Marlins 4    	
</P>
<P>
	At Haines City, Fla., rookie outfielder Carlos Beltran hit his  
first home run of the spring for Kansas City and Steve Scarsone 
also homered. 
</P>
<P>
                        *Mariners 10, Angels 3    	
</P>
<P>
	At Peoria, Ariz., Jay Buhner, making his first spring training  
appearance since major surgery on his right elbow, had three hits 
and drove in four runs to lead an 18-hit attack. 
</P>
<P>
                     *Rockies 6, Cubs 5, 10 innings    	
</P>
<P>
	At Tucson, Ariz., Larry Walker drove in two runs and saved two  
with sparkling defense in right field. He threw out Jose Hernandez 
at second base ahead of Mark Grace's homer in the first and made a 
running catch on what looked to be an RBI double by Robin Jennings 
in the second. 
</P>
<P>
                         *Giants 7, Padres 4    	
</P>
<P>
	At Scottsdale, Ariz., Damon Minor, who drove in six runs during  
a ``B'' game earlier in the day, hit a three-run homer in the 10th 
inning. Tony Gwynn hit a two-run homer for the Padres, who tied the 
score in the ninth off Robb Nen. 
</P>
<P>
                      *Diamondbacks 8, Brewers 2    	
</P>
<P>
	At Phoenix, Steve Finley hit a three-run homer and Damian Miller  
added a solo shot. 
</P>
<P>
                       *Athletics 9, White Sox 7    	
</P>
<P>
	At Tucson, Ariz., Mike Neill went 2-for-4 and drove in two runs,  
helping drop Chicago to 0-4. 
</P>
<P>
 *Phillies 7, Yankees 6    	
</P>
<P>
	At Tampa, Fla., Mike Lieberthal drove in the game-winning run  
with a seventh-inning double as Philadelphia beat the New York 
Yankees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
