<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mercedes-Benz Unveils New Coupe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- With demand for top-of-the-line luxury cars  
growing strong, Mercedes-Benz expects to double U.S. sales of its 
flagship CL coupe after the redesigned model goes on sale early 
next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Mercedes unveiled the sleek CL500 and CL600 to open the Geneva  
International Motor Show's press preview Monday night. With only 
about 8,000 of the big German coupes scheduled to be built a year, 
the CL is one of the world's most exclusive production cars. 
</P>
<P>
	And for good reason: Though prices haven't been set, the new CL  
is expected to sell for about the same as the current model, which 
ranges from $90,000 to $130,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a very exclusive clientele who have the means and desire  
to have such a product,'' said Mike Jackson, chief executive of 
Mercedes-Benz of North America. 
</P>
<P>
	Mercedes sold about 1,500 of the current CL in the United States  
last year and expects to sell about 3,000 of the new version, 
Jackson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The most expensive model, the CL600, features an all-new  
6-liter, V12 engine that produces 367 horsepower and automatically 
runs on six cylinders when all 12 aren't needed for acceleration. 
Mercedes officials say that results in about 20 percent less fuel 
consumption. 
</P>
<P>
	The interior is draped in top-quality leather and a choice of  
woods: walnut or chestnut. European customers who want to pay a 
premium can even order a center console with an unusual veneer of 
crushed rock on aluminum -- which has the look of polished granite. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside, the coupe has clean, flowing lines with an arched roof  
line and a low silhouette for a sportier look than its 
predecessor's. 
</P>
<P>
	The CL and S-Class sedan, with which the coupe shares its  
chassis and many parts, are the models Mercedes uses to display its 
latest high-tech features. 
</P>
<P>
	The coupe, for example, uses an unusual combination of  
lightweight body materials that resulted in significant weight 
savings. The hood, rear fenders, roof and other parts are made of 
aluminum, the front fenders and trunk lid are made of plastic and 
the inside of the doors are made of magnesium. 
</P>
<P>
	The different materials meant that conventional welds could not  
always be used to join the body panels. Mercedes instead had to use 
bonding technology developed from aviation, including flanging, 
riveting and use of high-tech adhesives, said Helmut Petri, 
production manager for the Mercedes-Benz passenger car division. 
</P>
<P>
	The coupe offers what the company calls ``active body control,''  
which uses high-pressure hydraulics and two high-performance 
microcomputers to reduce body roll and other unwanted movement 
common in large cars during hard cornering and braking. 
</P>
<P>
	The CL is scheduled to go on sale in Europe on Aug. 2, followed  
by the United States in the first quarter of 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 19:52:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stock Movements / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks rebounded Tuesday, powered by consumer  
electronics giant Sony Corp.'s announcement of a major corporate 
restructuring plan. The dollar fell against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei Stock Average rose 142.96 points, or 0.96 percent, to  
14,922.01 points by the close of the morning session. On Monday, 
the average closed down 114.95 points, or 0.77 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.06 yen in early trading, down 0.72 yen  
from late Monday in Tokyo and also below its level of 121.66 yen in 
New York. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, Sony was the rare bright spot, with  
declining issues outnumbering gainers as selling pressure from the 
unwinding of cross-shareholdings remains strong. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sony is pulling up the whole market,'' said Kazunori Jinnai,  
general manager of the equity department at Daiwa Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the market opened Tuesday, Sony unveiled a corporate  
reorganization plan to absorb Sony Music Entertainment, Sony 
Chemicals and Sony Precision Technology as wholly-owned units 
around next January. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading in the shares of the three units involved were  
temporarily suspended Tuesday morning as exchange officials 
verified the information. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section rose 4.60 points, or 0.40 percent, to 1,152.35 
points. The TOPIX closed up 1.03 points, or 0.09 percent, the day 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 132.08 yen, down  
from 132.09 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the yield on 10-year Japanese government bond rose to  
1.735 percent from Monday's finish of 1.625 percent, driving its 
price down to 100.51 yen from 101.41 yen. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
