<P>
	``I hate to see this once-proud franchise headed in the  
direction it's headed,'' said forward Chuck Person, a 12-year NBA 
veteran in his first season with the Hornets. ``I know that when I 
played in Indiana and even with San Antonio, when we came to 
Charlotte it was really a home court and the fans were really some 
of the best fans in the world just from being around Carolina 
basketball. And now to see how the fans respond when our product 
runs on the floor, it's definitely a different scenario.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Person and the rest of the Hornets who spoke to reporters after  
Sunday night's practice all voiced support for Cowens, voted one of 
the NBA's 50 greatest players, who found quick success in 
Charlotte. 
</P>
<P>
	Cowens, the only coach to lead the Hornets to consecutive 50-win  
seasons (54-28 in 1996-97, 51-31 in 1997-98), signed a three-year, 
$1.89 million contract in May 1996. The contract called for him to 
get $575,000 his first year, $625,000 last year and $675,000 this 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	When Cowens went to Shinn last season and said he felt he should  
receive the NBA average of about $1.3 million, the Hornets offered 
him a four-year, $5.2 million extension. But Shinn reportedly 
withdrew the offer in February 1998 because he didn't feel Cowens 
was being appreciative enough. 
</P>
<P>
	Cowens went public with complaints about his salary last month  
as the team struggled to get started during the lockout-shortened 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Coach just decided he had to do what's best for him,'' forward  
J.R. Reid said. ``For whatever reasons, Shinn and Coach didn't get 
along and couldn't work out the contract.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Silas said he tried to talk Cowens out of resigning.  
</P>
<P>
	``I told him there's just two more months left in the season,  
but his mind was made up,'' Silas said. ``At this point in the 
season, it's just shocking. That's the only word I can use.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Silas, who joined Cowens on NBA championship teams in Boston in  
1974 and 1976, was with five other teams during his 16-year playing 
career. He coached the San Diego Clippers from 1980-83, compiling a 
78-168 mark. Silas was an assistant with New Jersey, New York and 
Phoenix before joining the Hornets in 1997. He interviewed last 
summer for head-coaching vacancies in Chicago, Sacramento and 
Seattle, but wasn't offered any of the jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a difficult position to be in,'' he said as he left  
the training center Sunday night, five hours after Cowens quit. 
``But if you're called upon, then I think you have to accept it for 
the good of the organization, for the good of the team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Point guard B.J. Armstrong said the coaching change could give  
the team a fresh start. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we can rebound,'' Armstrong said. ``I think throughout  
all of this something positive will happen, because this is one 
less thing for us to be concerned about.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 06:05:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed generally higher  
Monday on the back of last week's record rally on Wall Street, but 
the key index slumped in Tokyo on worries over the rising Japanese 
yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average sank 114.95  
points, or 0.77 percent, to close at 14,779.05 points. On Friday, 
the average jumped 710.55 points, or 5.0 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices plunged in late trading, erasing a gain of more than 1  
percent in the major index, on worries that the rise in the yen 
could erode profits for Japanese companies. 
</P>
<P>
	In the morning, the Nikkei rose to as high as 15,116.10 -- its  
first time above 15,000 since Dec. 10 -- following a 5 percent rally 
on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	But the average fell back on fears a stronger currency could rob  
Japan's giant exporters of earnings by making their products more 
expensive and less competitive overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was quoted at 121.78 yen in late-afternoon trading,  
down 1.16 yen from late Friday in Tokyo and below its New York 
level of 122.80 yen late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar rose against the yen last week after Japan's central  
bank pushed interest rates lower by flooding the short-term money 
market with funds. 
</P>
<P>
	South Korean shares surged in reaction to Friday's sharp gains  
on Wall Street, where the Dow Jones industrial average rose 268.68 
points for a new closing high of 9,736.08. 
</P>
<P>
	The ratings upgrades of three South Korean banks by Moody's  
Investors Service Inc. late last week also boosted the Seoul Stock 
Exchange, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Korea Composite Stock Price Index rose 33.65 points, or 6.3  
percent, to 571.84. 
</P>
<P>
	Share prices in Hong Kong closed higher for the second  
consecutive session, helped by last week's record gains on Wall 
Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index, the market's key indicator of blue chips,  
rose 22.87 points, or 0.2 percent, closing at 10,263.99. On Friday, 
the index had surged 328.36 points, or 3.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hong Kong market was also boosted by news reports that  
Hongkong Telecom and Microsoft Corp. of the United states plan a 
venture that would let Hong Kong residents use their computers to 
quickly download movies and to play video games. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share prices closed higher for the second consecutive  
session after the government announced rising exports in the first 
two months of the year. The market's key Weighted Stock Price Index 
rose 10.23 points, or 0.15 percent, to 6,431.96. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed slightly higher. The  
The benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index rose 3.22 points, or 0.1 
percent, to 2,173.74. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine share prices closed higher, bouyed by cuts in  
key interest rates and Wall Street's huge gain on Friday. The 
Philippine Stock Exchange index of 30 selected companies rose 14.87 
points, or 0.7 percent, to 2,028.28. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: The Australian stock market closed higher, bolstered by  
a strong U.S. equities market. The All Ordinaries index closed at 
2,929.6, up 27.1 points, or 0.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares closed lower in thin trading. The key  
Composite Index fell 4.111 points, or 1.1 percent, to 384.568. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian shares closed mixed, with the key index  
rising slightly. The Composite Index, which tracks 100 blue-chip 
stocks, rose 3.04 points, or 0.5 percent, to 519.86. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed mixed. The benchmark Straits  
Times Index rose 2.18 points, or 0.1 percent, to 1,451.84. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: The key Thailand SET Index edged up 0.47 point to close  
at 336.68. 

</P>
</TEXT>
