	Terry got 48 first-team votes and 293 points, 83 more than  
Cleaves, who was on 19 first-team ballots. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleaves, 6-2, was a second-team choice last season and was named  
Big Ten player of the year by the league's coaches for the second 
straight year. He averaged 11.8 points and 7.2 assists as the 
Spartans won their second straight Big Ten regular-season title. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got to give a lot of credit to my teammates,'' he said.  
``If we wouldn't have won a championship, I wouldn't have earned 
this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The second team was senior center Evan Eschmeyer of  
Northwestern, who had one point less than Cleaves, Chris Porter of 
Auburn, Wally Szczerbiak of Miami of Ohio, Steve Francis of 
Maryland and Trajan Langdon of Duke, a third-team choice last 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	The third team was Tim James of Miami, Baron Davis of UCLA,  
Scoonie Penn of Ohio State, Quincy Lewis of Minnesota and Ron 
Artest of St. John's. 
</P>
<P>
	Terry was the only first-team choice who wasn't on the preseason  
All-America team. TCU's Lee Nailon was the fifth member of the 
preseason team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 13:21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Blackmun's Coffin Viewed at Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Harry A. Blackmun's body lay in repose Monday  
at the Supreme Court building where he spent close to a 
quarter-century influencing American law. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of family members, 88 former law clerks and seven of the  
court's current nine members gathered for a simple, solemn 
15-minute ceremony in the building's ornate Great Hall before 
members of the public began to file past the closed coffin. 
</P>
<P>
	Blackmun, author of the 1973 Roe vs. Wade decision that  
legalized abortion nationwide and more than 350 other Supreme Court 
rulings, died Thursday at 90. He had retired in 1994 after serving 
24 years on the nation's highest court. 
</P>
<P>
	He became history's fifth Supreme Court member to lie in repose,  
following Chief Justices Earl Warren and Warren Burger and fellow 
justices Thurgood Marshall and William Brennan. 
</P>
<P>
	As violinist Robert McDuffie played the hymn ``How Great Thou  
Art,'' Blackmun's widow, Dottie, listened silently from her 
wheelchair. The couple's five grandchildren, arms linked and softly 
weeping, stood to her left, the Blackmuns' three daughters to her 
right. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. William Lawrence, a Methodist minister, read from the  
Book of Psalms and led those present in prayers in memory of ``our 
brother Harry Andrew Blackmun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blackmun's casket, draped in the same 48-star flag that adorned  
his father's coffin, rested on the bier first used for Abraham 
Lincoln's funeral. Nearby, a 1978 portrait of the justice was on 
display. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist noted, ``with sadness,''  
Blackmun's death for the court's official record earlier in the 
day. 
</P>
<P>
	``He will be missed by his friends throughout the judiciary and  
the country,'' Rehnquist said. 
</P>
<P>
	Justices John Paul Stevens and Antonin Scalia, who were out of  
town, were the only current court members not present. The sole 
remaining retired justice, Byron R. White, attended, standing next 
to Mary Fowler Brennan, widow of the late Justice William Brennan. 
</P>
<P>
	Just three years ago, White was one of four retired justices but  
Brennan died in 1997 and Lewis Powell in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
