<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Strawberries Doing Well in Ga. / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) -- Georgia's strawberry crop is looking peachy,  
but farmers are worried about this year's peach crop -- only about 
one-third of which has begun to bloom. 
</P>
<P>
	About 750 cold hours have been logged this year. And that's less  
than what farmers like to see, said James Willis, a University of 
Georgia extension agent in Taylor County. Peach trees blossom best 
with 800 to 1,000 cold hours by this time of year. 
</P>
<P>
	The lack of cold has caused the state's peach farmers to begin  
experimenting with a technique that forces their trees to bloom. 
The technique, adopted by an agriculture specialist at Auburn 
University, uses a chemical called Dormex on the trees. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just been the wrong weather at all the wrong times this  
year,'' Willis said. ``We're holding our breath.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Willis said that despite the lack of cold, farmers are hoping a  
hard freeze does not make matters worse like it has in years past. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Georgia's peach crop totaled 70 million pounds, which  
was 44 percent of the 160 million pounds produced the year before. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales from Georgia's peach crop normally total about $35  
million. Middle Georgia farmers produce about 80 percent to 85 
percent of the crop while growers in southern Georgia produce the 
remainder. 
</P>
<P>
	But while the peach crop is still a work in progress, growers  
say the state's strawberry crop is looking promising. 
</P>
<P>
	William Bell owns self-pick strawberry farms in Ward, S.C., and  
North Augusta. He says the cold has done a little bit of damage but 
amid the greenery, he has strawberries as big as quarters. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just frustrating when you don't know what you're going to  
be up against from day to day,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bell say his biggest fear is another hard frost that will ruin  
his strawberry crops, which look so promising right now. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, it wasn't frost that damaged his crops but rain and  
rot. 
</P>
<P>
	``We saved between 80 and 95 percent of our crop, but we went to  
extreme measures to do it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	For now though, Bell says his strawberry crop, which spans four  
acres in Taylor County, looks like a winner. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've seemed to escape the cold,'' Willis said. ``We should  
be picking next week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BENTONVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- Fruit growers in Northwest Arkansas are  
keeping a nervous eye on their crops because mild weather has 
caused some blackberries, strawberries and blueberries to bloom 
early. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're on pins and needles,'' said Robert Seay, an agent of  
the Benton County Cooperative Extension Service. ``The jury will 
stay out until April 15th or 20th because that's when the last 
frost is expected. ... If you're a commercial grower, your whole 
season is determined in the next few weeks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Small plants are pretty well protected until their fruit-bud  
shoots begin to open, he said, and the recent warm weather has 
speeded the process. 
</P>
<P>
	Seay said the coldest temperature tolerated consistently by most  
small fruit plants is 26 degrees although growers usually can 
protect plants against one night of freezing weather. 
</P>
<P>
	``What it all boils down to is how far along the plant  
development has progressed,'' Seay said. 
</P>
<P>
	The strawberry crop in the area is most at risk, Seay said,  
adding that strawberries tend to bloom quickly, while blueberries 
and blackberries are heartier and slower to develop. 
</P>
<P>
	John R. Clark, assistant professor of horticulture at the  
University of Arkansas, said growers with sprinkler systems can 
protect strawberries by continually applying water to plants when 
the temperature dips into the 20s. 
</P>
<P>
	Clark said the freezing reaction gives off heat, which keeps the  
plants at around 30 degrees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
