<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CIT Buys Newcourt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LIVINGSTON, N.J. (AP) -- CIT Group Inc. acquired Newcourt Credit  
Group Inc. in a $4.2 billion stock deal Monday, creating the 
commercial financing industry's largest publicly held company. 
</P>
<P>
	CIT, based in Livingston, will exchange 0.92 of its shares for  
each share of Newcourt. The two companies combined have more than 
$50 billion in managed assets, $2.2 billion in revenues and more 
than $500 million in after-tax earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of CIT fell 56 1/4 cents to $30.18 3/4 in trading on the New  
York Stock Exchange. Shares of Newcourt rose 81 1/4 to $26.62 1/2, also 
on the NYSE. 
</P>
<P>
	CIT president and chief executive officer Albert R. Gamper Jr.  
will become chairman of the board and will remain CEO of the 
combined companies. Steven K. Hudson, Newcourt's president and CEO, 
will be The CIT Group's president and a member of the board of 
directors. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a bold and transforming transaction for CIT, combining  
our extensive management experience and `best in class' credit 
capabilities with Newcourt's innovative, entrepreneurial spirit,'' 
Gamper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hudson said the merger would streamline costs and diversify the  
businesses of Newcourt, based in Toronto and Parsippany, and 
Livingston-based CIT. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies expect to save $150 million through the merger, he  
said. CIT also hopes to capitalize on Newcourt clients like Dell 
and Lucent and expand its marketing presence in North America and 
Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Both companies' boards unanimously approved the merger, which is  
expected to be completed during the third quarter of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	CIT shareholders will own 54 percent of the combined company  
after the merger -- with CIT's largest shareholder, the Dai-Ichi 
Kangyo Bank, owning 24 percent of the company. Newcourt 
shareholders will own 46 percent. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
