<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Army Museums Eyed for Penn., D.C. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Pennsylvania and the Washington, D.C., area  
will be home to two new Army museums, including one that will 
chronicle the American soldier from the pre-Revolutionary period to 
the present, Army officials said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Army Secretary Louis Caldera did not elaborate on what  
collections or artifacts would go to each location. 
</P>
<P>
	But an Army spokesman said the museum in Carlisle, Pa., will not  
be the comprehensive national museum that has been in the works 
since 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	That leaves Washington as the location for the national museum,  
although Lt. Col. Bill Wheelehan said the Army is not ready to make 
a formal announcement. But he said: ``To have an Army museum, one 
that represents the entire Army, if you put it in any one state, 
you slight the other states.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pennsylvania had lobbied long and hard to build it in Carlisle,  
near the Carlisle Barracks, the second-oldest U.S. Army post behind 
West Point, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	One site mentioned for the museum is vacant acreage at the  
Washington Navy Yard complex. Five dozen sites across the nation 
have been considered for the national Army museum, which would be 
built using private donations. 
</P>
<P>
	Army officials have envisioned a museum to house about 500,000  
artifacts, such as uniforms, insignia, muskets, cannon, tanks, 
books, photographs and paintings dating to the late 18th century. 
Some artifacts are on display at the Pentagon, but most are stored 
in warehouses in Alabama. 
</P>
<P>
	Carlisle would join 55 specialized Army museums around the  
nation that focus on specific units, such as infantry or artillery. 
Other military branches have comprehensive national museums similar 
to the one the Army plans to build. 
</P>
<P>
	Pennsylvania officials initially proposed an $80 million,  
300,000-square-foot complex to house the national museum. They 
tempered their praise for Carlisle's selection as the site of a 
museum of yet-to-be-determined scope. 
</P>
<P>
	``The most important thing is it must be first-rate,'' Rep.  
William Goodling, R-Pa., said. ``It has to have the equipment, the 
uniforms and the history and the ammunition and everything from 
every era.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Army criteria developed in early stages would locate the  
national museum in the Washington area. Army officials have been 
reluctant to change that. 
</P>
<P>
	To lure the Army to Carlisle, Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge  
offered $5 million in road improvements and other state funding. 
Carlisle's Cumberland County offered to donate 54 acres of farmland 
near the old barracks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Carlisle post was where President George Washington reviewed  
troops as they left to quell the Whiskey Rebellion in western 
Pennsylvania in 1794. It was set ablaze by Confederates during the 
Civil War. The barracks now house the Army War College and the 
Military History Institute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
