<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Weeps at Sweepstakes Hearing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a Senate hearing designed to present horror  
stories about sweepstakes promotions, a Florida man began sobbing 
today as he testified about spending money he had saved to send his 
daughter to law school. 
</P>
<P>
	Eustace A. Hall, of Brandon, Fla., became so emotional that the  
daughter, Angela, had to finish reading his statement. Despite the 
financial problems encountered by her father, she completed her 
studies and is now an attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall was among six witnesses who lashed out at sweepstakes  
companies at a hearing of the Senate Permanent Subcommittee on 
Investigations. The chairman, Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine, has 
sponsored legislation that would impose the first national 
regulation of sweepstakes mailings and levy hefty fines for 
deceptive practices. They legislation also would prevent companies 
from telling recipients they won something when they haven't, and 
from using the smallest print to list the almost insurmountable 
odds of winning a major prize. 
</P>
<P>
	``I estimate I have spent $15,000 to $20,000 from 1992 to the  
present on sweepstake purchases,'' Hall's statement, read by his 
daughter, said. ``They always led me to believe that I had to 
purchase products to win. After all the time and money I spent I 
have nothing to show for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before a hushed hearing room filled with lobbyists and  
representatives of the major sweepstakes companies, Hall, with a 
box of tissues in front of him, broke down after telling the 
hearing that he entered the contests to provide his daughter ``with 
more financial assistance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The sweepstakes industry representatives, who have been accused  
by numerous state attorneys general of preying on the elderly, will 
testify Tuesday. The companies have not yet taken a position on the 
legislation, but have hired some of Washington's major lobbying 
firms to help shape the legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to Hall, five other witnesses recounted the  
experiences of their parents and in-laws, who also spent much of 
their life savings to buy magazines and other products in pursuit 
of prizes that they thought they had won. 
</P>
<P>
	Patti McElligott, of Tyler, Texas, handed Collins and Sen. Carl  
Levin, D-Mich. a ``golden horseshoe watch'' that was purchased in a 
sweepstakes promotion for $20.29. ``I wouldn't give you a dime for 
it,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Levin said he would keep it to show to the industry witnesses on  
Tuesday, joking, ``This won't violate our gift rule'' that only 
allows senators to keep gifts worth less than $50. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990308.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 13:26:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US, EU Face Off on Banana Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- An irate European Union appealed today to members  
of the World Trade Organization to denounce U.S. sanctions in the 
trans-Atlantic banana trade row, but found many countries telling 
both trade giants to stop tying up the world agenda. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington insists it has the right to take the step on  
sanctions because of EU reluctance to change import policies that 
American banana sellers say squeeze them out of the European 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	But many trade diplomats complain that the dispute is blocking  
the WTO from doing anything else. Some have expressed fears that 
the maneuvering by the WTO's two most powerful members threatens to 
wreck the world's rules-based trading system. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were a lot of countries which said we need to get this  
dispute settled,'' said WTO spokesman Keith Rockwell during a break 
in a closed-door gathering of the entire WTO membership this 
morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Rockwell quoted Canadian Ambassador John Weekes as saying the  
world was ``mesmerized'' by the dispute even though EU-US trade 
amounts to only 5 percent of the global market. The WTO should be 
focusing on the other 95 percent, Weekes added. 
</P>
<P>
	Roderick Abbott, head of the EU trade delegation in Geneva,  
claimed to have broad support against U.S. actions. ``There is a 
very wide feeling that they have done the wrong thing,'' Abbott 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the request of the EU, the WTO summoned all its 134 member  
countries to the meeting of the general council, its top 
decision-making body, to discuss U.S. sanctions. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States accuses the 15-member European Union of  
failing to carry out WTO rulings against its selective banana 
import policy, which the United States claims favors producers in 
former European colonies at the expense of U.S.-owned producers 
with huge plantations in Central and South America. 
</P>
<P>
	It has asked the WTO to approve Washington's proposal of 100  
percent tariffs on $520 million worth of European goods, which aim 
to equal the lost sales claimed by U.S.-owned banana companies. 
</P>
<P>
	After the WTO last week delayed approving the U.S. tariffs, the  
Clinton administration notified U.S. importers that they must start 
setting aside funds to cover the tariffs pending a WTO decision. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. requirement means that Washington is in effect  
implementing the sanctions without first getting WTO approval, said 
Abbott. 
</P>
<P>
	The tariffs would apply to a wide range of European products  
chosen by the Clinton administration to penalize particularly those 
EU countries that supported the banana policies. Products could 
include handbags, coffee makers and cashmere sweaters. 
</P>
<P>
	Denmark and the Netherlands are excluded, but all other  
countries are affected. Britain, one of the hardest-hit, has been 
particularly outspoken in its protest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
