<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Diet Guidelines May Add Food Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Food safety advice should be included in the  
federal dietary guidelines, because keeping people healthy means 
teaching them to protect themselves from food-borne illnesses, a 
Clinton administration official said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe the time has come to include food safety in the  
guidelines,'' Catherine Woteki, the Agriculture Department's 
undersecretary for food safety, said Monday. ``Government has an 
obligation to help people protect themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Woteki's comments came during a meeting of an advisory committee  
reviewing the ``Dietary Guidelines for Americans.'' The guidelines 
are issued every five years by USDA and the Department of Health 
and Human Services and form the cornerstone of federal nutrition 
policy. They were last published in 1995, and the advisory panel's 
report later this year will contain revisions for 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The guidelines advise choosing a diet with plenty of grain  
products, vegetables and fruits, and also low in fat, saturated fat 
and cholesterol. 
</P>
<P>
	The guidelines have never included food safety information, but  
times and dangers have changed since the early 1980s when the 
guidelines began, Woteki said. She declined to recommend particular 
guidelines, but said they might include advice on appropriate 
temperatures to store food or proper food handling. 
</P>
<P>
	``Food safety is a critical factor in any discussion about diet  
and long-term health,'' she said. ``New pathogens have emerged just 
in the last decade.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the last few months, numerous food products have been  
recalled because of contamination with the bacteria Listera 
monocytogenes. A large recall in December by the Bil Mar Foods 
plant in Zeeland, Mich., has been linked to an outbreak that has 
resulted in at least 14 deaths, six miscarriages and 97 illnesses 
across the country. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration's stand has support among some nutritionists,  
including the American Dietetic Association. ``Given the scope of 
consumer concerns about food safety, ADA urges the committee to 
consider adding food safety messages in an informative but not 
alarming way,'' Kathryn M. Carroll, senior nutrition scientist for 
the ADA, told the panel. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Cutberto Garza, chairman of the advisory panel, said the  
committee would take the request ``very seriously.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Food-borne illnesses cost society between $6.6 billion and $37  
billion annually in medical costs and lost productivity, Woteki 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are food-borne illnesses associated with virtually every  
category of food,'' she said, noting that while meat and poultry 
are the largest contributors, other foods also carry pathogens. 
</P>
<P>
	``Education is a very important component in this strategy.  
Consumers need to know what they can do to protect themselves.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
