<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cooke Widow Loses Court Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The wife of the late Washington Redskins owner  
Jack Kent Cooke lost a Supreme Court appeal today in her effort to 
avoid being deported over a 1986 guilty plea to a drug conspiracy 
charge. 
</P>
<P>
	The court, without comment, turned away Marlena Ramallo Cooke's  
argument that a federal judge can enforce a government promise not 
to deport her in exchange for help in prosecuting drug traffickers. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruling in an unrelated case last month, the Supreme Court  
limited aliens' access to federal courts in immigration cases. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite today's setback, it does not appear that Mrs. Cooke's  
deportation is imminent. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Cooke, a Bolivian native, served 5 1/2 months in prison on her  
guilty plea to conspiracy to import cocaine. In 1988, the 
Immigration and Naturalization Service issued a deportation order 
but, under an agreement with Mrs. Cooke, did not immediately seek 
to enforce it. 
</P>
<P>
	The government says it agreed to let her stay in the country  
while she was cooperating with prosecutors. 
</P>
<P>
	She contended the government promised to let her stay  
permanently. Her lawyers said she aided in about 30 convictions, 
and that returning her to Bolivia would put her life in danger. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, Mrs. Cooke filed a lawsuit seeking to overturn the  
deportation order and force the government to honor its agreement 
not to deport her. A federal judge in Washington ruled that the 
government was bound by the agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia  
reversed that ruling in 1997, saying a 1996 law stripped federal 
trial courts of their authority to hear such claims stemming from 
deportation orders. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal acted on today, Mrs. Cooke's lawyers said the  
appeals court's ruling means that aliens who cooperate in 
international drug investigations can be ``deported into the arms 
of those against whom they have testified.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Government lawyers said the appeals court was correct in  
throwing out the judge's order. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Ramallo vs. Reno, 97-526.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
