<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                          *J. Leland Atwood    	
</P>
<P>
	COSTA MESA, Calif. (AP) -- J. Leland ``Lee'' Atwood, a key figure  
in the aerospace industry for more than 50 years while president 
and chief executive officer of Rockwell International Corp., died 
Friday. He was 94. 
</P>
<P>
	Atwood's work led to the development of the P-51 Mustang  
fighter, one of the main aircraft used in World War II. The fighter 
was developed for Rockwell's predecessor company, North American 
Aviation, now part of the Boeing Co. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1934, he began work at North American Aviation, becoming  
chief engineer and vice president. He was elected president in 
1948, gaining the title of CEO in 1960 and then chairman of the 
company two years later. 
</P>
<P>
	He received various aviation awards, including a Presidential  
Certificate of Merit in 1948 for his contributions to the war 
effort. In 1995, Italy gave him its Commander of Merit declaration 
for his contributions to the aerospace industry. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Mary Dalton    	
</P>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Mary Dalton, who with her husband donated  
200 pieces of art to the Mint Museum of Charlotte, died Thursday. 
She was 94. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dalton and her late husband built a multimillion-dollar art  
and rare book collection and gave most of it away to institutions 
around the Southeast. 
</P>
<P>
	Harry Dalton, a successful banker and textile executive, died in  
1990 at age 95. 
</P>
<P>
	Museums and universities around the Southeast bear their  
generosity. There's the Dalton Rare Book room at Duke University, 
where Harry Dalton graduated, and the Dalton Art Gallery at Agnes 
Scott College in Georgia, where Mrs. Dalton attended. 
</P>
<P>
	Voters in 1982 rejected a bond issue to pay for an expansion of  
the Mint Museum, prompting the Daltons to offer much of their 
collection to the museum if a wing could be built to house it. 
Voters passed a bond issue and the museum raised money to fund the 
wing. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Antonio Houaiss    	
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Antonio Houaiss, Brazil's former  
minister of culture, died Sunday from multiple organ failure. He 
was 83. 
</P>
<P>
	Houaiss became minister of culture in 1992 under former  
President Itamar Franco. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to books about politics and poetry, he also wrote  
one on the pleasure of drinking beer. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, Houaiss was made president of the prestigious Brazilian  
Academy of Literature. He left the post after six months because of 
ill health but remained an academy member. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Leopold Just    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Leopold Just, a Latvian-born engineer who built  
a reputation worldwide for constructing highways and New York City 
bridges, died Feb. 25. He was 95. 
</P>
<P>
	Just helped design the George Washington Bridge, linking New  
York and New Jersey, and the Verrazano-Narrows Bridge, connecting 
Staten Island and Brooklyn. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1931, he joined what was then called the Port of New York  
Authority and helped design the Lincoln Tunnel. He left in 1938 to 
build tunnels for the Pennsylvania Turnpike Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Returning to New York in 1940 he became a structural engineer  
with the famed Swiss-born engineer, Othmar Ammann. 
</P>
<P>
	Just, who became a chief engineer in 1952, had a key part in  
designing the Walt Whitman Bridge in Philadelphia and the Throgs 
Neck Bridge, connecting the Bronx and Queens. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Stanley Kubrick    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Stanley Kubrick, a visionary craftsman whose films  
-- including ``Dr. Strangelove,'' ``A Clockwork Orange'' and ``2001: 
A Space Odyssey'' -- often reflected a violent and despairing view 
of life, died Sunday. He was 70. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time of his death, the publicity-shy Kubrick was  
preparing for the midyear release of ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' his first 
film in 12 years. Starring Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman, the film 
had been shrouded in the secrecy that attended all of Kubrick's 
later movies. 
</P>
<P>
	Kubrick chronicled the effects of war in ``Fear and Desire''  
(1953); ``Paths of Glory'' (1957) and Full Metal Jacket (1987); the 
suicidal logic of the Cold War in the blackly comic ``Dr. 
Strangelove: or, How I Learned To Stop Worrying and Love the Bomb'' 
(1964); and sexual obsession in ``Lolita'' (1962). 
</P>
<P>
	For ``2001: A Space Odyssey,'' Kubrick got the second of his  
four Academy Award nominations for best director. The other 
nominations were for ``Dr. Strangelove,'' ``Barry Lyndon,'' and ``A 
Clockwork Orange,'' which unlike ``2001'' were also nominated for 
best picture. 
</P>
<P>
	Other Kubrick films include ``Spartacus'' and ``The Shining.''  

</P>
<P>
                        *William L. McGonagle    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Retired Navy Capt. William L. McGonagle, who  
received the Medal of Honor for heroism as skipper of the USS 
Liberty when Israel unleashed a deadly attack on the 
intelligence-gathering ship in 1967, died Wednesday. He was 73. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty-four crewmen were killed and 171 were wounded when the  
Liberty was attacked by Israeli air force planes and torpedo boats 
in international waters north of Sinai during the Six Day War 
between Israel and its Arab neighbors. 
</P>
<P>
	The ship was bombed with napalm, torpedoed and shelled.  
</P>
<P>
	The attack, blamed on a mistaken identification of the Liberty  
as an Egyptian ship, remains one of the most controversial events 
in U.S.-Israeli relations and led to allegations of a cover-up by 
the governments. 
</P>
<P>
	McGonagle, who was severely wounded but stayed in command on the  
bridge through the battle and for many hours afterward, broke his 
silence years later and joined former shipmates in demanding the 
two governments release all details of the attack. 
</P>
<P>
	Israel apologized to the United States but claimed there had  
been a misidentification and that the ship's markings were 
inadequate. Israel paid more than $12 million in compensation. 

</P>
<P>
 *Sheik Isa bin Salman Al Khalifa,    	
</P>
<P>
	MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) -- Sheik Isa bin Salman Al Khalifa, the emir  
of Bahrain, died Saturday of a heart attack shortly after a meeting 
with Defense Secretary William Cohen. He was 65. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheik Isa ruled Bahrain for 38 years. He is the second  
pro-Western Arab leader to die in two months, following the death 
of Jordan's King Hussein in February. 
</P>
<P>
	Bahrain, a nation of 35 islands covering 260 square miles, is  
home to the biggest U.S. naval presence in the region. Sheik Isa 
allowed British and American warplanes to use Bahraini airfields 
during the 1991 Persian Gulf War. Afterward, he traveled to 
Washington and signed a security pact with the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	About 2,500 Americans live and work in Bahrain, including about  
1,000 in the military. U.S. warships often dock in Bahrain, home to 
the 5th Fleet, so sailors can take shore leave. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheik Isa had offered the facilities to the Navy, discreetly at  
first fearing popular resentment against a foreign military 
presence. During and after the 1990-91 Gulf crisis, he became more 
open about the U.S. presence. 
</P>
<P>
	His son, Sheik Hamad bin Isa Al Khalifa, assumed the throne.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
