<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Times Mirror Co. Exec Junck Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Mary E. Junck, executive vice president of  
Times Mirror Co. and president of its Eastern Newspapers division, 
is resigning, the company said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Junck, 51, joined Times Mirror as publisher and CEO of The  
(Baltimore) Sun in 1993. She became a senior vice president and 
president of Times Mirror Eastern Newspapers in 1997 and was 
promoted to executive vice president of Times Mirror Co. in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``She has achieved a remarkable record of success, first as  
publisher of The Sun where she put the paper on a strong, 
profitable path, and more recently, as president of our Eastern 
Newspapers where the group reached all-time highs on key financial 
measures,'' said Mark H. Willes, Times Mirror chairman, president 
and chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll miss working with my colleagues throughout Times  
Mirror,'' Ms. Junck said, ``but it is time for me to move on. I 
look forward to new career challenges, be they in publishing or in 
a business yet unexplored.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Senior Vice Presidents Raymond A. Jansen and Efrem Zimbalist III  
have been promoted to executive vice presidents and will share her 
responsibilities, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	Their new duties include oversight of The Sun; Greenwich (Conn.)  
Time; The Hartford Courant; The Morning Call of Allentown, Pa.; 
Newsday and The Advocate of Stamford, Conn.; as well as Times 
Mirror Magazines and StayWell. 
</P>
<P>
	Jansen, 58, is publisher, president and CEO of Newsday.  
Zimbalist, 50, is president and CEO of Times Mirror Magazines. 

</P>
</TEXT>
