<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pittsburgh Names Basketball Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Ben Howland was introduced as Pitt's  
basketball coach today, saying his philosophy will be the same in 
the Big East as it was in the Big Sky: recruit players who can 
shoot. 
</P>
<P>
	Howland leaves Northern Arizona to replace Ralph Willard, who  
resigned after never taking Pitt to the NCAA tournament in five 
seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Willard's last season was marred by player suspensions, arrests  
and practice altercations that left the Panthers with only seven 
scholarship players for their Big East tournament loss to Rutgers 
last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Howland, 41, has been coach at Northern Arizona for five years.  
His teams won two Big Sky regular season titles and went to the 
NCAA Tournament last year, losing 65-62 to Cincinnati in the first 
round. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lumberjacks (21-8) lost to Weber State in the finals of this  
year's Big Sky tournament and did not get a tournament bid, either 
from the NCAA or NIT. 
</P>
<P>
	``As much as I wanted to win that game Saturday, I am glad to be  
here today,'' Howland said. 
</P>
<P>
	He pointed to other successful coaches who have left the Big Sky  
Conference, including Chicago Bulls coach Tim Floyd, Stanford coach 
Mike Montgomery and former Michigan State coach Jud Heathcote. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lumberjacks led the nation in 3-point shooting in each of  
the last two seasons and could lead NCAA Division I in field-goal 
and 3-point shooting this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe in recruiting shooters. You can't teach kids to  
shoot once they are freshmen or sophomores in college,'' he said. 
``We also need to recruit some size. We need some athletes 6-10, 
240, 250.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pitt had a small team this year with 6-foot-9 Isaac Hawkins  
starting at center. 
</P>
<P>
	Willard finished with a 63-77 record, including 14-16 this  
season. The Panthers got into the Top 25 after early upsets of 
Xavier and Kentucky in the Puerto Rico Shootout but got into 
trouble during their Big East schedule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
