<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton Arrives in El Salvador  
</P>
<P>
	POSOLTEGA, Nicaragua (AP) -- Arriving in San Salvador Monday  
night, President Clinton declared that all Americans have an 
interest in rebuilding Central America. Clinton opened a four-day 
trip to hurricane-ravaged Nicaragua, El Salvador, Honduras and 
Guatemala promising an unprecedented amount of reconstruction aid -- 
$956 million. Across Central America, more than 9,000 people died -- 
more than 5,000 in Honduras alone. Thousands more remain missing. 
Crops and bridges were destroyed and the damage toll ranges up to 
$10 billion in the already impoverished countries. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Kosovo Goals Advance Slightly  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The administration's goal of winning support  
of Kosovo Albanians for a six-nation peace plan advanced Monday as 
major rebel military leaders gave their blessing, the State 
Department announced. But a hard-line commander of the Kosovo 
Liberation Army defiantly insisted the KLA will not give up its 
arms -- an important requirement of the peace plan. But even as the 
tense diplomatic moves continued, international monitors reported 
new clashes Monday at the village of Kacanik near Kosovo's border 
with Macedonia. 

</P>
<P>
	Scientist Fired in China Nuke Probe  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A computer scientist was fired Monday by the  
Department of Energy in connection with an investigation about 
alleged disclosure of sensitive nuclear missile technology to China 
in the 1980s. The Associated Press learned the scientist is Wen Ho 
Lee, a native of Taiwan. He had worked for years at the Los Alamos 
National Laboratory in New Mexico. 

</P>
<P>
	Baseball Mourns DiMaggio's Death  
</P>
<P>
	HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) -- Joe DiMaggio died at home Monday at the  
age of 84 following a five-month battle with lung cancer. Said 
former Dodgers manager Tom Lasorda: ``If you said to God, `Create 
someone who was what a baseball player should be,' God would have 
created Joe DiMaggio. And he did.'' DiMaggio played for the New 
York Yankees for 13 years through 1951, playing for nine World 
Series champions despite missing three years because of service in 
World War II. He batted .325 lifetime, won three AL Most Valuable 
Player awards and entered the Hall of Fame in 1955. 

</P>
<P>
	Sony To Cut 17,000 Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The Sony Group on Tuesday announced it will cut  
17,000 jobs over the next four years as part of a sweeping 
restructuring. The cuts, to be completed by March 2003, represent 
about 10 percent of the Sony group's total work force, said company 
President Nobuyuki Idei. Sony will also eliminate 15 manufacturing 
facilities around the world, leaving it with 55 by 2003. The cuts, 
intended to reduce costs and improve profitability, are part of 
broader changes in the way Sony will run its operations. 

</P>
<P>
	France Submits Terrorist Bill to UN  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- France submitted a treaty proposal to the  
U.N. General Assembly Monday that would make the financing of 
terrorist activities a crime. The convention would require 
signatories to adopt laws punishing any individual who knowingly 
finances a person or organization involved in terrorist acts and 
imposing penalties ``which take into account the grave nature of 
those offenses.'' It also calls for the adoption of measures to 
prevent the financing of terrorism. 

</P>
<P>
	William Wrigley Dead at 66  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- William Wrigley, the president and chief  
executive officer of the chewing gum company founded by his 
grandfather, died Monday of complications associated with 
pneumonia. He was 66. Wrigley was listed as the 58th richest 
American last year in a survey by Forbes magazine, with an 
estimated wealth of $2.7 billion. He became director and vice 
president of the company in 1960 and succeeded his father as 
president in 1961. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Higher at Midday  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks rebounded Tuesday, powered by consumer  
electronics giant Sony Corp.'s announcement of a major corporate 
restructuring plan. The Nikkei Stock Average rose 142.96 points to 
14,922.01 points by the close of the morning session. In New York, 
the Dow fell 8.47 points to close at 9,727.61. 

</P>
<P>
	Blaylock's Steal Seals Hawks' Win  
</P>
<P>
	ORLANDO (AP) -- Mookie Blaylock's steal of an inbounds pass with  
5.4 seconds remaining helped Atlanta hang on to defeat Orlando 
114-110, snapping the Magic's 10-game home winning streak. Steve 
Smith led Atlanta with 24 points and Dikembe Mutombo added 18 
points and 17 rebounds. Nick Anderson had 34 points on 11-of-17 
shooting as six Magic players scored in double figures. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  

</P>
</TEXT>
