<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Death Penalty Sought for Charles Ng </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) -- Prosecutors asked jurors Monday to give  
the death penalty to a convicted torture killer as the penalty 
phase began in one of the state's longest and costliest homicide 
cases. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury must choose between capital punishment or life in  
prison without chance of parole for Charles Ng, 38. 
</P>
<P>
	He was convicted Feb. 24 of 11 murder counts in a spree of  
kidnapping, bondage and sadism in Northern California in the 1980s. 
The jury reached an impasse on a 12th count. 
</P>
<P>
	Calaveras County District Attorney Peter Smith called witnesses  
to testify about Ng's propensity to violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Sean Doyle, a former security officer for the Hudson Bay Co.  
department store, testified how a shoplifting incident led to Ng's 
arrest in Calgary, Alberta, about a month after Lake's suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	Doyle said Ng bit him on the wrist and shot him in the hand  
during a scuffle after Doyle spotted him stealing canned fish and a 
two-liter bottle of soda. Doyle said he never regained use of his 
middle finger. 
</P>
<P>
	Other witnesses talked about the pain of losing their relatives  
in the killing spree. 
</P>
<P>
	``To be honest with you, I've put it out of my mind all these  
years because it's hard to even talk about it,'' said Robert 
McCourt of Philadelphia, the brother of a victim, Clifford 
Peranteau. ``It's not like he got hit by a car or something.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ng fought extradition for six years in Canada, and his trial was  
moved to Orange County in 1994 because of heavy news coverage in 
Northern California. 
</P>
</TEXT>
