<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colo. Student Wins Science Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A 14-year-old who studied the elusive  
subatomic particles called neutrinos won the prestigious Intel 
Science Talent Search on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Natalia Toro, a senior at Fairview High School in Boulder,  
Colo., becomes the youngest winner in the history of the 
58-year-old event. She receives a $50,000 college scholarship. 
</P>
<P>
	Miss Toro, who began taking college courses in the sixth grade,  
did her winning research last summer as part of a program at 
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, which she hopes to attend. 
</P>
<P>
	She studied neutrinos, elementary particles that have no  
electrical charge and are thought to have no mass when at rest, but 
which move at the speed of light. 
</P>
<P>
	In announcing the winner, the judges said Miss Toro's work may  
help explain mysterious shortages of neutrino counts. 
</P>
<P>
	Recent studies in Japan suggested that neutrinos might oscillate  
between a state that a neutrino detector can see and one that it 
cannot. Miss Toro developed an equation to predict theoretical 
neutrino counts. When compared with the data from Japan, her work 
strongly supports the oscillation theory, the judges reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The Intel Science Talent Search, formerly known as the  
Westinghouse Science Search, is now sponsored by the Intel Corp. 
and Science Service, a nonprofit Washington organization that 
publishes Science News. 
</P>
<P>
	Second place, and a $40,000 scholarship, went to David Moore,  
18, of Montgomery Blair High School in Silver Spring, Md., who 
determined the electrical properties of a newly proposed design for 
molecular electronic switches. 
</P>
<P>
	And Keith Winstein, 17, of the Illinois Science and Mathematics  
Academy in Aurora, Ill., was third. He won a $30,000 scholarship 
for work on a method to embed information in computerized data 
without making any perceptible change in the original material. 
</P>
<P>
	Rounding out the top 10 winners were:  
</P>
<P>
	--Carol Ann Fassbinder, 18, Valley Community High School, Elgin,  
Iowa, $20,000 scholarship. 
</P>
<P>
	--Rio Gabriel Benin, 17, a home-schooled senior from Berkeley,  
Calif., $20,000 scholarship. 
</P>
<P>
	--Lisa Beth Schwartz, 17, of Roslyn High School in Roslyn  
Heights, N.Y., $20,000 scholarship. 
</P>
<P>
	--Scott Alexander Fruhan, 17, of Roxbury Latin School, West  
Roxbury, Mass., $15,000 scholarship. 
</P>
<P>
	--Kurt Elliot Mitman, 16, Thomas Jefferson High School for  
Science and Technology, Fairfax County, Va., $15,000 scholarship. 
</P>
<P>
	--Diana Barnard Townsend-Butterworth, 17, of Chapin School in New  
York City, $15,000 scholarship. 
</P>
<P>
	--Alexander David Wissner-Gross, 17, of Great Neck High School,  
Great Neck, N.Y., $15,000 scholarship. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the first and second alternates, in case any of the  
top 10 cannot accept their scholarship, were Cullen Blake, 17, of 
Bethlehem Central High School in Delmar, N.Y., and David Harden, 
17, of South Miami Senior High School in Miami, Fla. 

</P>
</TEXT>
