<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baseball Hall of Fame Lowers Flag </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. (AP) -- The Baseball Hall of Fame lowered its  
official flag in tribute to Joe DiMaggio on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The baseball shrine, where DiMaggio last appeared eight years  
ago, also placed a wreath at the Yankee Clipper's plaque in the 
inductees' room. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reverence for him was unsurpassed,'' Hall of Fame  
spokesman Jeff Idelson said. 
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio, who died Monday at 84 in his home in Hollywood, Fla.,  
attended the 1991 induction ceremonies in Cooperstown, marking the 
50th anniversary of his 56-game hitting streak and Ted Williams' 
.400 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Wherever DiMaggio and Williams went that weekend, people would  
stop and applaud, paying tribute to a pair of baseball greats 
linked forever by that one magical season. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though he had been ailing for several months, DiMaggio's  
death stunned visitors as word of his death spread around the Hall 
of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most were older folks who were coming with their kids or  
grandkids anyway,'' Idelson said. ``Upon learning of his death, you 
could see a certain sadness in their faces.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio was inducted into the Hall in 1955. His memorabilia on  
display includes his Yankee Stadium locker, which was later used by 
Mickey Mantle. 
</P>
<P>
	Hanging in the locker are DiMaggio's home uniform and cap from  
the 1951 season, his last, along with some gloves and bats from his 
1939 MVP season. 
</P>
<P>
	There's also the pen he used to sign baseball's first $100,000  
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Idelson said film programs featuring DiMaggio will be played in  
the museum's movie theater all month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
